{"title_page": "Irell & Manella", "text_new": "{{Infobox law firm\n| name = Irell & Manella\n| logo = [[File:Irell & Manella.png|frameless|Irell & Manella]]\n| headquarters = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], United States\n| foundation = 1941\n| num_offices = 2\n| num_attorneys = 90+\n| practice_areas = General practice, [[intellectual property|IP]] litigation\n| revenue = {{gain}} 253 million [[United States dollar|USD]] (2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jdjournal.com/2010/02/16/profits-and-revenue-up-at-irell-manella/ |title=Irell & Manella, Revenue Increase, Profits Per Partner Increase |publisher=JD Journal |date=2010-02-16 |accessdate=2013-11-07}}</ref>\n| date_founded = 1941\n| company_type = [[LLP]]\n| homepage = {{url|Irell.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Irell & Manella LLP''' is an American [[law firm]] founded in 1941 by lawyers Lawrence E. Irell (1912\u20132000) and Arthur Manella (1917\u20131997).<ref>https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2000-jun-27-me-45311-story.html</ref><ref>https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1997-01-17-mn-19495-story.html</ref>  It has approximately 94 lawyers (down from a high of over 220), and placed 158th on The American Lawyer's 2019 Am Law 200 ranking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.com/law-firm-profile/?id=155&slreturn=20200005134043|title=Irell & Manella LLP|last=|first=|date=|website=Law.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-16}}</ref> It has two locations in [[Southern California]]: [[Century City]] and [[Newport Beach]]. Irell specializes in [[intellectual property]] [[litigation]] and general business litigation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abovethelaw.com/2012/01/associate-bonus-watch-irell-whacks-cravath-again/ |title=Associate Bonus Watch: Irell Whacks Cravath, Again \u00ab Above the Law: A Legal Web Site \u2013 News, Commentary, and Opinions on Law Firms, Lawyers, Law Schools, Law Suits, Judges and Courts + Career Resources |publisher=Abovethelaw.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-15}}</ref>\n\n[[Morgan Chu]], one of Irell's attorneys, is the brother of former United States [[Secretary of Energy]] [[Steven Chu]].<ref name=\"Office of the President-Elect\">{{cite news| title=Chu to be Energy Secretary| url=http://change.gov/newsroom/entry/president_elect_barack_obama_announces_key_members_of_energy_and_environmen/| date=2008-12-15| accessdate=2008-12-16| publisher=[[change.gov]]| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140813143325/http://change.gov/newsroom/entry/president_elect_barack_obama_announces_key_members_of_energy_and_environmen/| archivedate=2014-08-13}}</ref><ref name=\"Irell&Manella\">{{cite web|publisher=Irell & Manella LLP|url=http://www.irell.com/professionals-22.html|title=Morgan Chu|accessdate=2008-12-16}}</ref> The managing partner of the firm is Ellisen Turner. Michael Ermer is the managing partner of the Newport Beach office. Jane Shay Wald is the head of the trademark practice group, and David Siegel is the head of the securities litigation practice group. Former federal judge [[Layn R. Phillips]] was a longtime partner at the firm.   Under Secretary of Commerce for Intellectual Property and Director of the United States Patent and Trademark Office [[Andrei Iancu]] was also a longtime partner at the firm.\n\nIn 2020, Irell & Manella represented Labrador Diagnostics (a subsidiary of Fortress Investment Group, itself owned by the firm [[SoftBank]]) in an infringement lawsuit against bioFire (a subsidiary of [[BioM\u00e9rieux]]), claiming the firm infringed patents purchased from the disgraced company [[Theranos]].  This legal action attracted heavy criticism due both to the origin of the patents, as well as bioFire responding by saying they were working on COVID-19 tests during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"ArtsTechnica\">{{cite web|publisher=Ars Technica|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2020/03/firm-uses-theranos-patents-to-sue-company-making-coronavirus-test|title=Firm wielding Theranos patents asks judge to block coronavirus test|accessdate=2020-03-17}}</ref><ref>[https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/18/21185006/softbank-theranos-coronavirus-covid-lawsuit-patent-testing A SoftBank-owned company used Theranos patents to sue over COVID-19 tests]</ref><ref>[https://www.law360.com/articles/1254102/fortress-offers-ip-rights-to-fight-covid-19-after-backlash Fortress Offers IP Rights To Fight COVID-19 After Backlash]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Irell & Manella Graduate School of Biological Sciences]] at [[City of Hope National Medical Center]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|https://www.irell.com}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Irell and Manella}}\n[[Category:Newport Beach, California]]\n[[Category:Law firms established in 1941]]\n[[Category:Law firms based in Los Angeles]]\n\n\n{{US-law-firm-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox law firm\n| name = Irell & Manella\n| logo = [[File:Irell & Manella.png|frameless|Irell & Manella]]\n| headquarters = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], United States\n| foundation = 1941\n| num_offices = 2\n| num_attorneys = 90+\n| practice_areas = General practice, [[intellectual property|IP]] litigation\n| revenue = {{gain}} 253 million [[United States dollar|USD]] (2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jdjournal.com/2010/02/16/profits-and-revenue-up-at-irell-manella/ |title=Irell & Manella, Revenue Increase, Profits Per Partner Increase |publisher=JD Journal |date=2010-02-16 |accessdate=2013-11-07}}</ref>\n| date_founded = 1941\n| company_type = [[LLP]]\n| homepage = {{url|Irell.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Irell & Manella LLP''' is an American [[law firm]] founded in 1941 by lawyers Lawrence E. Irell (1912\u20132000) and Arthur Manella (1917\u20131997).<ref>https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2000-jun-27-me-45311-story.html</ref><ref>https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1997-01-17-mn-19495-story.html</ref>  It has approximately 94 lawyers (down from a high of over 220), and placed 158th on The American Lawyer's 2019 Am Law 200 ranking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.com/law-firm-profile/?id=155&slreturn=20200005134043|title=Irell & Manella LLP|last=|first=|date=|website=Law.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2019-12-16}}</ref> It has two locations in [[Southern California]]: [[Century City]] and [[Newport Beach]]. Irell specializes in [[intellectual property]] [[litigation]] and general business litigation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abovethelaw.com/2012/01/associate-bonus-watch-irell-whacks-cravath-again/ |title=Associate Bonus Watch: Irell Whacks Cravath, Again \u00ab Above the Law: A Legal Web Site \u2013 News, Commentary, and Opinions on Law Firms, Lawyers, Law Schools, Law Suits, Judges and Courts + Career Resources |publisher=Abovethelaw.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-15}}</ref>\n\n[[Morgan Chu]], one of Irell's attorneys, is the brother of former United States [[Secretary of Energy]] [[Steven Chu]].<ref name=\"Office of the President-Elect\">{{cite news| title=Chu to be Energy Secretary| url=http://change.gov/newsroom/entry/president_elect_barack_obama_announces_key_members_of_energy_and_environmen/| date=2008-12-15| accessdate=2008-12-16| publisher=[[change.gov]]| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140813143325/http://change.gov/newsroom/entry/president_elect_barack_obama_announces_key_members_of_energy_and_environmen/| archivedate=2014-08-13}}</ref><ref name=\"Irell&Manella\">{{cite web|publisher=Irell & Manella LLP|url=http://www.irell.com/professionals-22.html|title=Morgan Chu|accessdate=2008-12-16}}</ref> The managing partner of the firm is Ellisen Turner. Michael Ermer is the managing partner of the Newport Beach office. Jane Shay Wald is the head of the trademark practice group, and David Siegel is the head of the securities litigation practice group. Former federal judge [[Layn R. Phillips]] was a longtime partner at the firm.   Under Secretary of Commerce for Intellectual Property and Director of the United States Patent and Trademark Office [[Andrei Iancu]] was also a longtime partner at the firm.\n\nIn 2020, Irell & Manella represented Labrador Diagnostics (a subsidiary of Fortress Investment Group, itself owned by the firm [[SoftBank]]) in an infringement lawsuit against bioFire (a subsidary of [[BioM\u00e9rieux]]), claiming the firm infringed patents purchased from the disgraced company [[Theranos]].  This legal action attracted heavy criticism due both to the origin of the patents, as well as bioFire responding by saying they were working on COVID-19 tests during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"ArtsTechnica\">{{cite web|publisher=Ars Technica|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2020/03/firm-uses-theranos-patents-to-sue-company-making-coronavirus-test|title=Firm wielding Theranos patents asks judge to block coronavirus test|accessdate=2020-03-17}}</ref><ref>[https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/18/21185006/softbank-theranos-coronavirus-covid-lawsuit-patent-testing A SoftBank-owned company used Theranos patents to sue over COVID-19 tests]</ref><ref>[https://www.law360.com/articles/1254102/fortress-offers-ip-rights-to-fight-covid-19-after-backlash Fortress Offers IP Rights To Fight COVID-19 After Backlash]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Irell & Manella Graduate School of Biological Sciences]] at [[City of Hope National Medical Center]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|https://www.irell.com}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Irell and Manella}}\n[[Category:Newport Beach, California]]\n[[Category:Law firms established in 1941]]\n[[Category:Law firms based in Los Angeles]]\n\n\n{{US-law-firm-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: subsidary \u2192 subsidiary", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irell_%26_Manella"}
{"title_page": "Microraptor", "text_new": "Microraptors are cute\n| fossil_range = [[Early Cretaceous]], {{fossil range|120}}\n| image = Microraptor gui holotype.png\n| image_upright = 1.15\n| image_caption = Fossil specimen, with white arrows pointing at preserved feathers\n| taxon = Microraptor\n| authority = [[Xu Xing (paleontologist)|Xu]] ''et al.'', 2000\n| type_species = {{extinct}}'''''Microraptor zhaoianus'''''\n| type_species_authority = Xu ''et al.'', 2000\n| subdivision_ranks = [[Species]]\n| subdivision =\n* '''''M. zhaoianus''''' <small>Xu ''et al.'', 2000</small>\n* '''''M. gui''''' <small>Xu ''et al.'', 2003</small>\n* '''''M. hanqingi''''' <small>Gong ''et al.'', 2012</small>\n| synonyms = \n* ''Cryptovolans'' <small>Czerkas ''et al.'', 2002</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Microraptor''''' ([[Greek language|Greek]], \u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2, ''m\u012bkros'': \"small\"; [[Latin language|Latin]], ''raptor'': \"one who seizes\") is a [[genus]] of small, four-winged [[Paraves|paravian]] [[dinosaur]]s. Numerous well-preserved [[fossil]] specimens have been recovered from [[Liaoning]], [[China]]. They date from the early [[Cretaceous]] [[Jiufotang Formation]] ([[Aptian]] stage), 120&nbsp;million [[year]]s ago. Three species have been named (''M. zhaoianus'', ''M. gui'', and ''M. hanqingi''), though further study has suggested that all of them represent variation in a single species, which is properly called ''M. zhaoianus''. '''''Cryptovolans''''', initially described as another four-winged dinosaur, is usually considered to be a synonym of ''Microraptor''.<ref name=\"senteretal2004\">{{cite journal | last1 = Senter | first1 = P. | last2 = Barsold | first2 = R. | last3 = Britt | first3 = B.B. | last4 = Burnham | first4 = D.A. | year = 2004 | title = Systematics and evolution of Dromaeosauridae (Dinosauria, Theropoda) | url = | journal = Bulletin of the Gunma Museum of Natural History | volume = 8 | issue = | pages = 1\u201320 }}</ref>\n\nLike ''[[Archaeopteryx]]'', well-preserved fossils of ''Microraptor'' provide important evidence about the evolutionary relationship between [[bird]]s and dinosaurs. ''Microraptor'' had long [[pennaceous feather]]s that formed aerodynamic surfaces on the arms and tail but also on the legs. This led paleontologist [[Xu Xing (paleontologist)|Xu Xing]] in 2003 to describe the first specimen to preserve this feature as a \"four-winged dinosaur\" and to speculate that it may have [[Gliding flight|glided]] using all four limbs for lift. Subsequent studies have suggested that ''Microraptor'' was capable of powered flight as well.\n\n''Microraptor'' was among the most abundant non-[[Avialae|avialan]] dinosaurs in its ecosystem, and the genus is represented by more fossils than any other dromaeosaurid, with possibly over 300 fossil specimens represented across various museum collections.<ref name=alexanderetal2010/>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Microraptor scale.png|thumb|left|Wingspan and body size compared with a human]]\nWith adult specimens estimated up to {{convert|77|cm|ft|disp=x| long (}}) and with a weight estimated up to {{convert|1|kg}}, ''Microraptor'' was among the [[Dinosaur size|smallest-known non-avian dinosaurs]].<ref name=\"chatterjee2007\"/> Holtz estimated it at {{convert|90|cm|ft}}.<ref name=\"Holtz2008\">Holtz, Thomas R. Jr. (2011) ''Dinosaurs: The Most Complete, Up-to-Date Encyclopedia for Dinosaur Lovers of All Ages,'' [http://www.geol.umd.edu/~tholtz/dinoappendix/HoltzappendixWinter2010.pdf Winter 2010 Appendix.]</ref> An estimate by Benson ''et al.'' in 2012 was that ''Microraptor'' had a maximum length of {{cvt|1.2|m|ft}}.<ref name=\"benson2012\"/> Aside from their extremely small size, ''Microraptor'' were among the first non-[[Avialae|avialan]] dinosaurs discovered with the impressions of feathers and wings. Seven specimens of ''M. zhaoianus'' have been described in detail, from which most feather impressions are known. Unusual even among early birds and feathered dinosaurs, ''Microraptor'' is one of the few known bird precursors to sport long flight feathers on the legs as well as the wings. Their bodies had a thick covering of feathers, with a diamond-shaped fan on the end of the tail (possibly for added stability during flight). Xu ''et al.'' (2003) compared the longer plumes on ''Microraptor''{{'}}s head to those of the [[Philippine eagle]]. Bands of dark and light present on some specimens may indicate color patterns present in life,<ref name=\"hwangetal2002\"/> though at least some individuals almost certainly possessed an iridescent black coloration.<ref name=\"iridescence\"/> Several anatomical features found in ''Microraptor'', such as a combination of unserrated and partially serrated teeth with constricted 'waists', and unusually long upper arm bones, are shared with both primitive avians and primitive [[Troodontidae|troodontids]]. ''Microraptor'' is particularly similar to the basal troodontid ''[[Sinovenator]]''; in their 2002 description of two ''M. zhaoianus'' specimens, Hwang ''et al.'' note that this is not particularly surprising, given that both ''Microraptor'' and ''Sinovenator'' are very primitive members of two closely related groups, and both are close to the [[Dromaeosauridae|deinonychosaurian]] split between dromaeosaurids and troodontids.<ref name=\"hwangetal2002\">Hwang, S.H., Norell, M.A., Ji, Q., and Gao, K. (2002). \"New Specimens of ''Microraptor zhaoianus'' (Theropoda: Dromaeosauridae) from Northeastern China.\" ''American Museum Novitates'', 3381: 44pp.</ref>\n\n===Coloration===\n[[File:Microraptor Restoration.png|thumb|[[Paleoart|Restoration]] of ''M. gui'' with coloration based on fossilized melanosomes]]\nIn March 2012, Quanguo Li ''et al.'' determined the plumage coloration of ''Microraptor'' based on the new specimen BMNHC PH881, which also showed several other features previously unknown in ''Microraptor''. By analyzing the fossilized melanosomes (pigment cells) in the fossil with [[scanning electron microscope]] techniques, the researchers compared their arrangements to those of modern birds. In ''Microraptor'', these cells were shaped in a manner consistent with black, glossy coloration in modern birds. These rod-shaped, narrow melanosomes were arranged in stacked layers, much like those of a modern [[Common starling|starling]], and indicated [[iridescence]] in the plumage of ''Microraptor''. Though the researchers state that the true function of the iridescence is yet unknown, it has been suggested that the tiny dromaeosaur was using its glossy coat as a form of communication or sexual display, much as in modern iridescent birds.<ref name=\"iridescence\">{{cite journal| last1 = Li| first1 = Q. | last2 = Gao | first2 = K.-Q. | last3 = Meng | first3 = Q. | last4 = Clarke | first4 = J.A. | last5 = Shawkey | first5 = M.D. | last6 = D'Alba | first6 = L. | last7 = Pei | first7 = R. | last8 = Ellision | first8 = M. | last9 = Norell | first9 = M.A. | last10 = Vinther | first10 = J.| title = Reconstruction of ''Microraptor'' and the Evolution of Iridescent Plumage| journal = Science| volume = 335| pages = 1215\u20131219| date = 2012| doi = 10.1126/science.1213780| pmid=22403389 | issue = 6073| bibcode = 2012Sci...335.1215L}}</ref><ref name=\"iridescence2\">{{cite news| last = Wilford| first = John Noble| title = Feathers Worth a 2nd Look Found on a Tiny Dinosaur| newspaper = The New York Times| location = New York| date = 8 March 2012| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/09/science/feather-cells-tell-of-microraptors-crowlike-sheen.html| accessdate = 22 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Paleobiology==\n===Wings and flight===\n''Microraptor'' had four [[wing]]s, one on each of its forelimbs and hindlimbs, somewhat resembling one possible arrangement of the quartet of flight surfaces on a [[tandem wing]] aircraft of today. It had long [[pennaceous feather]]s on arms and hands {{convert|10|\u2013|20|cm|in|adj=mid|long|abbr=on}} with legs and feet {{convert|11|\u2013|15|cm|in|adj=mid|long|abbr=on}}. The long feathers on the legs of ''Microraptor'' were true flight feathers as seen in modern [[bird]]s, with asymmetrical vanes on the arm, leg, and tail feathers. As in modern bird wings, ''Microraptor'' had both primary (anchored to the hand) and secondary (anchored to the arm) flight feathers. This standard wing pattern was mirrored on the hindlegs, with [[flight feather]]s anchored to the upper foot bones as well as the upper and lower leg. Though not apparent in most fossils under natural light, due to obstruction from decayed soft tissue, the feather bases extended close to or in contact with the bones, as in modern birds, providing strong anchor points.<ref name=hone2010>{{cite journal | last1 = Hone | first1 = D.W.E. | last2 = Tischlinger | first2 = H. | last3 = Xu | first3 = X. | last4 = Zhang | first4 = F. | year = 2010 | title = The extent of the preserved feathers on the four-winged dinosaur ''Microraptor gui'' under ultraviolet light | journal = PLOS One | volume = 5 | issue = 2| page = e9223 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0009223 | pmid=20169153 | pmc=2821398 | bibcode = 2010PLoSO...5.9223H }}</ref>\n\nIt was originally thought that ''Microraptor'' was a [[Gliding flight|glider]], and probably lived mainly in trees, because the hindwings anchored to the feet of ''Microraptor'' would have hindered their ability to run on the ground.<ref name=\"Xuetal2003\">Xu, X., Zhou, Z., Wang, X., Kuang, X., Zhang, F. and Du, X. (2003). \"Four-winged dinosaurs from China.\" ''Nature'', '''421'''(6921): 335-340, 23 Jan 2003.</ref> Some paleontologists have suggested that feathered dinosaurs used their wings to parachute from trees, possibly to attack or ambush prey on the ground, as a precursor to gliding or true flight.<ref name=\"benson2012\"/> In their 2007 study, Chatterjee and Templin tested this hypothesis as well, and found that the combined wing surface of ''Microraptor'' was too narrow to successfully parachute to the ground without injury from any significant height. However, the authors did leave open the possibility that ''Microraptor'' could have parachuted short distances, as between closely spaced tree branches.<ref name=\"chatterjee2007\"/><ref name=\"benson2012\">{{cite book|authors=Benson, R.B.J. & Brussatte, S.|year=2012|title=Prehistoric Life|location=London|publisher=Dorling Kindersley|page=332|isbn=978-0-7566-9910-9}}</ref> Wind tunnel experiments have demonstrated that sustaining a high-lift coefficient at the expense of high drag was likely the most efficient strategy for ''Microraptor'' when gliding between low elevations. ''Microraptor'' did not require a sophisticated, 'modern' wing morphology to be an effective glider.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Dyke | first1 = Gareth | last2 = de Kat | first2 = Roeland | last3 = Palmer | first3 = Colin | last4 = van der Kindere | first4 = Jacques | last5 = Naish | first5 = Darren | last6 = Ganapathisubramani | first6 = Bharathram | year = 2013 | title = Aerodynamic performance of the feathered dinosaur Microraptor and the evolution of feathered flight | url = | journal = Nature Communications | volume = 4 | issue = | page = 2489 | doi = 10.1038/ncomms3489 | pmid = 24048346 | bibcode = 2013NatCo...4.2489D }}</ref> However, the idea that ''Microraptor'' was an arboreal glider relies on it to have regularly climbed or even lived in trees, when study of its anatomy have shown that its limb proportions fall in line with modern ground birds rather than climbers, and its skeleton shows none of the expected adaptations in animals specialized for climbing trees.<ref name=Dececchi_etal_2016>{{cite journal | last1 = Dececchi | first1 = T.A. | last2 = Larsson | first2 = H.C.E. | last3 = Habib | first3 = M.B. | year = 2016 | title = The wings before the bird: an evaluation of flapping-based locomotory hypotheses in bird antecedents | journal = PeerJ | volume = 4 | issue = | page = e2159 | doi = 10.7717/peerj.2159 | pmid=27441115 | pmc=4941780}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Microraptor gui holotype under UV light.png|thumb|''M. gui'' [[holotype]] under two different UV light filters, revealing extent of preserved feathers and soft tissue]]\nDescribing specimens originally referenced as a distinctive species (''Cryptovolans pauli''), paleontologist Stephen Czerkas argued ''Microraptor'' may have been a powered flier, and indeed possibly a better flyer than ''[[Archaeopteryx]]''. He noted that the ''Microraptor's'' fused sternum, asymmetrical feathers, and features of the shoulder girdle indicated that it could fly under its own power, rather than merely gliding. Today, most scientists agree that ''Microraptor'' had the anatomical features expected of a flying animal, though it would have been a less advanced form of flight compared to birds. For example, some studies suggest the shoulder joint was too primitive to allow a full flapping flight stroke. In the ancestral anatomy of theropod dinosaurs, the shoulder socket faced downward and slightly backward, making it impossible for the animals to raise their arms vertically, a prerequisite for the flapping flight stroke in birds. Studies of maniraptoran anatomy have suggested that the shoulder socket did not shift into the bird-like position of a high, upward orientation close to the [[vertebra]]l column until relatively advanced avialans like the [[enantiornithes]] appeared.<ref name=senter2006>{{cite journal | last1 = Senter | first1 = P | year = 2006 | title = Scapular orientation in theropods and basal birds, and the origin of flapping flight | url = | journal = Acta Palaeontol. Pol. | volume = 51 | issue = | pages = 305\u2013313 }}</ref> However, other scientists have argued that the shoulder girdle in some [[Paraves|paravian]] theropods, including ''Microraptor'', is curved in such a way that the shoulder joint could only have been positioned high on the back, allowing for a nearly vertical upstroke of the wing. This possibly advanced shoulder anatomy, combined with the presence of a [[Patagium|propatagium]] linking the wrist to the shoulder (which fills the space in front of the flexed wing and may support the wing against drag in modern birds) and an [[alula]], much like a \"thumb-like\" form of [[leading edge slot]], may indicate that ''Microraptor'' was capable of true, powered flight.<ref name=avianancestry>{{Cite journal|author1=Federico L. Agnol\u00edn |author2=Fernando E. Novas |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2013 |title=Avian ancestors. A review of the phylogenetic relationships of the theropods Unenlagiidae, Microraptoria, ''Anchiornis'' and Scansoriopterygidae |journal=SpringerBriefs in Earth System Sciences |volume= |issue= |pages=1\u201396 |doi=10.1007/978-94-007-5637-3 |isbn=978-94-007-5636-6 }}</ref>\n\nOther studies have demonstrated that the wings of ''Microraptor'' were large enough to generate the lift necessary for powered launching into flight even without a fully vertical flight stroke. A 2016 study of incipient flight ability in paravians demonstrated that ''Microraptor'' was capable of [[wing-assisted incline running]], as well as wing-assisted leaping and even ground-based launching.<ref name=Dececchi_etal_2016/>\n\nStephen Czerkas, Gregory S. Paul, and others have argued that the fact ''Microraptor'' could fly and yet is also very clearly a dromaeosaurid suggests that the [[Dromaeosauridae]], including later and larger species such as ''[[Deinonychus]]'', were secondarily flightless. The work of Xu and colleagues also suggested that the ancestors of dromaeosaurids were probably small, arboreal, and capable of [[Gliding flight|gliding]], although later discoveries of more primitive dromaeosaurids with short forelimbs unsuitable for gliding have cast doubt on this view.<ref name=\"Xuetal2003\"/><ref name=Turneretal07>{{cite journal | last1 = Turner | first1 = Alan H. | last2 = Pol | first2 = Diego | last3 = Clarke | first3 = Julia A. | last4 = Erickson | first4 = Gregory M. | last5 = Norell | first5 = Mark | year = 2007 | title = A basal dromaeosaurid and size evolution preceding avian flight | url = | journal = Science | volume = 317 | issue = 5843| pages = 1378\u20131381 | doi = 10.1126/science.1144066 | pmid = 17823350 | bibcode = 2007Sci...317.1378T }}</ref> Work done on the question of flight ability in other paravians, however, showed that most of them probably would not have been able to achieve enough lift for powered flight, given their limited flight strokes and relatively smaller wings. These studies concluded that ''Microraptor'' probably evolved flight and its associated features (fused sternum, alula, etc.) independently of the ancestors of birds.<ref name=Dececchi_etal_2016/>\n\n===Hindwing posture===\n[[File:Microraptor models.png|thumb|Wind tunnel experiments with different wing configurations]]\n[[Sankar Chatterjee]] suggested in 2005 that, in order for ''Microraptor'' to [[Gliding flight|glide]] or fly, the forewings and hindwings must have been on different levels (as on a [[biplane]]) and not overlaid (as on a [[dragonfly]]), and that the latter posture would have been anatomically impossible. Using this biplane model, Chatterjee was able to calculate possible methods of gliding, and determined that ''Microraptor'' most likely employed a ''[[phugoid]]'' style of gliding: launching itself from a perch, the animal would have swooped downward in a deep U-shaped curve and then lifted again to land on another tree. The feathers not directly employed in the biplane [[wing]] structure, like those on the [[tibia]] and the [[tail]], could have been used to control drag and alter the [[Airway (aviation)|flight path]], [[trajectory]], etc. The orientation of the hindwings would also have helped the animal control its gliding flight. Chatterjee also used computer [[algorithm]]s that test [[Flying and gliding animals|animal flight]] capacity to test whether or not ''Microraptor'' was capable of true, powered flight, as opposed to or in addition to passive gliding. The resulting data showed that ''Microraptor'' did have the requirements to sustain level powered flight, so it is theoretically possible that the animal flew, as opposed to gliding.<ref name=\"chatterjee2007\">{{cite journal | last1 = Chatterjee | first1 = S. | last2 = Templin | first2 = R.J. | year = 2007 | title = Biplane wing planform and flight performance of the feathered dinosaur ''Microraptor gui'' | url = http://www.pnas.org/cgi/reprint/0609975104v1.pdf | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences | volume = 104 | issue = 5| pages = 1576\u20131580 | doi=10.1073/pnas.0609975104 | pmid=17242354 | pmc=1780066| bibcode = 2007PNAS..104.1576C }}</ref>\n\nSome paleontologists have doubted the biplane hypothesis, and have proposed other configurations. A 2010 study by Alexander ''et al.'' described the construction of a lightweight three-dimensional physical model used to perform glide tests. Using several hindleg configurations for the model, they found that the biplane model, while not unreasonable, was structurally deficient and needed a heavy-headed weight distribution for stable gliding, which they deemed unlikely. The study indicated that a laterally abducted hindwing structure represented the most biologically and aerodynamically consistent configuration for ''Microraptor''.<ref name=alexanderetal2010>{{cite journal | last1 = Alexander | first1 = D.E. | last2 = Gong | first2 = E. | last3 = Martin | first3 = L.D. | last4 = Burnham | first4 = D.A. | last5 = Falk | first5 = A.R. | year = 2010 | title = Model tests of gliding with different hindwing configurations in the four-winged dromaeosaurid ''Microraptor gui'' | url = | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA | volume = 107 | issue = 7| pages = 2972\u20132976 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0911852107 | pmid = 20133792 | bibcode = 2010PNAS..107.2972A | pmc = 2840342 }}</ref> A further analysis by Brougham and Brusatte, however, concluded that Alexander's model reconstruction was not consistent with all of the available data on ''Microraptor'' and argued that the study was insufficient for determining a likely flight pattern for ''Microraptor''. Brougham and Brusatte criticized the anatomy of the model used by Alexander and his team, noting that the hip anatomy was not consistent with other dromaeosaurs. In most dromaeosaurids, features of the hip bone prevent the legs from splaying horizontally; instead, they are locked in a vertical position below the body. Alexander's team used a specimen of ''Microraptor'' which was crushed flat to make their model, which Brougham and Brusatte argued did not reflect its actual anatomy.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Brusatte | first1 = Stephen L. | last2 = Brougham | first2 = Jason | year = 2010| title = Distorted ''Microraptor'' specimen is not ideal for understanding the origin of avian flight | url = | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA | volume = 107| issue = 40| pages = E155| doi = 10.1073/pnas.1004977107 | pmid = 20864633 | bibcode = 2010PNAS..107E.155B| pmc = 2951411}}</ref> Later in 2010, Alexander's team responded to these criticisms, noting that the related dromaeosaur ''[[Hesperonychus]]'', which is known from complete hip bones preserved in three dimensions, also shows hip sockets directed partially upward, possibly allowing the legs to splay more than in other dromaeosaurs.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Alexander | first1 = D.E. | last2 = Gong | first2 = E. | last3 = Martin | first3 = L.D. | last4 = Burnham | first4 = D.A. | last5 = Falk | first5 = A.R. | year = 2010 | title = Reply to Brougham and Brusatte: Overall anatomy confirms posture and flight model offers insight into the evolution of bird flight | url = | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA | volume = 107| issue = 40| pages = E155| doi = 10.1073/pnas.1004977107 | pmid = 20864633 | bibcode = 2010PNAS..107E.155B | pmc = 2951411 }}</ref>\n\n===Ground movement===\n[[File:Microraptor by durbed.jpg|thumb|Restoration of two individuals by the ground]]\nDue to the extent of the hindwings onto most of the animal's foot, many scientists have suggested that ''Microraptor'' would have been awkward during normal ground movement or running. The front wing feathers would also have hindered ''Microraptor'' when on the ground, due to the limited range of motion in the wrist and the extreme length of the wing feathers. A 2010 study by Corwin Sullivan and colleagues showed that, even with the wing folded as far as possible, the feathers would still have dragged along the ground if the arms were held in a neutral position, or extended forward as in a predatory strike. Only by keeping the wings elevated, or the upper arm extended fully backward, could ''Microraptor'' have avoided damaging the wing feathers. Therefore, it may have been anatomically impossible for ''Microraptor'' to have used its clawed forelimbs in capturing prey or manipulating objects.<ref name=sullivanetal2010>{{cite journal | last1 = Sullivan | first1 = C. | last2 = Hone | first2 = D.W.E. | last3 = Xu | first3 = X. | last4 = Zhang | first4 = F. | year = 2010 | title = The asymmetry of the carpal joint and the evolution of wing folding in maniraptoran theropod dinosaurs | url = | journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society B | volume = 277 | issue = 1690| pages = 2027\u20132033 | doi = 10.1098/rspb.2009.2281 | pmid = 20200032 | pmc = 2880093 }}</ref>\n\n===Implications===\n[[File:Tetrapteryx.jpg|thumb|left|[[William Beebe]]'s hypothetical \"''Tetrapteryx''\" with four wings, 1915]]\nThe unique wing arrangement found in ''Microraptor'' raised the question of whether the evolution of flight in modern birds went through a four-winged stage, or whether four-winged gliders like ''Microraptor'' were an evolutionary side-branch that left no descendants. As early as 1915, [[Natural history|naturalist]] [[William Beebe]] had argued that the evolution of bird flight may have gone through a four-winged (or ''tetrapteryx'') stage.<ref name=\"beebe1915\">{{cite journal | last1 = Beebe | first1 = C. W. A. | year = 1915 | title = Tetrapteryx stage in the ancestry of birds | url = | journal = Zoologica | volume = 2 | issue = | pages = 38\u201352 }}</ref> Chatterjee and Templin did not take a strong stance on this possibility, noting that both a conventional interpretation and a tetrapteryx stage are equally possible. However, based on the presence of unusually long leg feathers in various feathered dinosaurs, ''[[Archaeopteryx]]'', and some modern birds such as raptors, as well as the discovery of further dinosaur with long primary feathers on their feet (such as ''[[Pedopenna]]''), the authors argued that the current body of evidence, both from morphology and phylogeny, suggests that bird flight did shift at some point from shared limb dominance to front-limb dominance, and that all modern birds may have evolved from four-winged ancestors, or at least ancestors with unusually long leg feathers relative to the modern configuration.<ref name=\"chatterjee2007\"/>\n\n===Feeding===\n[[File:Microraptor gui cast.jpg|thumb|Close-up of a cast]]\nIn 2010 researchers announced that further preparation of the type fossil of ''M. zhaoianus'' revealed preserved probable gut contents. These consisted of mammalian bones, including possible skull, limb, and vertebral fragments and also a whole foot. The foot skeleton is similar to those of ''[[Eomaia]]'' and ''[[Sinodelphys]]''. It corresponds to an animal with an estimated snout to vent length of {{cvt|80|mm}} and a mass of {{cvt|20|\u2013|25|g}}. The unguals of the foot are less curved than in ''Eomaia'' or ''Sinodelphys'', indicating that the mammal could climb but less effectively than in the two latter genera.<ref name=\"Larsson et al. 2010\">Larsson, Hans, Hone, David, Dececchi, T. Alexander, Sullivan, Corwin, Xu, Xing. \"THE WINGED NON-AVIAN DINOSAUR MICRORAPTOR FED ON MAMMALS: IMPLICATIONS FOR THE JEHOL BIOTA ECOSYSTEM\" \"Program and Abstracts. 70th Anniversary Meeting Society of Vertebrate Paleontology October 2010\" 114A.</ref>\n\nIn the December 6, 2011 issue of ''Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences'', Jingmai O'Connor and coauthors described a ''Microraptor'' specimen containing bird bones in its abdomen, specifically a partial wing and feet. Their position indicate that the dinosaur swallowed a tree-perching bird whole.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Jingmai O'Connor |author2=Zhonghe Zhou |author3=Xing Xu |last-author-amp=yes |year=2011 |title=Additional specimen of ''Microraptor'' provides unique evidence of dinosaurs preying on birds |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America |volume=108 |issue=49 |pages=19662\u201319665 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1117727108 |url=http://www.pnas.org/content/108/49/19662.abstract |pmid=22106278 |pmc=3241752|bibcode=2011PNAS..10819662O }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 researchers announced that they had found fish scales in the abdominal cavity of a ''Microraptor'' specimen.<ref name=Xing13>{{cite journal |author=Lida Xing|year=2013 |title=Piscivory in the feathered dinosaur ''Microraptor'' |journal=Evolution|doi=10.1111/evo.12119|display-authors=etal |volume=67 |issue=8 |pages=2441\u20132445 |pmid=23888864}}</ref> This new finding corrects the previous position that ''Microraptor'' hunted only in an arboreal environment. They also argued that the specimen showed a probable adaptation to a fish-eating diet: the good preservation of the mandible shows that the first three teeth were inclined anterodorsally, a character often associated with piscivory.<ref name=Xing13/> ''Microraptor'' was an opportunistic feeder, hunting the most common prey in both arboreal and aquatic habitats.<ref name=Xing13/>\n\nIn 2019, a new genus of [[Scleroglossa|scleroglossan]] [[lizard]] (''[[Indrasaurus]]'') was described from a specimen found in the stomach of a ''Microraptor''. The ''Microraptor'' apparently swallowed its prey head first, a behavior typical of modern [[Carnivore|carnivorous]] [[Bird|birds]] and lizards. The ''Indrasaurus'' bones lacked marked pitting and scarring, indicating that the ''Microraptor'' died shortly after eating the lizard and before significant digestion had occurred.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhou|first=Zhonghe|last2=Zhang|first2=Xiaomei|last3=Wang|first3=Yan|last4=Wang|first4=Xiaoli|last5=Dong|first5=Liping|last6=Zheng|first6=Xiaoting|last7=O\u2019Connor|first7=Jingmai|date=2019-07-11|title=Microraptor with Ingested Lizard Suggests Non-specialized Digestive Function|url=https://www.cell.com/current-biology/abstract/S0960-9822(19)30713-4|journal=Current Biology|language=English|volume=0|issue=14|pages=2423\u20132429.e2|doi=10.1016/j.cub.2019.06.020|issn=0960-9822|pmid=31303494}}</ref>\n\nUnlike its fellow [[Paraves|paravian]] ''[[Anchiornis]]'', ''Microraptor'' has never been found with [[Pellet (ornithology)|gastric pellets]], despite the existence of four ''Microraptor'' specimens that preserve stomach contents. This suggests that ''Microraptor'' passed indigestible fur, feathers, and bits of bone in its droppings instead of producing pellets.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBased on the size of the [[Sclerotic ring|scleral ring]] of the eye, it has been suggested ''Microraptor'' hunted at night.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Nocturnality in dinosaurs inferred from scleral ring and orbit morphology|vauthors=Schmitz L, Motani R | journal=Science| year=2011| doi=10.1126/science.1200043| pmid=21493820| volume=332 | issue=6030 | pages=705\u20138| bibcode=2011Sci...332..705S}}</ref> However, the discovery of iridescent plumage in ''Microraptor'' has cast doubt on this conclusion, as no modern birds that have iridescent plumage are known to be nocturnal.<ref name=\"iridescence\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n===Naming controversy===\n{{Main|Archaeoraptor}}\n[[File:Archaeoraptor-Paleozoological Museum of China.jpg|alt=|thumb|The \"[[Archaeoraptor]]\" fossil; the tail belongs to ''Microraptor'']]\nThe initial naming of ''Microraptor'' was controversial, because of the unusual circumstances of its first description. The first specimen to be described was part of a chimeric specimen\u2014a patchwork of different feathered dinosaur species (''Microraptor'' itself, ''Yanornis'' and an as-of-yet undescribed third species) assembled from multiple specimens in China and smuggled to the USA for [[Fossil collecting|sale]]. After the forgery was revealed by [[Xu Xing (paleontologist)|Xu Xing]] of [[Beijing]]'s [[Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology]], [[Storrs L. Olson]], curator of birds in the [[National Museum of Natural History]] of the [[Smithsonian Institution]], published a description of the Microraptor's tail in an obscure journal, giving it the name ''Archaeoraptor liaoningensis'' in an attempt to remove the name from the paleornithological record by assigning it to the part least likely to be a bird.<ref name=\"olson2000\">Olson, S.L. (2000). \"Countdown to Piltdown at ''National Geographic'': the rise and fall of ''Archaeoraptor''.\" ''Backbone'', '''13'''(2) (April): 1\u20133.</ref> However, Xu had discovered the remainder of the specimen from which the tail had been taken and published a description of it later that year, giving it the name ''Microraptor zhaoianus''.<ref name=\"Xu2000\">Xu, X., Zhou, Z., and Wang, X. (2000). \"The smallest known non-avian theropod dinosaur.\" ''Nature'', '''408''' (December): 705-708.{{cite web |url=http://research.amnh.org/%7Esunny/microraptor.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-12-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217154907/http://research.amnh.org/%7Esunny/microraptor.pdf |archivedate=2008-12-17 }}</ref>\n\nSince the two names designate the same individual as the [[Type (biology)|type]] specimen, ''Microraptor zhaoianus'' would have been a [[junior objective synonym]] of ''Archaeoraptor liaoningensis'' and the latter, if valid, would have had priority under the [[International Code of Zoological Nomenclature]]. However, there is some doubt whether Olson in fact succeeded in meeting all the formal requirements for establishing a new taxon. Namely, Olson designated the specimen as a [[lectotype]], before an actual type species was formally erected.<ref name=dmlarchaeoraptor>Creisler, B. (2002). \"[http://dml.cmnh.org/2001Jan/msg00092.html Archaeoraptor still a nomen nudum].\" Message to the Dinosaur Mailing List, 4 Jan 2001. accessed 23 Sep 2009.</ref> A similar situation arose with ''[[Tyrannosaurus rex]]'' and ''Manospondylus gigas'', in which the former became a ''nomen protectum'' and the latter a ''nomen oblitum'' due to revisions in the ICZN rules that took place on December 31, 1999.<ref name=\"sowhyhasn\">Taylor, M. (2002). \"[http://www.miketaylor.org.uk/dino/faq/s-class/priority/].\" So why hasn't ''Tyrannosaurus'' been renamed ''Massospondylus''?, 27 Aug 2002. accessed 30 Sept 2014.</ref> In addition, Xu's name for the type specimen (''Microraptor'') was subsequently used more frequently than the original name; as such, this and the chimeric nature of the specimen would render the name \"Archaeoraptor\" a ''nomen vanum'' (as it was improperly described) and the junior synonym ''Microraptor'' a ''nomen protectum'' (as it's been used in more published works than \"Archaeoraptor\" and was properly described).<ref name=dmlarchaeoraptorvmicroraptor>Williams, T. (2002). \"[http://dml.cmnh.org/2001Jan/msg00020.html Archaeoraptor v Microraptor].\" Message to the Dinosaur Mailing List, 1 Jan 2001. accessed 30 Sept 2014.</ref>\n\n===Additional specimens===\n[[File:Microraptor Skeletons by Qilong.jpg|thumb|Skeletal restorations of various specimens]]\nThe first specimen referred to ''Microraptor'' represented a small individual and included faint feather remnants, but was otherwise not well preserved and lacked a skull.\nIn 2002 [[Mark Norell]] et al. described another specimen, BPM 1 3-13, which they did not name or refer to an existing species.<ref name=\"norelletal02\">Norell, Mark, Ji, Qiang, Gao, Keqin, Yuan, Chongxi, Zhao, Yibin, Wang, Lixia. (2002). \"'Modern' feathers on a non-avian dinosaur\". ''Nature'', 416: pp. 36. 7 March 2002.></ref> Later that year [[Stephen Czerkas]] et al. named the specimen ''Cryptovolans pauli'', and referred two additional specimens (the first to show well-preserved feathers) to this species. The generic name was derived from Greek ''kryptos'', \"hidden\", and [[Latin]] ''volans'', \"flying\". The [[specific name (zoology)|specific name]], ''pauli'', honors [[Paleontology|paleontologist]] [[Gregory S. Paul]], who had long proposed that dromaeosaurids evolved from flying ancestors.<ref name=\"Czerkas2002\"/>\n\nThe [[type specimen]]s of ''C. pauli'' were collected from the [[Jiufotang Formation]], dating from the early [[Albian]] and now belong to the collection of the Paleontology Museum of Beipiao, in [[Liaoning]], China. They are referred to by the inventory numbers LPM 0200, the [[holotype]]; LPM 0201, its counterslab (slab and counterslab together represent the earlier BPM 1 3-13); and the [[paratype]] LPM 0159, a smaller skeleton. Both individuals are preserved as articulated compression fossils; they are reasonably complete but partially damaged.<ref name=\"Czerkas2002\"/>\n[[File:Microraptor-Beijing Museum of Natural History.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|Specimen at the [[Beijing Museum of Natural History]]]]\nCzerkas ''et al.'' (2002) diagnosed the genus on the basis of having primary feathers (which in the authors' opinion made it a [[bird]]), a co-ossified sternum, a tail consisting of 28 to 30 vertebrae and a third finger with a short phalanx III-3.<ref name=\"Czerkas2002\"/> Some of the feathers Czerkas described as primary were actually attached to the leg, rather than the arm. This, along with most of the other diagnostic characters, is also present in the genus ''Microraptor'', which was first described earlier than ''Cryptovolans''.<ref name=\"Xuetal03\">{{cite journal | last1 = Xu | first1 = Xing | last2 = Zhou | first2 = Zhinghe | last3 = Wang | first3 = Xiaolin | last4 = KUang | first4 = Xuewen | last5 = Zhang | first5 = Fucheng | last6 = Du | first6 = Xiangke | year = 2003 | title = Four-winged dinosaurs from China | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 421 | issue = 6921| pages = 335\u2013340 | doi=10.1038/nature01342 | pmid=12540892| bibcode = 2003Natur.421..335X }}</ref> However, BPM 1 3-13 has a longer tail, proportionately, than other ''Microraptor'' specimens that had been described by 2002, which have 24 to 26 tail vertebrae.<ref name=\"norelletal02\"/>\n\nSubsequent studies (and more specimens of ''Microraptor'') have shown that the features used to distinguish ''Cryptovolans'' are not unique, but are present to varying degrees across various specimens. In a review by Phil Senter and colleagues in 2004, the scientists suggested that all these features represented individual variation across various age groups of a single ''Microraptor'' species, making the name ''Cryptovolans pauli'' and ''Microraptor gui'' junior synonyms of ''Microraptor zhaoianus''.<ref name=\"senteretal2004\"/> Many other researchers, including Alan Feduccia and Tom Holtz, have since supported its synonymy.<ref name=\"Holtz2008\"/><ref name=FLH05>{{cite journal|last=Feduccia |first=A. |year=2005 |title=Do feathered dinosaurs exist? Testing the hypothesis on neontological and paleontological evidence |journal=Journal of Morphology |volume=266 |issue=2 |pages=125\u2013166 |pmid=16217748 |doi=10.1002/jmor.10382|last2=Lingham-Soliar|first2=T|last3=Hinchliffe|first3=JR}}</ref>\n\nA new specimen of ''Microraptor'', BMNHC PH881, showed several features previously unknown in the animal, including the probably glossy-black iridescent plumage coloration. The new specimen also featured a bifurcated tailfan, similar in shape to previously known ''Microraptor'' tailfans except sporting a pair of long, narrow feathers at the center of the fan. The new specimen also showed no sign of the nuchal crest, indicating that the crest inferred from the holotype specimen may be an artifact of [[taphonomy|taphonomic]] distortion.<ref name=\"iridescence\"/><ref name=\"iridescence2\"/>\n\nNumerous further specimens likely belonging to ''Microraptor'' have been uncovered, all from the Shangheshou Bed of the [[Jiufotang Formation]] in Liaoning, China. In fact, ''Microraptor'' is the most abundant non-avialan dinosaur fossil type found in this formation.<ref name=\"xu&norell2006\">{{cite journal | last1 = Xu | first1 = X. | last2 = Norell | first2 = M.A. | year = 2006 | title = Non-Avian dinosaur fossils from the Lower Cretaceous Jehol Group of western Liaoning, China | doi = 10.1002/gj.1044 | journal = Geological Journal | volume = 41 | issue = 3\u20134| pages = 419\u2013437 }}</ref> In 2010, it was reported that there were over 300 undescribed specimens attributable to ''Microraptor'' or its close relatives among the collections of several Chinese museums, though many had been altered or composited by private fossil collectors.<ref name=alexanderetal2010/>\n\n===Study and debate===\n[[File:Microraptor zhaoianus.jpg|thumb|upright|Fossil specimen]]\nNorell ''et al.'' (2002) described BPM 1 3-13 as the first dinosaur known to have flight feathers on its legs as well as on its arms.<ref name=\"Norelletal02\">{{cite journal | last1 = Norell | first1 = Mark | last2 = Ji | first2 = Qiang | last3 = Gao | first3 = Keqin | last4 = Yuan | first4 = Chongxi | last5 = Zhao | first5 = Yibin | last6 = Wang | first6 = Lixia | year = 2002 | title = 'Modern' feathers on a non-avian dinosaur | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 416 | issue = 6876| pages = 36\u20137 | doi=10.1038/416036a| pmid = 11882883 | bibcode = 2002Natur.416...36N }}</ref>\n\nCzerkas (2002) mistakenly described the fossil as having no long feathers on its legs, but only on its hands and arms, as he illustrated on the cover of his book ''Feathered Dinosaurs and the Origin of Flight''.<ref name=\"Czerkas2002\">Czerkas, Sylvia J. ed. (2002) \"Feathered Dinosaurs and the Origin of Flight\" The Dinosaur Museum Journal Volume 1. Blanding, Utah, USA. The Dinosaur Museum, August 1, 2002</ref> In his discussion of ''Cryptovolans'' in this book, Czerkas strongly denounces Norell's conclusions; \"''The misinterpretation of the primary wing feathers as being from the hind legs stems directly to'' [sic] ''seeing what one believes and wants to see''\".<ref name=\"Czerkas2002\"/> Czerkas also denounced Norell for failing to conclude that [[Dromaeosauridae|dromaeosaurs]] are birds, accusing him of succumbing to \"''...the blinding influences of preconceived ideas.''\"<ref name=\"Czerkas2002\"/> The [[crown group]] definition of Aves, as a subset of [[Avialae]], the explicit definition of the term \"bird\" that Norell employs, would definitely exclude BPM 1 3-13. However, he does not consider the specimen to belong to Avialae either.<ref name=\"Norelletal02\"/>\n\nCzerkas's interpretation of the hindleg feathers noted by Norell proved to be incorrect the following year, when additional specimens of ''Microraptor'' were published by Xu and colleagues, showing a distinctive \"hindwing\" completely separate from the forelimb wing. The first of these specimens was discovered in 2001, and between 2001 and 2003 four more specimens were bought from private collectors by Xu's museum, the [[Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology]]. Xu also considered these specimens, most of which had hindwings and proportional differences from the original ''Microraptor'' specimen, to be a new species, which he named ''Microraptor gui''. However, Senter also questioned this classification, noting that as with ''Cryptovolans'', most of the differences appeared to correspond with size, and likely age differences.<ref name=senteretal2004/> Two further specimens, classified as ''M. zhaoianus'' in 2002 (''M. gui'' had not yet been named), have also been described by Hwang and colleagues.<ref name=\"hwangetal2002\"/>\n\nCzerkas also believed that the animal may have been able to fly better than ''[[Archaeopteryx]]'', the animal usually referred to as the earliest known bird. He cited the fused sternum and asymmetrical feathers, and argued that ''Microraptor'' has modern bird features that make it more derived than ''Archaeopteryx''. Czerkas cited the fact that this possibly volant animal is also very clearly a dromaeosaurid to suggest that the [[Dromaeosauridae]] might actually be a basal bird group, and that later, larger, species such as ''[[Deinonychus]]'' were secondarily flightless (Czerkas, 2002). The current consensus is that there is not enough evidence to conclude whether dromaeosaurs descended from an ancestor with some aerodynamic abilities. The work of Xu ''et al.'' (2003) suggested that basal dromaeosaurs were probably small, arboreal, and could glide.<ref name=xuetal2003>{{cite journal | last1 = Xing | first1 = X. | last2 = Zhou | first2 = Z. | last3 = Wang | first3 = X. | last4 = Kuang | first4 = X. | last5 = Zhang | first5 = F. | last6 = Du | first6 = X. | year = 2003 | title = Four-winged dinosaurs from China | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 421 | issue = 6921| pages = 335\u2013340 | bibcode = 2003Natur.421..335X | doi = 10.1038/nature01342 | pmid = 12540892 }}</ref> The work of Turner ''et al.'' (2007) suggested that the ancestral dromaeosaur could not glide or fly, but that there was good evidence that it was small-bodied (around 65 cm long and 600\u2013700&nbsp;g in mass).<ref name=\"Turneretal07\"/>\n\n==Classification==\n[[File:Dromaeosaurs.png|thumb|Size of ''Microraptor'' (1) compared with other [[Dromaeosauridae|dromaeosaurs]]]]\n[[File:Shandong Microraptor.jpg|thumb|Specimen in the Shandong Tianyu Museum of Nature]]\nThe cladogram below follows a 2012 analysis by paleontologists Phil Senter, James I. Kirkland, Donald D. DeBlieux, Scott Madsen and Natalie Toth.<ref name=Yurgovuchia>{{Cite journal | last1 = Senter | first1 = P. | last2 = Kirkland | first2 = J. I. | last3 = Deblieux | first3 = D. D. | last4 = Madsen | first4 = S. | last5 = Toth | first5 = N. | editor1-last = Dodson | editor1-first = Peter | title = New Dromaeosaurids (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Utah, and the Evolution of the Dromaeosaurid Tail | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0036790 | journal = PLOS One | volume = 7 | issue = 5 | pages = e36790 | year = 2012 | pmid = 22615813| pmc = 3352940| bibcode = 2012PLoSO...736790S }}</ref>\n\n{{clade| style=font-size:100%;line-height:100%\n|label1=[[Dromaeosauridae]]\n|1={{clade\n   |1=''[[Xiaotingia]]'' [[File:Xiaotingia .jpg|80px]]\n   |2={{clade\n      |1=[[Unenlagiinae]] [[File:Austroraptor_Restoration_(flipped).png|80px]]\n      |2={{clade\n         |1=''[[Shanag]]'' [[File:Shanag.jpg|80px]]\n         |2={{clade\n            |label1=[[Eudromaeosauria]]\n            |1={{clade\n               |1=[[Saurornitholestinae]] \n               |2={{clade\n                  |1=[[Velociraptorinae]] [[File:Fred Wierum Velociraptor.png|80px]]\n                  |2=[[Dromaeosaurinae]] [[File:Deinonychus_ewilloughby_(flipped).png|80px]] }} }}\n            |label2=[[Microraptoria]]\n            |2={{clade\n               |1=''[[Tianyuraptor]]'' \n               |2={{clade\n                  |1=''[[Hesperonychus]]'' \n                  |2={{clade\n                     |1={{clade\n                        |1='''''Microraptor sp.''''' \n                        |2={{clade\n                           |1='''''Microraptor gui''''' [[File:Fred_Wierum_Microraptor.png|80px]]\n                           |2='''''Microraptor zhaoianus''''' }} }}\n                     |2={{clade\n                        |1=''[[Cryptovolans]]''\n                        |2=''[[Graciliraptor]]'' [[File:Graciliraptor.jpg|80px]]\n                        |3=''[[Sinornithosaurus]]'' [[File:Sinornithosaurus.jpg|80px]] }} }} }} }} }} }} }} }} }}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Dinosaurs}}\n* [[Timeline of dromaeosaurid research]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikispecies|Microraptor}}\n*[[Dromaeosauridae#Relationship with birds|Dromaeosauridae, ''Relationship with birds'']]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040306034207/http://www.indyrad.iupui.edu/public/jrafert/Filipovic/newfeather/Microraptor-gui-%28Cryptovol.jpg A model of ''Microraptor''/Cryptovolans pauli by Boban Filipovic]\n*Jacqui Hayes: [http://www.cosmosmagazine.com/node/984 Bird wings evolved from biplane dinosaurs] COSMOS magazine\n*[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/microraptor/ The Four-Winged Dinosaur] - PBS web site for the ''Nova'' documentary\n*NewScientist [https://www.newscientist.com/articleimages/dn21552/1-microraptors-glossy-black-feather-coat-reconstructed.html Microraptor's glossy black feather coat reconstructed]\n*[http://phenomena.nationalgeographic.com/2012/03/08/a-shiny-dinosaur-four-winged-microraptor-gets-colour-and-gloss/ nationalgeographic.com 2012-03-08 Ed Yong, A shiny dinosaur four-winged Microraptor gets colour and gloss]\n*[http://phenomena.nationalgeographic.com/2008/10/08/microraptor-the-dinosaur-that-flew-like-a-biplane/ nationalgeographic.com 2008-10-08 Ed Yong, Microraptor\u2013the dinosaur that flew like a biplane]\n\n{{Paraves|D.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q310537}}\n\n[[Category:Jiufotang fauna]]\n[[Category:Early Cretaceous dinosaurs of Asia]]\n[[Category:Microraptorians]]\n[[Category:Feathered dinosaurs]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 2000]]\n[[Category:Animal flight]]\n", "text_old": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = [[Early Cretaceous]], {{fossil range|120}}\n| image = Microraptor gui holotype.png\n| image_upright = 1.15\n| image_caption = Fossil specimen, with white arrows pointing at preserved feathers\n| taxon = Microraptor\n| authority = [[Xu Xing (paleontologist)|Xu]] ''et al.'', 2000\n| type_species = {{extinct}}'''''Microraptor zhaoianus'''''\n| type_species_authority = Xu ''et al.'', 2000\n| subdivision_ranks = [[Species]]\n| subdivision =\n* '''''M. zhaoianus''''' <small>Xu ''et al.'', 2000</small>\n* '''''M. gui''''' <small>Xu ''et al.'', 2003</small>\n* '''''M. hanqingi''''' <small>Gong ''et al.'', 2012</small>\n| synonyms = \n* ''Cryptovolans'' <small>Czerkas ''et al.'', 2002</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Microraptor''''' ([[Greek language|Greek]], \u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2, ''m\u012bkros'': \"small\"; [[Latin language|Latin]], ''raptor'': \"one who seizes\") is a [[genus]] of small, four-winged [[Paraves|paravian]] [[dinosaur]]s. Numerous well-preserved [[fossil]] specimens have been recovered from [[Liaoning]], [[China]]. They date from the early [[Cretaceous]] [[Jiufotang Formation]] ([[Aptian]] stage), 120&nbsp;million [[year]]s ago. Three species have been named (''M. zhaoianus'', ''M. gui'', and ''M. hanqingi''), though further study has suggested that all of them represent variation in a single species, which is properly called ''M. zhaoianus''. '''''Cryptovolans''''', initially described as another four-winged dinosaur, is usually considered to be a synonym of ''Microraptor''.<ref name=\"senteretal2004\">{{cite journal | last1 = Senter | first1 = P. | last2 = Barsold | first2 = R. | last3 = Britt | first3 = B.B. | last4 = Burnham | first4 = D.A. | year = 2004 | title = Systematics and evolution of Dromaeosauridae (Dinosauria, Theropoda) | url = | journal = Bulletin of the Gunma Museum of Natural History | volume = 8 | issue = | pages = 1\u201320 }}</ref>\n\nLike ''[[Archaeopteryx]]'', well-preserved fossils of ''Microraptor'' provide important evidence about the evolutionary relationship between [[bird]]s and dinosaurs. ''Microraptor'' had long [[pennaceous feather]]s that formed aerodynamic surfaces on the arms and tail but also on the legs. This led paleontologist [[Xu Xing (paleontologist)|Xu Xing]] in 2003 to describe the first specimen to preserve this feature as a \"four-winged dinosaur\" and to speculate that it may have [[Gliding flight|glided]] using all four limbs for lift. Subsequent studies have suggested that ''Microraptor'' was capable of powered flight as well.\n\n''Microraptor'' was among the most abundant non-[[Avialae|avialan]] dinosaurs in its ecosystem, and the genus is represented by more fossils than any other dromaeosaurid, with possibly over 300 fossil specimens represented across various museum collections.<ref name=alexanderetal2010/>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Microraptor scale.png|thumb|left|Wingspan and body size compared with a human]]\nWith adult specimens estimated up to {{convert|77|cm|ft|disp=x| long (}}) and with a weight estimated up to {{convert|1|kg}}, ''Microraptor'' was among the [[Dinosaur size|smallest-known non-avian dinosaurs]].<ref name=\"chatterjee2007\"/> Holtz estimated it at {{convert|90|cm|ft}}.<ref name=\"Holtz2008\">Holtz, Thomas R. Jr. (2011) ''Dinosaurs: The Most Complete, Up-to-Date Encyclopedia for Dinosaur Lovers of All Ages,'' [http://www.geol.umd.edu/~tholtz/dinoappendix/HoltzappendixWinter2010.pdf Winter 2010 Appendix.]</ref> An estimate by Benson ''et al.'' in 2012 was that ''Microraptor'' had a maximum length of {{cvt|1.2|m|ft}}.<ref name=\"benson2012\"/> Aside from their extremely small size, ''Microraptor'' were among the first non-[[Avialae|avialan]] dinosaurs discovered with the impressions of feathers and wings. Seven specimens of ''M. zhaoianus'' have been described in detail, from which most feather impressions are known. Unusual even among early birds and feathered dinosaurs, ''Microraptor'' is one of the few known bird precursors to sport long flight feathers on the legs as well as the wings. Their bodies had a thick covering of feathers, with a diamond-shaped fan on the end of the tail (possibly for added stability during flight). Xu ''et al.'' (2003) compared the longer plumes on ''Microraptor''{{'}}s head to those of the [[Philippine eagle]]. Bands of dark and light present on some specimens may indicate color patterns present in life,<ref name=\"hwangetal2002\"/> though at least some individuals almost certainly possessed an iridescent black coloration.<ref name=\"iridescence\"/> Several anatomical features found in ''Microraptor'', such as a combination of unserrated and partially serrated teeth with constricted 'waists', and unusually long upper arm bones, are shared with both primitive avians and primitive [[Troodontidae|troodontids]]. ''Microraptor'' is particularly similar to the basal troodontid ''[[Sinovenator]]''; in their 2002 description of two ''M. zhaoianus'' specimens, Hwang ''et al.'' note that this is not particularly surprising, given that both ''Microraptor'' and ''Sinovenator'' are very primitive members of two closely related groups, and both are close to the [[Dromaeosauridae|deinonychosaurian]] split between dromaeosaurids and troodontids.<ref name=\"hwangetal2002\">Hwang, S.H., Norell, M.A., Ji, Q., and Gao, K. (2002). \"New Specimens of ''Microraptor zhaoianus'' (Theropoda: Dromaeosauridae) from Northeastern China.\" ''American Museum Novitates'', 3381: 44pp.</ref>\n\n===Coloration===\n[[File:Microraptor Restoration.png|thumb|[[Paleoart|Restoration]] of ''M. gui'' with coloration based on fossilized melanosomes]]\nIn March 2012, Quanguo Li ''et al.'' determined the plumage coloration of ''Microraptor'' based on the new specimen BMNHC PH881, which also showed several other features previously unknown in ''Microraptor''. By analyzing the fossilized melanosomes (pigment cells) in the fossil with [[scanning electron microscope]] techniques, the researchers compared their arrangements to those of modern birds. In ''Microraptor'', these cells were shaped in a manner consistent with black, glossy coloration in modern birds. These rod-shaped, narrow melanosomes were arranged in stacked layers, much like those of a modern [[Common starling|starling]], and indicated [[iridescence]] in the plumage of ''Microraptor''. Though the researchers state that the true function of the iridescence is yet unknown, it has been suggested that the tiny dromaeosaur was using its glossy coat as a form of communication or sexual display, much as in modern iridescent birds.<ref name=\"iridescence\">{{cite journal| last1 = Li| first1 = Q. | last2 = Gao | first2 = K.-Q. | last3 = Meng | first3 = Q. | last4 = Clarke | first4 = J.A. | last5 = Shawkey | first5 = M.D. | last6 = D'Alba | first6 = L. | last7 = Pei | first7 = R. | last8 = Ellision | first8 = M. | last9 = Norell | first9 = M.A. | last10 = Vinther | first10 = J.| title = Reconstruction of ''Microraptor'' and the Evolution of Iridescent Plumage| journal = Science| volume = 335| pages = 1215\u20131219| date = 2012| doi = 10.1126/science.1213780| pmid=22403389 | issue = 6073| bibcode = 2012Sci...335.1215L}}</ref><ref name=\"iridescence2\">{{cite news| last = Wilford| first = John Noble| title = Feathers Worth a 2nd Look Found on a Tiny Dinosaur| newspaper = The New York Times| location = New York| date = 8 March 2012| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/09/science/feather-cells-tell-of-microraptors-crowlike-sheen.html| accessdate = 22 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Paleobiology==\n===Wings and flight===\n''Microraptor'' had four [[wing]]s, one on each of its forelimbs and hindlimbs, somewhat resembling one possible arrangement of the quartet of flight surfaces on a [[tandem wing]] aircraft of today. It had long [[pennaceous feather]]s on arms and hands {{convert|10|\u2013|20|cm|in|adj=mid|long|abbr=on}} with legs and feet {{convert|11|\u2013|15|cm|in|adj=mid|long|abbr=on}}. The long feathers on the legs of ''Microraptor'' were true flight feathers as seen in modern [[bird]]s, with asymmetrical vanes on the arm, leg, and tail feathers. As in modern bird wings, ''Microraptor'' had both primary (anchored to the hand) and secondary (anchored to the arm) flight feathers. This standard wing pattern was mirrored on the hindlegs, with [[flight feather]]s anchored to the upper foot bones as well as the upper and lower leg. Though not apparent in most fossils under natural light, due to obstruction from decayed soft tissue, the feather bases extended close to or in contact with the bones, as in modern birds, providing strong anchor points.<ref name=hone2010>{{cite journal | last1 = Hone | first1 = D.W.E. | last2 = Tischlinger | first2 = H. | last3 = Xu | first3 = X. | last4 = Zhang | first4 = F. | year = 2010 | title = The extent of the preserved feathers on the four-winged dinosaur ''Microraptor gui'' under ultraviolet light | journal = PLOS One | volume = 5 | issue = 2| page = e9223 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0009223 | pmid=20169153 | pmc=2821398 | bibcode = 2010PLoSO...5.9223H }}</ref>\n\nIt was originally thought that ''Microraptor'' was a [[Gliding flight|glider]], and probably lived mainly in trees, because the hindwings anchored to the feet of ''Microraptor'' would have hindered their ability to run on the ground.<ref name=\"Xuetal2003\">Xu, X., Zhou, Z., Wang, X., Kuang, X., Zhang, F. and Du, X. (2003). \"Four-winged dinosaurs from China.\" ''Nature'', '''421'''(6921): 335-340, 23 Jan 2003.</ref> Some paleontologists have suggested that feathered dinosaurs used their wings to parachute from trees, possibly to attack or ambush prey on the ground, as a precursor to gliding or true flight.<ref name=\"benson2012\"/> In their 2007 study, Chatterjee and Templin tested this hypothesis as well, and found that the combined wing surface of ''Microraptor'' was too narrow to successfully parachute to the ground without injury from any significant height. However, the authors did leave open the possibility that ''Microraptor'' could have parachuted short distances, as between closely spaced tree branches.<ref name=\"chatterjee2007\"/><ref name=\"benson2012\">{{cite book|authors=Benson, R.B.J. & Brussatte, S.|year=2012|title=Prehistoric Life|location=London|publisher=Dorling Kindersley|page=332|isbn=978-0-7566-9910-9}}</ref> Wind tunnel experiments have demonstrated that sustaining a high-lift coefficient at the expense of high drag was likely the most efficient strategy for ''Microraptor'' when gliding between low elevations. ''Microraptor'' did not require a sophisticated, 'modern' wing morphology to be an effective glider.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Dyke | first1 = Gareth | last2 = de Kat | first2 = Roeland | last3 = Palmer | first3 = Colin | last4 = van der Kindere | first4 = Jacques | last5 = Naish | first5 = Darren | last6 = Ganapathisubramani | first6 = Bharathram | year = 2013 | title = Aerodynamic performance of the feathered dinosaur Microraptor and the evolution of feathered flight | url = | journal = Nature Communications | volume = 4 | issue = | page = 2489 | doi = 10.1038/ncomms3489 | pmid = 24048346 | bibcode = 2013NatCo...4.2489D }}</ref> However, the idea that ''Microraptor'' was an arboreal glider relies on it to have regularly climbed or even lived in trees, when study of its anatomy have shown that its limb proportions fall in line with modern ground birds rather than climbers, and its skeleton shows none of the expected adaptations in animals specialized for climbing trees.<ref name=Dececchi_etal_2016>{{cite journal | last1 = Dececchi | first1 = T.A. | last2 = Larsson | first2 = H.C.E. | last3 = Habib | first3 = M.B. | year = 2016 | title = The wings before the bird: an evaluation of flapping-based locomotory hypotheses in bird antecedents | journal = PeerJ | volume = 4 | issue = | page = e2159 | doi = 10.7717/peerj.2159 | pmid=27441115 | pmc=4941780}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Microraptor gui holotype under UV light.png|thumb|''M. gui'' [[holotype]] under two different UV light filters, revealing extent of preserved feathers and soft tissue]]\nDescribing specimens originally referenced as a distinctive species (''Cryptovolans pauli''), paleontologist Stephen Czerkas argued ''Microraptor'' may have been a powered flier, and indeed possibly a better flyer than ''[[Archaeopteryx]]''. He noted that the ''Microraptor's'' fused sternum, asymmetrical feathers, and features of the shoulder girdle indicated that it could fly under its own power, rather than merely gliding. Today, most scientists agree that ''Microraptor'' had the anatomical features expected of a flying animal, though it would have been a less advanced form of flight compared to birds. For example, some studies suggest the shoulder joint was too primitive to allow a full flapping flight stroke. In the ancestral anatomy of theropod dinosaurs, the shoulder socket faced downward and slightly backward, making it impossible for the animals to raise their arms vertically, a prerequisite for the flapping flight stroke in birds. Studies of maniraptoran anatomy have suggested that the shoulder socket did not shift into the bird-like position of a high, upward orientation close to the [[vertebra]]l column until relatively advanced avialans like the [[enantiornithes]] appeared.<ref name=senter2006>{{cite journal | last1 = Senter | first1 = P | year = 2006 | title = Scapular orientation in theropods and basal birds, and the origin of flapping flight | url = | journal = Acta Palaeontol. Pol. | volume = 51 | issue = | pages = 305\u2013313 }}</ref> However, other scientists have argued that the shoulder girdle in some [[Paraves|paravian]] theropods, including ''Microraptor'', is curved in such a way that the shoulder joint could only have been positioned high on the back, allowing for a nearly vertical upstroke of the wing. This possibly advanced shoulder anatomy, combined with the presence of a [[Patagium|propatagium]] linking the wrist to the shoulder (which fills the space in front of the flexed wing and may support the wing against drag in modern birds) and an [[alula]], much like a \"thumb-like\" form of [[leading edge slot]], may indicate that ''Microraptor'' was capable of true, powered flight.<ref name=avianancestry>{{Cite journal|author1=Federico L. Agnol\u00edn |author2=Fernando E. Novas |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2013 |title=Avian ancestors. A review of the phylogenetic relationships of the theropods Unenlagiidae, Microraptoria, ''Anchiornis'' and Scansoriopterygidae |journal=SpringerBriefs in Earth System Sciences |volume= |issue= |pages=1\u201396 |doi=10.1007/978-94-007-5637-3 |isbn=978-94-007-5636-6 }}</ref>\n\nOther studies have demonstrated that the wings of ''Microraptor'' were large enough to generate the lift necessary for powered launching into flight even without a fully vertical flight stroke. A 2016 study of incipient flight ability in paravians demonstrated that ''Microraptor'' was capable of [[wing-assisted incline running]], as well as wing-assisted leaping and even ground-based launching.<ref name=Dececchi_etal_2016/>\n\nStephen Czerkas, Gregory S. Paul, and others have argued that the fact ''Microraptor'' could fly and yet is also very clearly a dromaeosaurid suggests that the [[Dromaeosauridae]], including later and larger species such as ''[[Deinonychus]]'', were secondarily flightless. The work of Xu and colleagues also suggested that the ancestors of dromaeosaurids were probably small, arboreal, and capable of [[Gliding flight|gliding]], although later discoveries of more primitive dromaeosaurids with short forelimbs unsuitable for gliding have cast doubt on this view.<ref name=\"Xuetal2003\"/><ref name=Turneretal07>{{cite journal | last1 = Turner | first1 = Alan H. | last2 = Pol | first2 = Diego | last3 = Clarke | first3 = Julia A. | last4 = Erickson | first4 = Gregory M. | last5 = Norell | first5 = Mark | year = 2007 | title = A basal dromaeosaurid and size evolution preceding avian flight | url = | journal = Science | volume = 317 | issue = 5843| pages = 1378\u20131381 | doi = 10.1126/science.1144066 | pmid = 17823350 | bibcode = 2007Sci...317.1378T }}</ref> Work done on the question of flight ability in other paravians, however, showed that most of them probably would not have been able to achieve enough lift for powered flight, given their limited flight strokes and relatively smaller wings. These studies concluded that ''Microraptor'' probably evolved flight and its associated features (fused sternum, alula, etc.) independently of the ancestors of birds.<ref name=Dececchi_etal_2016/>\n\n===Hindwing posture===\n[[File:Microraptor models.png|thumb|Wind tunnel experiments with different wing configurations]]\n[[Sankar Chatterjee]] suggested in 2005 that, in order for ''Microraptor'' to [[Gliding flight|glide]] or fly, the forewings and hindwings must have been on different levels (as on a [[biplane]]) and not overlaid (as on a [[dragonfly]]), and that the latter posture would have been anatomically impossible. Using this biplane model, Chatterjee was able to calculate possible methods of gliding, and determined that ''Microraptor'' most likely employed a ''[[phugoid]]'' style of gliding: launching itself from a perch, the animal would have swooped downward in a deep U-shaped curve and then lifted again to land on another tree. The feathers not directly employed in the biplane [[wing]] structure, like those on the [[tibia]] and the [[tail]], could have been used to control drag and alter the [[Airway (aviation)|flight path]], [[trajectory]], etc. The orientation of the hindwings would also have helped the animal control its gliding flight. Chatterjee also used computer [[algorithm]]s that test [[Flying and gliding animals|animal flight]] capacity to test whether or not ''Microraptor'' was capable of true, powered flight, as opposed to or in addition to passive gliding. The resulting data showed that ''Microraptor'' did have the requirements to sustain level powered flight, so it is theoretically possible that the animal flew, as opposed to gliding.<ref name=\"chatterjee2007\">{{cite journal | last1 = Chatterjee | first1 = S. | last2 = Templin | first2 = R.J. | year = 2007 | title = Biplane wing planform and flight performance of the feathered dinosaur ''Microraptor gui'' | url = http://www.pnas.org/cgi/reprint/0609975104v1.pdf | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences | volume = 104 | issue = 5| pages = 1576\u20131580 | doi=10.1073/pnas.0609975104 | pmid=17242354 | pmc=1780066| bibcode = 2007PNAS..104.1576C }}</ref>\n\nSome paleontologists have doubted the biplane hypothesis, and have proposed other configurations. A 2010 study by Alexander ''et al.'' described the construction of a lightweight three-dimensional physical model used to perform glide tests. Using several hindleg configurations for the model, they found that the biplane model, while not unreasonable, was structurally deficient and needed a heavy-headed weight distribution for stable gliding, which they deemed unlikely. The study indicated that a laterally abducted hindwing structure represented the most biologically and aerodynamically consistent configuration for ''Microraptor''.<ref name=alexanderetal2010>{{cite journal | last1 = Alexander | first1 = D.E. | last2 = Gong | first2 = E. | last3 = Martin | first3 = L.D. | last4 = Burnham | first4 = D.A. | last5 = Falk | first5 = A.R. | year = 2010 | title = Model tests of gliding with different hindwing configurations in the four-winged dromaeosaurid ''Microraptor gui'' | url = | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA | volume = 107 | issue = 7| pages = 2972\u20132976 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0911852107 | pmid = 20133792 | bibcode = 2010PNAS..107.2972A | pmc = 2840342 }}</ref> A further analysis by Brougham and Brusatte, however, concluded that Alexander's model reconstruction was not consistent with all of the available data on ''Microraptor'' and argued that the study was insufficient for determining a likely flight pattern for ''Microraptor''. Brougham and Brusatte criticized the anatomy of the model used by Alexander and his team, noting that the hip anatomy was not consistent with other dromaeosaurs. In most dromaeosaurids, features of the hip bone prevent the legs from splaying horizontally; instead, they are locked in a vertical position below the body. Alexander's team used a specimen of ''Microraptor'' which was crushed flat to make their model, which Brougham and Brusatte argued did not reflect its actual anatomy.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Brusatte | first1 = Stephen L. | last2 = Brougham | first2 = Jason | year = 2010| title = Distorted ''Microraptor'' specimen is not ideal for understanding the origin of avian flight | url = | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA | volume = 107| issue = 40| pages = E155| doi = 10.1073/pnas.1004977107 | pmid = 20864633 | bibcode = 2010PNAS..107E.155B| pmc = 2951411}}</ref> Later in 2010, Alexander's team responded to these criticisms, noting that the related dromaeosaur ''[[Hesperonychus]]'', which is known from complete hip bones preserved in three dimensions, also shows hip sockets directed partially upward, possibly allowing the legs to splay more than in other dromaeosaurs.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Alexander | first1 = D.E. | last2 = Gong | first2 = E. | last3 = Martin | first3 = L.D. | last4 = Burnham | first4 = D.A. | last5 = Falk | first5 = A.R. | year = 2010 | title = Reply to Brougham and Brusatte: Overall anatomy confirms posture and flight model offers insight into the evolution of bird flight | url = | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA | volume = 107| issue = 40| pages = E155| doi = 10.1073/pnas.1004977107 | pmid = 20864633 | bibcode = 2010PNAS..107E.155B | pmc = 2951411 }}</ref>\n\n===Ground movement===\n[[File:Microraptor by durbed.jpg|thumb|Restoration of two individuals by the ground]]\nDue to the extent of the hindwings onto most of the animal's foot, many scientists have suggested that ''Microraptor'' would have been awkward during normal ground movement or running. The front wing feathers would also have hindered ''Microraptor'' when on the ground, due to the limited range of motion in the wrist and the extreme length of the wing feathers. A 2010 study by Corwin Sullivan and colleagues showed that, even with the wing folded as far as possible, the feathers would still have dragged along the ground if the arms were held in a neutral position, or extended forward as in a predatory strike. Only by keeping the wings elevated, or the upper arm extended fully backward, could ''Microraptor'' have avoided damaging the wing feathers. Therefore, it may have been anatomically impossible for ''Microraptor'' to have used its clawed forelimbs in capturing prey or manipulating objects.<ref name=sullivanetal2010>{{cite journal | last1 = Sullivan | first1 = C. | last2 = Hone | first2 = D.W.E. | last3 = Xu | first3 = X. | last4 = Zhang | first4 = F. | year = 2010 | title = The asymmetry of the carpal joint and the evolution of wing folding in maniraptoran theropod dinosaurs | url = | journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society B | volume = 277 | issue = 1690| pages = 2027\u20132033 | doi = 10.1098/rspb.2009.2281 | pmid = 20200032 | pmc = 2880093 }}</ref>\n\n===Implications===\n[[File:Tetrapteryx.jpg|thumb|left|[[William Beebe]]'s hypothetical \"''Tetrapteryx''\" with four wings, 1915]]\nThe unique wing arrangement found in ''Microraptor'' raised the question of whether the evolution of flight in modern birds went through a four-winged stage, or whether four-winged gliders like ''Microraptor'' were an evolutionary side-branch that left no descendants. As early as 1915, [[Natural history|naturalist]] [[William Beebe]] had argued that the evolution of bird flight may have gone through a four-winged (or ''tetrapteryx'') stage.<ref name=\"beebe1915\">{{cite journal | last1 = Beebe | first1 = C. W. A. | year = 1915 | title = Tetrapteryx stage in the ancestry of birds | url = | journal = Zoologica | volume = 2 | issue = | pages = 38\u201352 }}</ref> Chatterjee and Templin did not take a strong stance on this possibility, noting that both a conventional interpretation and a tetrapteryx stage are equally possible. However, based on the presence of unusually long leg feathers in various feathered dinosaurs, ''[[Archaeopteryx]]'', and some modern birds such as raptors, as well as the discovery of further dinosaur with long primary feathers on their feet (such as ''[[Pedopenna]]''), the authors argued that the current body of evidence, both from morphology and phylogeny, suggests that bird flight did shift at some point from shared limb dominance to front-limb dominance, and that all modern birds may have evolved from four-winged ancestors, or at least ancestors with unusually long leg feathers relative to the modern configuration.<ref name=\"chatterjee2007\"/>\n\n===Feeding===\n[[File:Microraptor gui cast.jpg|thumb|Close-up of a cast]]\nIn 2010 researchers announced that further preparation of the type fossil of ''M. zhaoianus'' revealed preserved probable gut contents. These consisted of mammalian bones, including possible skull, limb, and vertebral fragments and also a whole foot. The foot skeleton is similar to those of ''[[Eomaia]]'' and ''[[Sinodelphys]]''. It corresponds to an animal with an estimated snout to vent length of {{cvt|80|mm}} and a mass of {{cvt|20|\u2013|25|g}}. The unguals of the foot are less curved than in ''Eomaia'' or ''Sinodelphys'', indicating that the mammal could climb but less effectively than in the two latter genera.<ref name=\"Larsson et al. 2010\">Larsson, Hans, Hone, David, Dececchi, T. Alexander, Sullivan, Corwin, Xu, Xing. \"THE WINGED NON-AVIAN DINOSAUR MICRORAPTOR FED ON MAMMALS: IMPLICATIONS FOR THE JEHOL BIOTA ECOSYSTEM\" \"Program and Abstracts. 70th Anniversary Meeting Society of Vertebrate Paleontology October 2010\" 114A.</ref>\n\nIn the December 6, 2011 issue of ''Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences'', Jingmai O'Connor and coauthors described a ''Microraptor'' specimen containing bird bones in its abdomen, specifically a partial wing and feet. Their position indicate that the dinosaur swallowed a tree-perching bird whole.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Jingmai O'Connor |author2=Zhonghe Zhou |author3=Xing Xu |last-author-amp=yes |year=2011 |title=Additional specimen of ''Microraptor'' provides unique evidence of dinosaurs preying on birds |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America |volume=108 |issue=49 |pages=19662\u201319665 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1117727108 |url=http://www.pnas.org/content/108/49/19662.abstract |pmid=22106278 |pmc=3241752|bibcode=2011PNAS..10819662O }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 researchers announced that they had found fish scales in the abdominal cavity of a ''Microraptor'' specimen.<ref name=Xing13>{{cite journal |author=Lida Xing|year=2013 |title=Piscivory in the feathered dinosaur ''Microraptor'' |journal=Evolution|doi=10.1111/evo.12119|display-authors=etal |volume=67 |issue=8 |pages=2441\u20132445 |pmid=23888864}}</ref> This new finding corrects the previous position that ''Microraptor'' hunted only in an arboreal environment. They also argued that the specimen showed a probable adaptation to a fish-eating diet: the good preservation of the mandible shows that the first three teeth were inclined anterodorsally, a character often associated with piscivory.<ref name=Xing13/> ''Microraptor'' was an opportunistic feeder, hunting the most common prey in both arboreal and aquatic habitats.<ref name=Xing13/>\n\nIn 2019, a new genus of [[Scleroglossa|scleroglossan]] [[lizard]] (''[[Indrasaurus]]'') was described from a specimen found in the stomach of a ''Microraptor''. The ''Microraptor'' apparently swallowed its prey head first, a behavior typical of modern [[Carnivore|carnivorous]] [[Bird|birds]] and lizards. The ''Indrasaurus'' bones lacked marked pitting and scarring, indicating that the ''Microraptor'' died shortly after eating the lizard and before significant digestion had occurred.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhou|first=Zhonghe|last2=Zhang|first2=Xiaomei|last3=Wang|first3=Yan|last4=Wang|first4=Xiaoli|last5=Dong|first5=Liping|last6=Zheng|first6=Xiaoting|last7=O\u2019Connor|first7=Jingmai|date=2019-07-11|title=Microraptor with Ingested Lizard Suggests Non-specialized Digestive Function|url=https://www.cell.com/current-biology/abstract/S0960-9822(19)30713-4|journal=Current Biology|language=English|volume=0|issue=14|pages=2423\u20132429.e2|doi=10.1016/j.cub.2019.06.020|issn=0960-9822|pmid=31303494}}</ref>\n\nUnlike its fellow [[Paraves|paravian]] ''[[Anchiornis]]'', ''Microraptor'' has never been found with [[Pellet (ornithology)|gastric pellets]], despite the existence of four ''Microraptor'' specimens that preserve stomach contents. This suggests that ''Microraptor'' passed indigestible fur, feathers, and bits of bone in its droppings instead of producing pellets.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBased on the size of the [[Sclerotic ring|scleral ring]] of the eye, it has been suggested ''Microraptor'' hunted at night.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Nocturnality in dinosaurs inferred from scleral ring and orbit morphology|vauthors=Schmitz L, Motani R | journal=Science| year=2011| doi=10.1126/science.1200043| pmid=21493820| volume=332 | issue=6030 | pages=705\u20138| bibcode=2011Sci...332..705S}}</ref> However, the discovery of iridescent plumage in ''Microraptor'' has cast doubt on this conclusion, as no modern birds that have iridescent plumage are known to be nocturnal.<ref name=\"iridescence\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n===Naming controversy===\n{{Main|Archaeoraptor}}\n[[File:Archaeoraptor-Paleozoological Museum of China.jpg|alt=|thumb|The \"[[Archaeoraptor]]\" fossil; the tail belongs to ''Microraptor'']]\nThe initial naming of ''Microraptor'' was controversial, because of the unusual circumstances of its first description. The first specimen to be described was part of a chimeric specimen\u2014a patchwork of different feathered dinosaur species (''Microraptor'' itself, ''Yanornis'' and an as-of-yet undescribed third species) assembled from multiple specimens in China and smuggled to the USA for [[Fossil collecting|sale]]. After the forgery was revealed by [[Xu Xing (paleontologist)|Xu Xing]] of [[Beijing]]'s [[Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology]], [[Storrs L. Olson]], curator of birds in the [[National Museum of Natural History]] of the [[Smithsonian Institution]], published a description of the Microraptor's tail in an obscure journal, giving it the name ''Archaeoraptor liaoningensis'' in an attempt to remove the name from the paleornithological record by assigning it to the part least likely to be a bird.<ref name=\"olson2000\">Olson, S.L. (2000). \"Countdown to Piltdown at ''National Geographic'': the rise and fall of ''Archaeoraptor''.\" ''Backbone'', '''13'''(2) (April): 1\u20133.</ref> However, Xu had discovered the remainder of the specimen from which the tail had been taken and published a description of it later that year, giving it the name ''Microraptor zhaoianus''.<ref name=\"Xu2000\">Xu, X., Zhou, Z., and Wang, X. (2000). \"The smallest known non-avian theropod dinosaur.\" ''Nature'', '''408''' (December): 705-708.{{cite web |url=http://research.amnh.org/%7Esunny/microraptor.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-12-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217154907/http://research.amnh.org/%7Esunny/microraptor.pdf |archivedate=2008-12-17 }}</ref>\n\nSince the two names designate the same individual as the [[Type (biology)|type]] specimen, ''Microraptor zhaoianus'' would have been a [[junior objective synonym]] of ''Archaeoraptor liaoningensis'' and the latter, if valid, would have had priority under the [[International Code of Zoological Nomenclature]]. However, there is some doubt whether Olson in fact succeeded in meeting all the formal requirements for establishing a new taxon. Namely, Olson designated the specimen as a [[lectotype]], before an actual type species was formally erected.<ref name=dmlarchaeoraptor>Creisler, B. (2002). \"[http://dml.cmnh.org/2001Jan/msg00092.html Archaeoraptor still a nomen nudum].\" Message to the Dinosaur Mailing List, 4 Jan 2001. accessed 23 Sep 2009.</ref> A similar situation arose with ''[[Tyrannosaurus rex]]'' and ''Manospondylus gigas'', in which the former became a ''nomen protectum'' and the latter a ''nomen oblitum'' due to revisions in the ICZN rules that took place on December 31, 1999.<ref name=\"sowhyhasn\">Taylor, M. (2002). \"[http://www.miketaylor.org.uk/dino/faq/s-class/priority/].\" So why hasn't ''Tyrannosaurus'' been renamed ''Massospondylus''?, 27 Aug 2002. accessed 30 Sept 2014.</ref> In addition, Xu's name for the type specimen (''Microraptor'') was subsequently used more frequently than the original name; as such, this and the chimeric nature of the specimen would render the name \"Archaeoraptor\" a ''nomen vanum'' (as it was improperly described) and the junior synonym ''Microraptor'' a ''nomen protectum'' (as it's been used in more published works than \"Archaeoraptor\" and was properly described).<ref name=dmlarchaeoraptorvmicroraptor>Williams, T. (2002). \"[http://dml.cmnh.org/2001Jan/msg00020.html Archaeoraptor v Microraptor].\" Message to the Dinosaur Mailing List, 1 Jan 2001. accessed 30 Sept 2014.</ref>\n\n===Additional specimens===\n[[File:Microraptor Skeletons by Qilong.jpg|thumb|Skeletal restorations of various specimens]]\nThe first specimen referred to ''Microraptor'' represented a small individual and included faint feather remnants, but was otherwise not well preserved and lacked a skull.\nIn 2002 [[Mark Norell]] et al. described another specimen, BPM 1 3-13, which they did not name or refer to an existing species.<ref name=\"norelletal02\">Norell, Mark, Ji, Qiang, Gao, Keqin, Yuan, Chongxi, Zhao, Yibin, Wang, Lixia. (2002). \"'Modern' feathers on a non-avian dinosaur\". ''Nature'', 416: pp. 36. 7 March 2002.></ref> Later that year [[Stephen Czerkas]] et al. named the specimen ''Cryptovolans pauli'', and referred two additional specimens (the first to show well-preserved feathers) to this species. The generic name was derived from Greek ''kryptos'', \"hidden\", and [[Latin]] ''volans'', \"flying\". The [[specific name (zoology)|specific name]], ''pauli'', honors [[Paleontology|paleontologist]] [[Gregory S. Paul]], who had long proposed that dromaeosaurids evolved from flying ancestors.<ref name=\"Czerkas2002\"/>\n\nThe [[type specimen]]s of ''C. pauli'' were collected from the [[Jiufotang Formation]], dating from the early [[Albian]] and now belong to the collection of the Paleontology Museum of Beipiao, in [[Liaoning]], China. They are referred to by the inventory numbers LPM 0200, the [[holotype]]; LPM 0201, its counterslab (slab and counterslab together represent the earlier BPM 1 3-13); and the [[paratype]] LPM 0159, a smaller skeleton. Both individuals are preserved as articulated compression fossils; they are reasonably complete but partially damaged.<ref name=\"Czerkas2002\"/>\n[[File:Microraptor-Beijing Museum of Natural History.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|Specimen at the [[Beijing Museum of Natural History]]]]\nCzerkas ''et al.'' (2002) diagnosed the genus on the basis of having primary feathers (which in the authors' opinion made it a [[bird]]), a co-ossified sternum, a tail consisting of 28 to 30 vertebrae and a third finger with a short phalanx III-3.<ref name=\"Czerkas2002\"/> Some of the feathers Czerkas described as primary were actually attached to the leg, rather than the arm. This, along with most of the other diagnostic characters, is also present in the genus ''Microraptor'', which was first described earlier than ''Cryptovolans''.<ref name=\"Xuetal03\">{{cite journal | last1 = Xu | first1 = Xing | last2 = Zhou | first2 = Zhinghe | last3 = Wang | first3 = Xiaolin | last4 = KUang | first4 = Xuewen | last5 = Zhang | first5 = Fucheng | last6 = Du | first6 = Xiangke | year = 2003 | title = Four-winged dinosaurs from China | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 421 | issue = 6921| pages = 335\u2013340 | doi=10.1038/nature01342 | pmid=12540892| bibcode = 2003Natur.421..335X }}</ref> However, BPM 1 3-13 has a longer tail, proportionately, than other ''Microraptor'' specimens that had been described by 2002, which have 24 to 26 tail vertebrae.<ref name=\"norelletal02\"/>\n\nSubsequent studies (and more specimens of ''Microraptor'') have shown that the features used to distinguish ''Cryptovolans'' are not unique, but are present to varying degrees across various specimens. In a review by Phil Senter and colleagues in 2004, the scientists suggested that all these features represented individual variation across various age groups of a single ''Microraptor'' species, making the name ''Cryptovolans pauli'' and ''Microraptor gui'' junior synonyms of ''Microraptor zhaoianus''.<ref name=\"senteretal2004\"/> Many other researchers, including Alan Feduccia and Tom Holtz, have since supported its synonymy.<ref name=\"Holtz2008\"/><ref name=FLH05>{{cite journal|last=Feduccia |first=A. |year=2005 |title=Do feathered dinosaurs exist? Testing the hypothesis on neontological and paleontological evidence |journal=Journal of Morphology |volume=266 |issue=2 |pages=125\u2013166 |pmid=16217748 |doi=10.1002/jmor.10382|last2=Lingham-Soliar|first2=T|last3=Hinchliffe|first3=JR}}</ref>\n\nA new specimen of ''Microraptor'', BMNHC PH881, showed several features previously unknown in the animal, including the probably glossy-black iridescent plumage coloration. The new specimen also featured a bifurcated tailfan, similar in shape to previously known ''Microraptor'' tailfans except sporting a pair of long, narrow feathers at the center of the fan. The new specimen also showed no sign of the nuchal crest, indicating that the crest inferred from the holotype specimen may be an artifact of [[taphonomy|taphonomic]] distortion.<ref name=\"iridescence\"/><ref name=\"iridescence2\"/>\n\nNumerous further specimens likely belonging to ''Microraptor'' have been uncovered, all from the Shangheshou Bed of the [[Jiufotang Formation]] in Liaoning, China. In fact, ''Microraptor'' is the most abundant non-avialan dinosaur fossil type found in this formation.<ref name=\"xu&norell2006\">{{cite journal | last1 = Xu | first1 = X. | last2 = Norell | first2 = M.A. | year = 2006 | title = Non-Avian dinosaur fossils from the Lower Cretaceous Jehol Group of western Liaoning, China | doi = 10.1002/gj.1044 | journal = Geological Journal | volume = 41 | issue = 3\u20134| pages = 419\u2013437 }}</ref> In 2010, it was reported that there were over 300 undescribed specimens attributable to ''Microraptor'' or its close relatives among the collections of several Chinese museums, though many had been altered or composited by private fossil collectors.<ref name=alexanderetal2010/>\n\n===Study and debate===\n[[File:Microraptor zhaoianus.jpg|thumb|upright|Fossil specimen]]\nNorell ''et al.'' (2002) described BPM 1 3-13 as the first dinosaur known to have flight feathers on its legs as well as on its arms.<ref name=\"Norelletal02\">{{cite journal | last1 = Norell | first1 = Mark | last2 = Ji | first2 = Qiang | last3 = Gao | first3 = Keqin | last4 = Yuan | first4 = Chongxi | last5 = Zhao | first5 = Yibin | last6 = Wang | first6 = Lixia | year = 2002 | title = 'Modern' feathers on a non-avian dinosaur | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 416 | issue = 6876| pages = 36\u20137 | doi=10.1038/416036a| pmid = 11882883 | bibcode = 2002Natur.416...36N }}</ref>\n\nCzerkas (2002) mistakenly described the fossil as having no long feathers on its legs, but only on its hands and arms, as he illustrated on the cover of his book ''Feathered Dinosaurs and the Origin of Flight''.<ref name=\"Czerkas2002\">Czerkas, Sylvia J. ed. (2002) \"Feathered Dinosaurs and the Origin of Flight\" The Dinosaur Museum Journal Volume 1. Blanding, Utah, USA. The Dinosaur Museum, August 1, 2002</ref> In his discussion of ''Cryptovolans'' in this book, Czerkas strongly denounces Norell's conclusions; \"''The misinterpretation of the primary wing feathers as being from the hind legs stems directly to'' [sic] ''seeing what one believes and wants to see''\".<ref name=\"Czerkas2002\"/> Czerkas also denounced Norell for failing to conclude that [[Dromaeosauridae|dromaeosaurs]] are birds, accusing him of succumbing to \"''...the blinding influences of preconceived ideas.''\"<ref name=\"Czerkas2002\"/> The [[crown group]] definition of Aves, as a subset of [[Avialae]], the explicit definition of the term \"bird\" that Norell employs, would definitely exclude BPM 1 3-13. However, he does not consider the specimen to belong to Avialae either.<ref name=\"Norelletal02\"/>\n\nCzerkas's interpretation of the hindleg feathers noted by Norell proved to be incorrect the following year, when additional specimens of ''Microraptor'' were published by Xu and colleagues, showing a distinctive \"hindwing\" completely separate from the forelimb wing. The first of these specimens was discovered in 2001, and between 2001 and 2003 four more specimens were bought from private collectors by Xu's museum, the [[Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology]]. Xu also considered these specimens, most of which had hindwings and proportional differences from the original ''Microraptor'' specimen, to be a new species, which he named ''Microraptor gui''. However, Senter also questioned this classification, noting that as with ''Cryptovolans'', most of the differences appeared to correspond with size, and likely age differences.<ref name=senteretal2004/> Two further specimens, classified as ''M. zhaoianus'' in 2002 (''M. gui'' had not yet been named), have also been described by Hwang and colleagues.<ref name=\"hwangetal2002\"/>\n\nCzerkas also believed that the animal may have been able to fly better than ''[[Archaeopteryx]]'', the animal usually referred to as the earliest known bird. He cited the fused sternum and asymmetrical feathers, and argued that ''Microraptor'' has modern bird features that make it more derived than ''Archaeopteryx''. Czerkas cited the fact that this possibly volant animal is also very clearly a dromaeosaurid to suggest that the [[Dromaeosauridae]] might actually be a basal bird group, and that later, larger, species such as ''[[Deinonychus]]'' were secondarily flightless (Czerkas, 2002). The current consensus is that there is not enough evidence to conclude whether dromaeosaurs descended from an ancestor with some aerodynamic abilities. The work of Xu ''et al.'' (2003) suggested that basal dromaeosaurs were probably small, arboreal, and could glide.<ref name=xuetal2003>{{cite journal | last1 = Xing | first1 = X. | last2 = Zhou | first2 = Z. | last3 = Wang | first3 = X. | last4 = Kuang | first4 = X. | last5 = Zhang | first5 = F. | last6 = Du | first6 = X. | year = 2003 | title = Four-winged dinosaurs from China | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 421 | issue = 6921| pages = 335\u2013340 | bibcode = 2003Natur.421..335X | doi = 10.1038/nature01342 | pmid = 12540892 }}</ref> The work of Turner ''et al.'' (2007) suggested that the ancestral dromaeosaur could not glide or fly, but that there was good evidence that it was small-bodied (around 65 cm long and 600\u2013700&nbsp;g in mass).<ref name=\"Turneretal07\"/>\n\n==Classification==\n[[File:Dromaeosaurs.png|thumb|Size of ''Microraptor'' (1) compared with other [[Dromaeosauridae|dromaeosaurs]]]]\n[[File:Shandong Microraptor.jpg|thumb|Specimen in the Shandong Tianyu Museum of Nature]]\nThe cladogram below follows a 2012 analysis by paleontologists Phil Senter, James I. Kirkland, Donald D. DeBlieux, Scott Madsen and Natalie Toth.<ref name=Yurgovuchia>{{Cite journal | last1 = Senter | first1 = P. | last2 = Kirkland | first2 = J. I. | last3 = Deblieux | first3 = D. D. | last4 = Madsen | first4 = S. | last5 = Toth | first5 = N. | editor1-last = Dodson | editor1-first = Peter | title = New Dromaeosaurids (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Utah, and the Evolution of the Dromaeosaurid Tail | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0036790 | journal = PLOS One | volume = 7 | issue = 5 | pages = e36790 | year = 2012 | pmid = 22615813| pmc = 3352940| bibcode = 2012PLoSO...736790S }}</ref>\n\n{{clade| style=font-size:100%;line-height:100%\n|label1=[[Dromaeosauridae]]\n|1={{clade\n   |1=''[[Xiaotingia]]'' [[File:Xiaotingia .jpg|80px]]\n   |2={{clade\n      |1=[[Unenlagiinae]] [[File:Austroraptor_Restoration_(flipped).png|80px]]\n      |2={{clade\n         |1=''[[Shanag]]'' [[File:Shanag.jpg|80px]]\n         |2={{clade\n            |label1=[[Eudromaeosauria]]\n            |1={{clade\n               |1=[[Saurornitholestinae]] \n               |2={{clade\n                  |1=[[Velociraptorinae]] [[File:Fred Wierum Velociraptor.png|80px]]\n                  |2=[[Dromaeosaurinae]] [[File:Deinonychus_ewilloughby_(flipped).png|80px]] }} }}\n            |label2=[[Microraptoria]]\n            |2={{clade\n               |1=''[[Tianyuraptor]]'' \n               |2={{clade\n                  |1=''[[Hesperonychus]]'' \n                  |2={{clade\n                     |1={{clade\n                        |1='''''Microraptor sp.''''' \n                        |2={{clade\n                           |1='''''Microraptor gui''''' [[File:Fred_Wierum_Microraptor.png|80px]]\n                           |2='''''Microraptor zhaoianus''''' }} }}\n                     |2={{clade\n                        |1=''[[Cryptovolans]]''\n                        |2=''[[Graciliraptor]]'' [[File:Graciliraptor.jpg|80px]]\n                        |3=''[[Sinornithosaurus]]'' [[File:Sinornithosaurus.jpg|80px]] }} }} }} }} }} }} }} }} }}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Dinosaurs}}\n* [[Timeline of dromaeosaurid research]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikispecies|Microraptor}}\n*[[Dromaeosauridae#Relationship with birds|Dromaeosauridae, ''Relationship with birds'']]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040306034207/http://www.indyrad.iupui.edu/public/jrafert/Filipovic/newfeather/Microraptor-gui-%28Cryptovol.jpg A model of ''Microraptor''/Cryptovolans pauli by Boban Filipovic]\n*Jacqui Hayes: [http://www.cosmosmagazine.com/node/984 Bird wings evolved from biplane dinosaurs] COSMOS magazine\n*[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/microraptor/ The Four-Winged Dinosaur] - PBS web site for the ''Nova'' documentary\n*NewScientist [https://www.newscientist.com/articleimages/dn21552/1-microraptors-glossy-black-feather-coat-reconstructed.html Microraptor's glossy black feather coat reconstructed]\n*[http://phenomena.nationalgeographic.com/2012/03/08/a-shiny-dinosaur-four-winged-microraptor-gets-colour-and-gloss/ nationalgeographic.com 2012-03-08 Ed Yong, A shiny dinosaur four-winged Microraptor gets colour and gloss]\n*[http://phenomena.nationalgeographic.com/2008/10/08/microraptor-the-dinosaur-that-flew-like-a-biplane/ nationalgeographic.com 2008-10-08 Ed Yong, Microraptor\u2013the dinosaur that flew like a biplane]\n\n{{Paraves|D.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q310537}}\n\n[[Category:Jiufotang fauna]]\n[[Category:Early Cretaceous dinosaurs of Asia]]\n[[Category:Microraptorians]]\n[[Category:Feathered dinosaurs]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 2000]]\n[[Category:Animal flight]]\n", "name_user": "76.106.109.204", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microraptor"}
{"title_page": "Georgia State University College of Law", "text_new": "{{Infobox Law School\n | image          = [[File:GSU Law Logo.jpg|250px]]\n | name           = Georgia State University College of Law\n | parent         = [[Georgia State University]]\n | established    = 1982<ref name=USNWR/>\n | type           = [[Public university|Public]]\n | endowment      =\n | parent endowment = \n | head           = Leslie Wolf (Interim Dean)<ref>https://news.gsu.edu/2019/05/12/leslie-wolf-named-interim-dean-of-georgia-state-university-college-of-law/</ref>\n | city           = [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]]\n | state          = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n | country        = [[United States|US]]\n | students       = 461 (Full Time)<ref name=USNWR/>\n | faculty        = 52 (Full- and part-time)<ref name=USNWR/>\n | ranking        = 67th (2020)<ref name=USNWR>{{cite web |title=''U.S. News & World Report'', Best Law Schools: Georgia State University |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/georgia-state-university-03040 |accessdate=October 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905165656/http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/law-rankings/page+3 |archivedate=September 5, 2015 }}</ref>\n | bar pass rate  = 85.4%<ref>https://www.gabaradmissions.org/getpdfform.action?id=1661</ref>\n | annual tuition = $15,154 (in-state)/<br>$34,834 (out-of-state)<ref>[https://officialguide.lsac.org/Release/SchoolsABAData/SchoolPage/SchoolPage_Info/ABA_LawSchoolData.aspx?sid=57|GSU College of Law]. Retrieved on 2013-12-18.</ref>\n | homepage       = [https://law.gsu.edu/ GSU College of Law]\n | aba profile    = [https://officialguide.lsac.org/Release/SchoolsABAData/SchoolPage/SchoolPage_Info/ABA_LawSchoolData.aspx?sid=57 GSU College of Law]\n }}\n\nThe '''Georgia State University College of Law''' is a [[law school]] located in downtown [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. Founded in 1982, it is accredited by the [[American Bar Association]] and is a member of the [[Association of American Law Schools]].\n[[File:Georgia State University College of Law Building.jpeg|thumb|300x300px|The new Georgia State University College of Law building located at 85 Park Place in downtown Atlanta.]]\n\nIn addition to the [[Juris Doctor]] degree, the college offers joint degree programs with other colleges at [[Georgia State University]].\n\nThe college offers a full-time and a part-time program. The cost of tuition at GSU Law for the 2018-2019 academic year is $17,050 for residents and $36,659 for non-residents.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/clinical-healthcare-law-rankings|title=U.S. News and World Report Law School Rankings}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAs far back as the early 1970s, Georgia legislators and academic leaders debated  establishing a new law school. The Georgia State University College of Law finally was sanctioned by the state\u2019s Board of Regents in 1981 and [[Ben F. Johnson (Georgia)|Ben F. Johnson]] became its first dean.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.gsu.edu/home/about/history/ben-f-johnson-jr/|title=Ben F. Johnson Jr.|publisher=Georgia State University College of Law}}</ref>\n\nThe college enrolled 200 students in its inaugural year, taught by six professors.  Most students were part-time, and many took classes at night, because they had full-time jobs during the day. The college\u2019s first seven graduates were hooded in December 1984.\n\nBy the end of its first decade, full-time faculty had grown to 31, nearly half of whom were women.\n\n==Rankings==\nGeorgia State University College of Law is currently ranked as the 67th best law school by U.S. News & World Report (2019).<ref name=\":0\" /> The College of Law also boasts a strong Health Law program (currently ranked 2nd nationally) and a large part-time program (ranked 13th nationally).<ref name=\":0\" />  The school is ranked 42nd by [[Above the Law (website)|Above The Law]] using metrics that focus more on student outcomes rather than inputs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abovethelaw.com/law-school-rankings/top-law-schools-2019/#rankings|title=The 2019 ATL Top 50 Law School Rankings|last=|first=|date=|website=Above the Law|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-02-04}}</ref> Additionally, GSU was named by ''[[Princeton Review]]'' in its 2013 edition of The Best 168 Law Schools.<ref>{{cite web|title=2013 Princeton Review Best Law Schools |url=http://law.gsu.edu/news/8289.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121203153900/http://law.gsu.edu/news/8289.html |archivedate=2012-12-03 }}</ref>\n\n==Tuition==\nThe cost of tuition at GSU Law for the 2018-2019 academic year is $17,050 for residents and $36,659 for non-residents.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/clinical-healthcare-law-rankings|title=U.S. News and World Report Law School Rankings}}</ref>\n\n==Admissions==\nIn 2016, incoming  Georgia State law students had a median GPA of 3.41 and a median LSAT score of 158.<ref>[http://law.gsu.edu/admissions/admissions-faq/]</ref>\n\n==Clinical programs==\nThe school has a number of legal clinics, such as the Phillip C. Cook Low-Income Taxpayer Clinic, which serves low-income taxpayers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Phillip C. Cook Low-Income Taxpayer Clinic |url=http://law.gsu.edu/taxclinic/index.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101123945/http://law.gsu.edu/taxclinic/index.html |archivedate=2013-11-01 }}</ref>\n\n==Study abroad==\nThe school operates the Summer Academy in International Commercial Arbitration, a five-week, six-credit hour study abroad program based in Linz, Austria.<ref>{{cite web|title=SAIICA |url=http://law.gsu.edu/students/5009.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130617121948/http://law.gsu.edu/students/5009.html |archivedate=2013-06-17 }}</ref> the Buenos Aires Summer Program in [[Argentina]] (jointly sponsored with the [[Florida International University College of Law]]); and the Summer Legal and Policy Study in [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Summer Legal and Policy - Rio|url=http://law.gsu.edu/metrogrowth/4866.html}}</ref>\n\n== Employment ==\nAccording to Georgia State's official 2018 ABA-required disclosures, 71.5% of the Class of 2018 obtained full-time, long-term, JD-required employment nine months after graduation.<ref>https://law.gsu.edu/files/2019/04/Updated_ABA_Summary_Report_for_Website.pdf</ref> Georgia State's Law School Transparency under-employment score is 13.4%, indicating the percentage of the Class of 2018 unemployed, pursuing an additional degree, or working in a non-professional, short-term, or part-time job nine months after graduation.<ref>https://www.lstreports.com/schools/gsu/</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* Judiciary\n**[[Trea Pipkin|John \"Trea\" Pipkin III]] - Judge, [[Georgia Court of Appeals]]\n**[[Barbara Swinton]], J.D. 1991 - Judge, [[Oklahoma Court of Civil Appeals]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.normantranscript.com/news/government/governor-mary-fallin-selects-judge-barbara-swinton-to-fill-vacancy/article_e0a2e28e-7ac6-11e6-9e95-eb8c6a27df66.html|title=Governor Mary Fallin selects Judge Barbara Swinton to fill vacancy on Oklahoma Civil Appeals Court|last=office|first=Submitted by Governor Mary Fallin's|work=Norman Transcript|access-date=2017-11-08|language=en}}</ref>\n**[[Cynthia J. Becker]], J.D. 1987 - Judge, [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb County]] Superior Court.\n**[[Bill Hamrick]], J.D. 1991 - Superior Court Judge, Coweta Judicial Circuit; former member of the [[Georgia State Senate]] (D-30)\n\n* Politicians\n**[[Glenn Richardson]], J.D. 1984 - Former Speaker of the [[Georgia House of Representatives]] (2005-2010)\n** [[Cynthia Coffman (politician)|Cynthia Coffman]], J.D. 1991 - 38th [[Colorado Attorney General|Attorney General of Colorado]]\n** [[Keisha Lance Bottoms]], J.D. 1996 - 60th [[List of mayors of Atlanta|Mayor of Atlanta]]; former member of the [[Atlanta City Council]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/local/who-atlanta-mayor-elect-keisha-lance-bottoms/RCV7O7QTZsjwktTkQHXsXM/|title=Who is Atlanta mayor-elect Keisha Lance Bottoms?|last=Godwin|first=Becca J. G.|website=ajc|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/local/keisha-lance-bottoms-begins-her-inauguration-day-with-prayer/ckbTRT2kRvUxJXaTs2iVpL/|title=Keisha Lance Bottoms sworn in as the new Mayor of Atlanta|last=Poole|first=Shelia|last2=Stafford|first2=Leon|website=ajc|access-date=2018-01-03}}</ref>\n** [[Steve Tumlin]], J.D. 1988 - Mayor of [[Marietta, Georgia]]\n** [[Curt Thompson]], J.D. 1993 - Former member of the Georgia State Senate (D-5); former member of the Georgia House of Representatives (69th District)\n** [[Rich Golick]], J.D. 1997 - Current member of the Georgia House of Representatives (40th District)\n** [[Trey Kelley]], J.D. 2014 - Current member of the Georgia House of Representatives (16th District)\n** [[Sam Park]], J.D. 2013 - Current member of the Georgia House of Representatives (101st District)\n** [[Matt Ramsey (politician)|Matt Ramsey]], J.D. 2005 - Former member of the Georgia House of Representatives (72nd District); House Majority Whip (2013-2016)\n**[[Stephen Dickson (executive)|Stephen Dickson]] - 18th Administrator of the [[Federal Aviation Administration]]\n**[[Nika Rurua]], J.D. 2001 - Former member of the [[Cabinet of Georgia]] (country)\n\n* Other notable alumni\n**[[Claudia Brind-Woody|Claudia Brind-Woody,]] J.D. 1999 - [[IBM]] executive\n**[[Stan Case]], J.D. 1996 - News anchor of [[CNN Radio]] (1985-2011)\n**[[Jimmy Faircloth]], J.D. 1990 - Lawyer in [[Alexandria, Louisiana|Alexandria]]-[[Pineville, Louisiana|Pineville]], [[Louisiana]], former executive counsel to [[Governor of Louisiana|Governor]] [[Bobby Jindal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.gsu.edu/2009/04/02/jimmy-faircloth-jd-90-executive-counsel-louisiana-governor-speak-april-7/|title=Jimmy Faircloth (JD '90), executive counsel to Louisiana governor, to speak April 7|date=April 2, 2009|publisher=gsu.edu|accessdate=July 20, 2015}}</ref>\n**[[Emily Jacobson]], J.D./MBA 2014 - Olympic saber fencer\n\n*Notable faculty\n** [[Paul A. Lombardo]], Professor of Law - Senior Advisor to the Presidential Commission for the Study of Bioethical Issues\n** [[Thomas W. Thrash, Jr.|Thomas W. Thrash]], Professor of Law (1986-1997) - Judge, United States District Court for the Northern District of Georgia\n\n==See also==\n* [[Georgia State University Law Review]]\n\n==References==\n{{refimprove|date=August 2013}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://law.gsu.edu/ College of Law]\n*[http://law.gsu.edu/academics/ Academic Programs and Centers]\n*[http://www.gsu.edu/ Georgia State University]\n\n{{Georgia State University}}\n{{Law Schools of the Southeast}}\n\n{{coord|33.7519|-84.3855|type:landmark_region:US-GA|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Law schools in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Georgia State University]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Law School\n | image          = [[File:GSU Law Logo.jpg|250px]]\n | name           = Georgia State University College of Law\n | parent         = [[Georgia State University]]\n | established    = 1982<ref name=USNWR/>\n | type           = [[Public university|Public]]\n | endowment      =\n | parent endowment = \n | head           = Leslie Wolf (Interim Dean)<ref>https://news.gsu.edu/2019/05/12/leslie-wolf-named-interim-dean-of-georgia-state-university-college-of-law/</ref>\n | city           = [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]]\n | state          = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n | country        = [[United States|US]]\n | students       = 461 (Full Time)<ref name=USNWR/>\n | faculty        = 52 (Full- and part-time)<ref name=USNWR/>\n | ranking        = 67th (2020)<ref name=USNWR>{{cite web |title=''U.S. News & World Report'', Best Law Schools: Georgia State University |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/georgia-state-university-03040 |accessdate=October 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905165656/http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/law-rankings/page+3 |archivedate=September 5, 2015 }}</ref>\n | bar pass rate  = 85.4%<ref>https://www.gabaradmissions.org/getpdfform.action?id=1661</ref>\n | annual tuition = $15,154 (in-state)/<br>$34,834 (out-of-state)<ref>[https://officialguide.lsac.org/Release/SchoolsABAData/SchoolPage/SchoolPage_Info/ABA_LawSchoolData.aspx?sid=57|GSU College of Law]. Retrieved on 2013-12-18.</ref>\n | homepage       = [https://law.gsu.edu/ GSU College of Law]\n | aba profile    = [https://officialguide.lsac.org/Release/SchoolsABAData/SchoolPage/SchoolPage_Info/ABA_LawSchoolData.aspx?sid=57 GSU College of Law]\n }}\n\nThe '''Georgia State University College of Law''' is a [[law school]] located in downtown [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. Founded in 1982, it is accredited by the [[American Bar Association]] and is a member of the [[Association of American Law Schools]].\n[[File:Georgia State University College of Law Building.jpeg|thumb|300x300px|The new Georgia State University College of Law building located at 85 Park Place in downtown Atlanta.]]\n\nIn addition to the [[Juris Doctor]] degree, the college offers joint degree programs with other colleges at [[Georgia State University]].\n\nThe college offers a full-time and a part-time program. The cost of tuition at GSU Law for the 2018-2019 academic year is $17,050 for residents and $36,659 for non-residents.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/clinical-healthcare-law-rankings|title=U.S. News and World Report Law School Rankings}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAs far back as the early 1970s, Georgia legislators and academic leaders debated  establishing a new law school. The Georgia State University College of Law finally was sanctioned by the state\u2019s Board of Regents in 1981 and [[Ben F. Johnson (Georgia)|Ben F. Johnson]] became its first dean.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.gsu.edu/home/about/history/ben-f-johnson-jr/|title=Ben F. Johnson Jr.|publisher=Georgia State University College of Law}}</ref>\n\nThe college enrolled 200 students in its inaugural year, taught by six professors.  Most students were part-time, and many took classes at night, because they had full-time jobs during the day. The college\u2019s first seven graduates were hooded in December 1984.\n\nBy the end of its first decade, full-time faculty had grown to 31, nearly half of whom were women.\n\n==Rankings==\nGeorgia State University College of Law is currently ranked as the 67th best law school by U.S. News & World Report (2019).<ref name=\":0\" /> The College of Law also boasts a strong Health Law program (currently ranked 2nd nationally) and a large part-time program (ranked 13th nationally).<ref name=\":0\" />  The school is ranked 42nd by [[Above the Law (website)|Above The Law]] using metrics that focus more on student outcomes rather than inputs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abovethelaw.com/law-school-rankings/top-law-schools-2019/#rankings|title=The 2019 ATL Top 50 Law School Rankings|last=|first=|date=|website=Above the Law|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-02-04}}</ref> Additionally, GSU was named by ''[[Princeton Review]]'' in its 2013 edition of The Best 168 Law Schools.<ref>{{cite web|title=2013 Princeton Review Best Law Schools |url=http://law.gsu.edu/news/8289.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121203153900/http://law.gsu.edu/news/8289.html |archivedate=2012-12-03 }}</ref>\n\n==Tuition==\nThe cost of tuition at GSU Law for the 2018-2019 academic year is $17,050 for residents and $36,659 for non-residents.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/clinical-healthcare-law-rankings|title=U.S. News and World Report Law School Rankings}}</ref>\n\n==Admissions==\nIn 2016, incoming  Georgia State law students had a median GPA of 3.41 and a median LSAT score of 158.<ref>[http://law.gsu.edu/admissions/admissions-faq/]</ref>\n\n==Clinical programs==\nThe school has a number of legal clinics, such as the Phillip C. Cook Low-Income Taxpayer Clinic, which serves low-income taxpayers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Phillip C. Cook Low-Income Taxpayer Clinic |url=http://law.gsu.edu/taxclinic/index.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101123945/http://law.gsu.edu/taxclinic/index.html |archivedate=2013-11-01 }}</ref>\n\n==Study abroad==\nThe school operates the Summer Academy in International Commercial Arbitration, a five-week, six-credit hour study abroad program based in Linz, Austria.<ref>{{cite web|title=SAIICA |url=http://law.gsu.edu/students/5009.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130617121948/http://law.gsu.edu/students/5009.html |archivedate=2013-06-17 }}</ref> the Buenos Aires Summer Program in [[Argentina]] (jointly sponsored with the [[Florida International University College of Law]]); and the Summer Legal and Policy Study in [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Summer Legal and Policy - Rio|url=http://law.gsu.edu/metrogrowth/4866.html}}</ref>\n\n== Employment ==\nAccording to Georgia State's official 2018 ABA-required disclosures, 71.5% of the Class of 2018 obtained full-time, long-term, JD-required employment nine months after graduation.<ref>https://law.gsu.edu/files/2019/04/Updated_ABA_Summary_Report_for_Website.pdf</ref> Georgia State's Law School Transparency under-employment score is 13.4%, indicating the percentage of the Class of 2018 unemployed, pursuing an additional degree, or working in a non-professional, short-term, or part-time job nine months after graduation.<ref>https://www.lstreports.com/schools/gsu/</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* Judiciary\n**[[Trea Pipkin|John \"Trea\" Pipkin III]] - Judge, [[Georgia Court of Appeals]]\n**[[Barbara Swinton]], J.D. 1991 - Judge, [[Oklahoma Court of Civil Appeals]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.normantranscript.com/news/government/governor-mary-fallin-selects-judge-barbara-swinton-to-fill-vacancy/article_e0a2e28e-7ac6-11e6-9e95-eb8c6a27df66.html|title=Governor Mary Fallin selects Judge Barbara Swinton to fill vacancy on Oklahoma Civil Appeals Court|last=office|first=Submitted by Governor Mary Fallin's|work=Norman Transcript|access-date=2017-11-08|language=en}}</ref>\n**[[Cynthia J. Becker]], J.D. 1987 - Judge, [[DeKalb County, Georgia|DeKalb County]] Superior Court.\n**[[Bill Hamrick]], J.D. 1991 - Superior Court Judge, Coweta Judicial Circuit; former Georgia State Senator\n\n* Politicians\n**[[Glenn Richardson]], J.D. 1984 - Former Speaker of the [[Georgia House of Representatives]] (2005-2010)\n** [[Cynthia Coffman (politician)|Cynthia Coffman]], J.D. 1991 - 38th [[Colorado Attorney General|Attorney General of Colorado]]\n** [[Keisha Lance Bottoms]], J.D. 1996 - 60th [[List of mayors of Atlanta|Mayor of Atlanta]]; former member of the [[Atlanta City Council]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/local/who-atlanta-mayor-elect-keisha-lance-bottoms/RCV7O7QTZsjwktTkQHXsXM/|title=Who is Atlanta mayor-elect Keisha Lance Bottoms?|last=Godwin|first=Becca J. G.|website=ajc|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/local/keisha-lance-bottoms-begins-her-inauguration-day-with-prayer/ckbTRT2kRvUxJXaTs2iVpL/|title=Keisha Lance Bottoms sworn in as the new Mayor of Atlanta|last=Poole|first=Shelia|last2=Stafford|first2=Leon|website=ajc|access-date=2018-01-03}}</ref>\n** [[Steve Tumlin]], J.D. 1988 - Mayor of [[Marietta, Georgia]]\n** [[Curt Thompson]], J.D. 1993 - Former member of the [[Georgia State Senate]] (D-5); former member of the Georgia House of Representatives (69th District)\n** [[Rich Golick]], J.D. 1997 - Current member of the Georgia House of Representatives (40th District)\n** [[Trey Kelley]], J.D. 2014 - Current member of the Georgia House of Representatives (16th District)\n** [[Sam Park]], J.D. 2013 - Current member of the Georgia House of Representatives (101st District)\n** [[Matt Ramsey (politician)|Matt Ramsey]], J.D. 2005 - Former member of the Georgia House of Representatives (72nd District); House Majority Whip (2013-2016)\n**[[Stephen Dickson (executive)|Stephen Dickson]] - 18th Administrator of the [[Federal Aviation Administration]]\n**[[Nika Rurua]], J.D. 2001 - Former member of the [[Cabinet of Georgia]] (country)\n\n* Other notable alumni\n**[[Claudia Brind-Woody|Claudia Brind-Woody,]] J.D. 1999 - [[IBM]] executive\n**[[Stan Case]], J.D. 1996 - News anchor of [[CNN Radio]] (1985-2011)\n**[[Jimmy Faircloth]], J.D. 1990 - Lawyer in [[Alexandria, Louisiana|Alexandria]]-[[Pineville, Louisiana|Pineville]], [[Louisiana]], former executive counsel to [[Governor of Louisiana|Governor]] [[Bobby Jindal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.gsu.edu/2009/04/02/jimmy-faircloth-jd-90-executive-counsel-louisiana-governor-speak-april-7/|title=Jimmy Faircloth (JD '90), executive counsel to Louisiana governor, to speak April 7|date=April 2, 2009|publisher=gsu.edu|accessdate=July 20, 2015}}</ref>\n**[[Emily Jacobson]], J.D./MBA 2014 - Olympic saber fencer\n\n*Notable faculty\n** [[Paul A. Lombardo]], Professor of Law - Senior Advisor to the Presidential Commission for the Study of Bioethical Issues\n** [[Thomas W. Thrash, Jr.|Thomas W. Thrash]], Professor of Law (1986-1997) - Judge, United States District Court for the Northern District of Georgia\n\n==See also==\n* [[Georgia State University Law Review]]\n\n==References==\n{{refimprove|date=August 2013}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://law.gsu.edu/ College of Law]\n*[http://law.gsu.edu/academics/ Academic Programs and Centers]\n*[http://www.gsu.edu/ Georgia State University]\n\n{{Georgia State University}}\n{{Law Schools of the Southeast}}\n\n{{coord|33.7519|-84.3855|type:landmark_region:US-GA|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Law schools in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Georgia State University]]\n", "name_user": "Shapsam19", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georgia_State_University_College_of_Law"}
{"title_page": "Jimmy Greaves", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Jimmy Greaves\n| image          = Jimmy Greaves 2007.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = Greaves in 2007\n| fullname       = James Peter Greaves\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1940|2|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Manor Park, London|Manor Park]], England\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=8}}<ref>{{cite web|title=James Peter Greaves|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersG/BioGreavesJP.html|work=englandfootballonline.com|accessdate=2 April 2014}}</ref>\n| position       = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| youthyears1    = 1955\u20131957| youthclubs1 = [[Chelsea F.C. Reserves and Academy|Chelsea]]\n| years1         = 1957\u20131961| clubs1 = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]                    | caps1 = 157| goals1 = 124\n| years2         = 1961     | clubs2 = [[A.C. Milan]]                              | caps2 =  12| goals2 = 9\n| years3         = 1961\u20131970| clubs3 = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]| caps3 = 321| goals3 = 220\n| years4         = 1970\u20131971| clubs4 = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]    | caps4 =  38| goals4 = 13\n| years5         = 1975\u20131976| clubs5 = [[Brentwood Town F.C.|Brentwood]]           | caps5 =    | goals5 = \n| years6         = 1976\u20131977| clubs6 = [[Chelmsford City F.C.|Chelmsford City]]    | caps6 =  38<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.chelmsfordcityfc.com/news/throwbackthursday-a-series-of-clarets-players-pict-1738225.html|title=#ThrowbackThursday: A series of Clarets players, pictures, programmes and collectables|publisher=Chelmsford City F.C.|date=5 January 2017|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref> | goals6 = 20\n| years7         = 1977\u20131979| clubs7 = [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]]                      | caps7 =    | goals7 = \n| years8         = 1979\u20131980| clubs8 = [[Woodford Town F.C.|Woodford Town]]        | caps8 =    | goals8 = \n| totalcaps      = 566| totalgoals = 386\n| nationalyears1 = 1957\u20131962<ref name=\"u23\">{{cite web|title=England - U-23 International Results- Details |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng-u23-intres-det.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040413100658/http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng-u23-intres-det.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 April 2004 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |accessdate=1 March 2015 }}</ref>| nationalteam1 = [[England national under-21 football team|England U23]]| nationalcaps1 = 12| nationalgoals1 = 13\n| nationalyears2 = 1959\u20131967<ref name=\"rsssf\">{{Cite news|title=James Peter \"Jimmy\" Greaves&nbsp;\u2013 Goals in International Matches|publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/greaves-intlg.html}}</ref>| nationalteam2 = [[England national football team|England]] | nationalcaps2 = 57| nationalgoals2 = 44\n| medaltemplates      = \n{{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{fb|ENG}}}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966 England]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''James Peter Greaves''' (born 20 February 1940) is a former [[England national football team|England]] international [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]]. He is England's fourth highest international goalscorer (44 goals), [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]'s highest ever goalscorer (266 goals), the highest goalscorer in the history of English [[English football league system|top-flight]] football (357 goals), and has also scored more [[hat-trick]]s (six) for England than anyone else. He finished as the [[Football League First Division|First Division]]'s top scorer in six seasons. He is a member of the [[English Football Hall of Fame]].\n\nGreaves began his professional career at [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in 1957, and played in the following year's [[FA Youth Cup]] final. He scored 124 First Division goals in just four seasons before being sold on to Italian club [[A.C. Milan]] for \u00a380,000 in April 1961. His stay in Italy was not a happy one and he returned to England with Tottenham Hotspur for a fee of \u00a399,999 in December 1961. Whilst with Spurs he won the [[FA Cup]] in [[1962 FA Cup Final|1961\u201362]] and [[1967 FA Cup Final|1966\u201367]], the [[FA Community Shield|Charity Shield]] in [[1962 FA Charity Shield|1962]] and [[1967 FA Charity Shield|1967]], and the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]] in [[1963 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|1962\u201363]]; he never won a league title but did help Spurs to a second-place finish in 1962\u201363. He moved to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in a player-exchange in March 1970 and retired the following year. After a four-year absence he returned to football at the non-league level, despite suffering from alcoholism. In a five-year spell he played for [[Brentwood Town F.C.|Brentwood]], [[Chelmsford City F.C.|Chelmsford City]], [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]], and [[Woodford Town F.C.|Woodford Town]] before retiring for good in 1980. \n\nGreaves scored 13 goals in 12 [[England national under-21 football team|England under-23]] internationals and scored 44 goals in 57 full England internationals between 1959 and 1967. He played in the [[1962 FIFA World Cup|1962]] and [[1966 FIFA World Cup]], but was injured in the group stage of the 1966 World Cup and lost his first team place to [[Geoff Hurst]], who kept Greaves out of the first team in [[1966 FIFA World Cup Final|the final]]. England won the World Cup, but Greaves was not given his medal until a change of FIFA rules in 2009.\n\nAfter retiring as a player Greaves went on to enjoy a successful career in broadcasting, most notably working alongside [[Ian St John]] on ''[[Saint and Greavsie]]'' from 1985 to 1992. During this period, he also made regular appearances on [[TV-am]]. He worked on a number of other sport programmes on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] during this period, including ''[[Sporting Triangles]]'' (1987-1990).\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Chelsea===\nGreaves was born in [[Manor Park, London|Manor Park]] and raised in [[Hainault, London|Hainault]].<ref name=\"page 29\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=29}}</ref> He was scouted playing football while a schoolboy by [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]'s [[James Thompson (footballer)|Jimmy Thompson]], and in 1955 was signed on as an apprentice to become one of \"Drake's Ducklings\" (Drake's Ducklings were named after manager [[Ted Drake]] in response to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]'s \"[[Busby Babes]]\").<ref name=\"page 29\"/> He soon made an impression at youth level, scoring 51 goals in the 1955\u201356 season and 122 goals in the 1956\u201357 season under the tutelage of youth team coach [[Dick Foss]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=34}}</ref> Greaves scored in the 1958 [[FA Youth Cup]] final, but Chelsea lost the [[two-legged tie]] 7\u20136 on aggregate after [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] turned round a four-goal deficit with a 6\u20131 win in the second leg.<ref name=\"yc58\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=35}}</ref> He turned professional in the summer of 1957, though spent eight weeks working at a steel company to supplement his income during the summer break.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=42}}</ref>\n\nAged 17, Greaves scored on his [[Football League First Division|First Division]] debut on 24 August 1957 against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in a 1\u20131 draw at [[White Hart Lane]].<ref name=cfc>{{cite web|title=Jimmy Greaves|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/the-club/club-history/former-players/boilerplate/jimmy-greaves.html|publisher=www.chelseafc.com|accessdate=11 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812202321/http://www.chelseafc.com/the-club/club-history/former-players/boilerplate/jimmy-greaves.html |archivedate=12 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"sdp\">{{cite web|last1=Lanigan |first1=Adam |title=Sporting memories - Jimmy Greaves breaks the British transfer record |url=http://www.sundaypost.com/sport/sporting-memories-2.1062/sporting-memories-jimmy-greaves-breaks-the-british-transfer-record-1.135853 |publisher=The Sunday Post |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140813120704/http://www.sundaypost.com/sport/sporting-memories-2.1062/sporting-memories-jimmy-greaves-breaks-the-british-transfer-record-1.135853 |archive-date=13 August 2014 |accessdate=13 August 2014 |date=27 September 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was an instant success, as the ''[[News Chronicle]]'' reported that he \"showed the ball control, confidence and positional strength of a seasoned campaigner\" and compared his debut to the instant impact the young [[Duncan Edwards]] had as a teenager.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=60}}</ref> The \"Blues\" played attacking football during the [[1957\u201358 Football League|1957\u201358]] campaign, resulting in high-scoring matches, and Greaves ended the season as the club's top scorer with 22 goals in 37 appearances.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=62}}</ref> Drake rested him for six weeks from mid-November as he did not wish the praise Greaves was receiving to go to his head; Greaves marked his return to the first team at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] with four goals in a 7\u20134 victory over [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] on Christmas Day.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=71}}</ref>\n\nGreaves scored five goals in a 6\u20132 win against league champions Wolverhampton Wanderers in the third match of the [[1958\u201359 Football League|1958\u201359]] season.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=102}}</ref> Chelsea remained inconsistent, though despite his team finishing in 14th place Greaves managed to finish as the division's top scorer with 32 goals in 44 league games.<ref name=\"sdp\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=107}}</ref> Greaves scored 29 goals in 40 league matches in the [[1959\u201360 Football League|1959\u201360]] campaign, five of which came in a 5\u20134 victory over [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=155}}</ref> Despite his goalscoring exploits, the club could manage only an 18th-place finish, three places and three points above the relegation zone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Season 1959-60|url=http://www.rsssf.com/engpaul/FLA/1959-60.html|publisher=rsssf.com|accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1960\u201361 Chelsea F.C. season|1960\u201361]] season, Greaves scored [[hat-trick]]s against Wolves, [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]; he scored four goals against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] and [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]; and hit five goals in a 7\u20131 win over [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]. His hat-trick against Manchester City on 19 November included his 100th league goal, making him the youngest player to pass the 100-goal mark, at the age of 20 years and 290 days.<ref name=cfc/> However, he became increasingly disillusioned at Chelsea as, despite his goals, the team also conceded goals with regularity, and were never consistent enough to mount a title challenge. They also exited the [[FA Cup]] by losing 2\u20131 at home to [[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]] side [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=181}}</ref> Club chairman [[Joe Mears]] agreed to sell Greaves as Chelsea were in need of extra cash.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=182}}</ref> His last game was the final game of the 1960\u201361 season on 29 April; he was made captain for the day and scored his 13th hat-trick for Chelsea, scoring all four goals in a 4\u20133 win against Nottingham Forest.<ref name=cfc/> This took his tally for the season to a [[List of Chelsea F.C. records and statistics|club record]] 41 goals in 40 league games, making him the division's top scorer<ref name=\"sdp\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Chelsea Legends|url=http://chelseazone.wordpress.com/chelsea-legends/|publisher=Chelsea News|accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> and, at the time, Chelsea's second highest [[Chelsea F.C. statistics#Goalscorers|goalscorer]] ever with 132 goals.\n\n===A.C. Milan===\nGreaves was signed by Italian [[Serie A]] club [[A.C. Milan]] in June 1961 for an \u00a380,000 fee, and was given a three-year contract on \u00a3140 a week with a \u00a315,000 [[signing bonus]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=187}}</ref> He became unhappy at the thought of leaving London and tried to cancel the move before it was fully confirmed, but \"Rossoneri\" manager [[Giuseppe Viani]] refused to annul the deal.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=189}}</ref> Greaves scored on his debut in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas|Botafogo]] at the [[San Siro]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=205}}</ref> However, he did not get on well with new head coach [[Nereo Rocco]], who insisted on keeping the players in a strict training regime with little personal freedom.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=210}}</ref> Greaves scored nine goals in 14 appearances, including one against [[Inter Milan]] in the [[Derby della Madonnina|Milan derby]]. During a match against [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]], Greaves kicked a player who had spat in his face. Sampdoria equalised from the resulting free kick, for which Rocco blamed Greaves, despite him having scored Milan's opener and set up the second.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=213}}</ref> Due to his low morale, Greaves was transfer-listed and Brazilian attacker [[Dino Sani]] was signed as his replacement.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=221}}</ref> Both Tottenham Hotspur and Chelsea made \u00a396,500 bids, which were both accepted.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=222}}</ref> After he left, the club went on to win the league title in [[1961\u201362 Serie A|1961\u201362]].<ref name=\"ac62\">{{cite web|title=Italy 1961/62|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/ital62.html|publisher=rsssf.com|accessdate=9 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Tottenham Hotspur===\nAfter protracted negotiations, [[Bill Nicholson (footballer)|Bill Nicholson]] signed Greaves for Tottenham Hotspur in December 1961 for \u00a399,999&nbsp;\u2013 the unusual fee was intended to relieve Greaves of the pressure of being the first \u00a3100,000 player in British football.<ref name=\"sdp\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=225}}</ref> He joined Spurs just after they became the first club in England to complete the First Division and FA Cup [[Double (association football)|double]] during the 20th century.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=230}}</ref> He played his first game in a Spurs shirt for the [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C. Reserves and Academy|reserve team]] on 9 December 1961, and scored twice in a 4\u20131 win over [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] Reserves at [[Home Park]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=231}}</ref> He scored a hat-trick on his first team debut, including a [[Bicycle kick|flying scissor kick]], in a 5\u20132 win over [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] at White Hart Lane.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=234}}</ref> He went on to feature against [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] in the semi-finals of the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]]; in the first leg at the [[Est\u00e1dio da Luz (1954)|Est\u00e1dio da Luz]] he had a goal disallowed for offside, and another disallowed in the return fixture also for offside.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=251}}</ref> He played in all seven games of the club's FA Cup run, scoring nine goals in the competition as they beat [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] (after a replay), Plymouth Argyle, [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]], [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] and Manchester United to reach the [[1962 FA Cup Final]] against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]]. Greaves opened the scoring against Burnley on 3 minutes when he hit a low shot past goalkeeper [[Adam Blacklaw]] from a tight angle, and Spurs went on to win the game 3\u20131.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=261}}</ref><ref name=\"fa62\">{{cite news|title=Tottenham 3\u20131 Burnley|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/archive/1962-FA-Cup-final-Tottenham-3-1-Burnley-unseen-pictures-of-Jimmy-Greaves-Danny-Blanchflower-Jimmy-Robson-and-co-plus-original-Daily-Mirror-match-reports-and-features-from-the-time-article18231.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140409155402/http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/archive/1962-FA-Cup-final-Tottenham-3-1-Burnley-unseen-pictures-of-Jimmy-Greaves-Danny-Blanchflower-Jimmy-Robson-and-co-plus-original-Daily-Mirror-match-reports-and-features-from-the-time-article18231.html|archivedate=9 April 2014|accessdate=30 March 2014|newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]]}}</ref> They finished the league in third place in [[1961\u201362 Football League|1961\u201362]], four points behind champions [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Season 1961-62|url=http://www.rsssf.com/engpaul/FLA/1961-62.html|publisher=rsssf.com|accessdate=9 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nGreaves scored twice in the [[1962 FA Charity Shield]], as Spurs secured the trophy with a 5\u20131 win over Ipswich at [[Portman Road]].<ref name=\"cs62\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=300}}</ref> In the [[1962\u201363 Football League|1962\u201363]] season Greaves scored hat-tricks in victories over Manchester United, Ipswich Town and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], as well as four goals in a 9\u20132 win over Nottingham Forest.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=302}}</ref> Spurs finished the league campaign in second place, six points behind champions [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref name=\"d6263\">{{cite web|last1=Holmes|first1=Logan|title=Jimmy Greaves sets new goal scoring record for Tottenham|url=http://hotspurhq.com/2013/05/04/jimmy-greaves-sets-new-goal-scoring-record-for-tottenham/|publisher=HotSpurHQ|accessdate=9 August 2014}}</ref> Greaves scored 37 goals in 41 league games, finishing as the division's top scorer.<ref name=\"d6263\" /> In the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]], Tottenham beat [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] (Scotland), [[\u0160K Slovan Bratislava]] ([[Czechoslovakia]]) and [[OFK Beograd]] ([[Yugoslavia]]) to reach [[1963 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|the final]], where they met Spanish club [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] at [[De Kuip]].<ref name=\"ecuprun\">{{cite web|last1=Holmes|first1=Logan|title=1962-63 Tottenham European Cup Winners Cup Winners|url=http://hotspurhq.com/2013/02/19/1962-63-tottenham-european-cup-winners-cup-winners/|publisher=HotSpurHQ|accessdate=9 August 2014}}</ref> In the first leg of the semi-final against Beograd in [[Belgrade]], Greaves was sent off for violent conduct (his first and only red card) after attempting to punch centre-back [[Blagomir Krivoku\u0107a]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=311}}</ref> Greaves served a one match ban and was able to play in the final, where he opened the scoring after an assist from [[Cliff Jones (Welsh footballer)|Cliff Jones]] and later added a fourth in a 5\u20131 victory ([[John White (footballer, born 1937)|John White]] and [[Terry Dyson]] getting the other goals).<ref name=\"cwc\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=316}}</ref> In winning the competition, Tottenham Hotspur became the first British team to win a European trophy.<ref name=\"ecuprun\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=317}}</ref>\n\nManager Bill Nicholson and his assistant [[Eddie Baily]] then began a period of transition at White Hart Lane&nbsp;\u2013 [[Danny Blanchflower]] aged 38 retired in 1964 and John White was killed by a lightning strike.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=318}}</ref> [[Dave Mackay]] remained until 1968 and Greaves remained a consistent goalscorer. In the [[1963\u201364 Football League|1963\u201364]] season Greaves scored hat-tricks in victories over Nottingham Forest, Blackpool, [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] and [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]. Spurs finished in fourth place, six points behind champions Liverpool, and exited the FA Cup and Cup Winners' Cup at the opening stages.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=321}}</ref> Greaves scored 35 goals in 41 league games to again finish as the division's top scorer. Strike partner [[Bobby Smith (footballer, born 1933)|Bobby Smith]] left the club in the summer, though Greaves felt the partnership he went on to form with new signing [[Alan Gilzean]] was even more effective.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=323}}</ref>\n\nSpurs finished sixth in [[1964\u201365 Football League|1964\u201365]], though Greaves scored 29 goals in 41 league games to finish as the division's joint top scorer (with [[Andy McEvoy]]). He also scored two hat-tricks in the FA Cup&nbsp;\u2013 against [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]] and Ipswich Town &nbsp;\u2013 to take his total tally to 35 goals in 45 appearances. He missed three months at the start of the [[1965\u201366 Football League|1965\u201366]] season after being diagnosed with [[hepatitis]],<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=331}}</ref> but recovered to end the campaign with 16 goals in 31 matches, remaining the club's top scorer as they finished the league campaign in eighth place whilst failing to make it past the Fifth Round of the FA Cup.\n\nGreaves scored 31 goals in 47 appearances in the [[1966\u201367 Football League|1966\u201367]] campaign, helping Spurs to launch a title challenge that ended with a third-place finish, four points behind Manchester United. They also won the FA Cup after knocking out [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]], [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]], Birmingham City and Nottingham Forest to reach the [[1967 FA Cup Final]] with Chelsea. Though he did not score in the final itself, a 2\u20131 victory, with six goals in eight games Greaves was the competition's leading scorer.<ref name=\"fa67\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=382}}</ref> The [[1967\u201368 Football League|1967\u201368]] season was a disappointing one for Spurs following their 3\u20133 draw with Manchester United at Old Trafford in the [[1967 FA Charity Shield]]. They finished seventh in the league, exited the FA Cup in the Fifth Round and were knocked out of the Cup Winners' Cup in the Second Round.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=384}}</ref> Greaves had a poor season by his own standards, though with 29 goals in 48 appearances he was still the club's top scorer.<ref name=\"page 385\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=385}}</ref> Nicholson bought Greaves a new strike partner in [[Martin Chivers]] from [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] for a [[List of Tottenham Hotspur F.C. records and statistics|club record]] \u00a3125,000 fee, with Gilzean dropping further back into midfield to accommodate, but Greaves and Chivers were not as effective together as Nicholson had hoped.<ref name=\"page 385\"/>\n\nIn [[1968\u201369 Football League|1968\u201369]], Greaves scored 27 goals in 42 league games to finish as the First Division's leading scorer for the sixth and final time.<ref name=\"page 388\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=388}}</ref> He scored four of his goals in one match against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], and also scored hat-tricks against Burnley and [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]. His nine goals in cup competitions, including a hat-trick against [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]], left him with an overall goal tally of 36 in 52 games.<ref name=\"page 388\"/> His goals for the season took him past [[Bobby Smith (footballer, born 1933)|Bobby Smith]] as Spurs' top goalscorer<ref name=Top10Goalscorers>{{cite web|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news-archive-1/our-all-time-top-10-goalscorers-and-100-club/|title=Our all-time top 10 goalscorers and 100 club|website=www.tottenhamhotspur.com|date=27 December 2017|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref> as well as surpassing [[Steve Bloomer]] as the First Division's top goalscorer with 336 goals. Spurs performed inconsistently in the [[1969\u201370 Football League|1969\u201370]] season, and Greaves was dropped from the first team after playing in an FA Cup defeat to [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] at [[Selhurst Park]] on 28 January 1970.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=393}}</ref> He was never recalled to the starting line-up, but still ended the season as the club's joint top scorer (with Martin Chivers), having scored 11 goals in 33 matches, taking his total to 266 goals, a club record,<ref name=Top10Goalscorers/> including 15 hat-tricks, another club record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news-archive-1/2016-17-in-numbers-harrys-hat-tricks/|title=2016-17 in numbers - Harry's hat-tricks|website=www.tottenhamhotspur.com|date=1 June 2017|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref> Greaves was given a [[testimonial match]] by Spurs on 17 October 1972 in a 2\u20131 win over [[Feyenoord]] at White Hart Lane.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barham |first1=Albert |title=Jimmy Greaves takes a curtain call \u2013 archive, 18 October 1972 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/oct/18/jimmy-greaves-curtain-call-last-match-1972 |accessdate=23 January 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=18 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===West Ham United===\nIn March 1970, Greaves joined [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] as part-exchange in [[Martin Peters]]' transfer to White Hart Lane.<ref name=\"Greaves 2004 395\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=395}}</ref> [[Brian Clough]]'s [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] had also been interested in Greaves, but he did not want to move away from London. In hindsight Greaves felt that Clough might have helped him revive his career, as he had done for Greaves' former Tottenham teammate [[Dave Mackay]].<ref name=\"Greaves 2004 395\"/> Greaves later admitted his regret in making the move to [[Boleyn Ground|Upton Park]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=397}}</ref> He scored two goals on his \"Hammers\" debut on 21 March, in a 5\u20131 win against Manchester City at [[Maine Road]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Game played on 21 Mar 1970|url=http://www.westhamstats.info/westham.php?west=5&ham=2680&united=21_Mar_1970|publisher=www.westhamstats.info|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1971, with [[Bobby Moore]], [[Brian Dear]] and [[Clyde Best]], Greaves was involved in late-night drinking, against the wishes of manager [[Ron Greenwood]], prior to an FA Cup tie away to Blackpool.<ref name=40Blackpool>{{cite news|last=Giller|first=Martin|title=Moore and Greaves get Hammered in Blackpool|url=http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/211308/Moore-and-Greaves-get-Hammered-in-Blackpool-Moore-and-Greaves-get-Hammered-in-Blackpool-Moore-and-Greaves-get-Hammered-in-Blackpool-Moore-and-Greaves-get-Hammered-in-Blackpool-Moore-and-Greaves-get-Hammered-in-Blackpool-Moore-and-Greaves-get-Hammered-in-Blackpool-Moore-and-Greaves-get-Hammered-in-Blackpool|accessdate=17 June 2012|newspaper=[[Daily Express]]|date=13 November 2010}}</ref> On arriving in [[Blackpool]], Greaves and his teammates had been informed by members of [[News media|the press]] that the game, the following day, was unlikely to go ahead due to a frozen pitch and the likelihood of [[frost]] that night. Believing that there would be no game the following day, Greaves drank 12 lagers in a club owned by [[Brian London]] and did not return to the team hotel until 1.45am. In fact, the match went ahead and West Ham lost 4\u20130. Greaves claimed the defeat was not a result of the late night, the drinking or the frozen pitch, but because the West Ham team in which he was playing was not good enough. As a result, the players were fined and dropped by the club.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=292}}</ref>\n\nGreaves was struggling with his fitness and his motivation. He felt he had become a [[journeyman]] footballer and lost motivation as he believed that apart from Moore, [[Geoff Hurst]], [[Billy Bonds]] and [[Pop Robson]], few of his teammates could play good football. Towards the end of his career with West Ham Greaves began to drink more and more alcohol, often going straight from training in [[Chadwell Heath]] to a pub in [[Romford]], where he would remain until [[last call (bar term)|closing time]]. He later admitted that he was in the early stages of alcoholism.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=294}}</ref> His final game came on 1 May 1971 in a 1\u20130 home defeat to [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]].<ref name=whustats/> Greaves scored 13 goals in 40 games in all competitions for West Ham.<ref name=whustats>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Wonderful World of West Ham United Statistics&nbsp;\u2013 Jimmy Greaves|url=http://www.westhamstats.info/westham.php?west=2&ham=279&united=Jimmy_Greaves|publisher=www.westhamstats.info|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nGreaves' final season in the First Division took his goalscoring tally to a record 357 goals in the First Division. Together with the 9 goals at A.C. Milan, he had scored 366 goals in the top five European leagues, a record that lasted until 2017 when it was finally surpassed by [[Cristiano Ronaldo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11096/10819175/cristiano-ronaldo-smashes-jimmy-greaves-all-time-goal-record |title=Cristiano Ronaldo smashes Jimmy Greaves' all-time goal record |work=Sky Sports |date=17 May 2017 |accessdate=12 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518094459/http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11096/10819175/cristiano-ronaldo-smashes-jimmy-greaves-all-time-goal-record |archive-date=18 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Later career===\nAfter leaving West Ham, Greaves put on weight and did not attend a match as either a player or a spectator for two years.<ref name=\"page 415\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=415}}</ref> Drinking formed a large part of his life and he became an alcoholic; at times he was drinking 20 pints of lager during the day and consuming a bottle of vodka in the evening.<ref name=\"page 415\"/> He later admitted that he was also regularly driving whilst drunk during this period.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=297}}</ref> Seeking an answer to his alcoholism, Greaves decided to return to football at a lower level where he would not be required to be as fit as he had been whilst playing in [[the Football League]]. He started playing for his local side, [[Brentwood Town F.C.|Brentwood]],<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=299}}</ref> and made his debut on 27 December 1975 in a 2\u20130 defeat to [[Witham Town F.C.|Witham Town]].<ref name=\"bwood\">{{cite web | url=http://brentwoodtownfc.co.uk/about-the-club/club-history | title=Club History&nbsp;\u2013 Brentwood Town F.C. | publisher=www.brentwoodtownfc.co.uk | accessdate=11 April 2014 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413124300/http://brentwoodtownfc.co.uk/about-the-club/club-history | archivedate=13 April 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHis return to football was successful enough that he signed for [[Chelmsford City F.C.|Chelmsford City]] in the [[Southern Football League|Southern League]] for the [[1976\u201377 Southern Football League|1976\u201377]] season. He played for only a few months with Chelmsford. He was still struggling with alcoholism and [[delirium tremens]] and sought out help from [[Alcoholics Anonymous]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=429}}</ref> He was also hospitalised in the alcoholics' ward of [[Warley Hospital|Warley Psychiatric Hospital]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=307}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1977 and still coping with alcoholism, Greaves made his debut for [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] in a 3\u20132 win against [[Atherstone Town F.C.|Atherstone Town]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=313}}</ref> Playing from midfield in [[1977\u201378 Southern Football League|1977\u201378]], Greaves netted 25 goals (13 in the Southern League) and was their player of the season.<ref name=Barnetmidfield>{{cite news|title=Sol Campbell and the top 10 stars who lit up the lower leagues|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/news/Sol-Campbell-and-the-top-10-stars-who-lit-up-the-lower-leagues-article131571.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413143039/http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/news/Sol-Campbell-and-the-top-10-stars-who-lit-up-the-lower-leagues-article131571.html|archivedate=13 April 2014|accessdate=17 June 2012|newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=25 August 2009}}</ref> He chose to leave the \"Bees\" early in the [[1978\u201379 Southern Football League|1978\u201379]] season to focus on his business interests and beating his alcoholism, despite manager [[Barry Fry]]'s attempts to get him to stay at [[Underhill Stadium|Underhill]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=440}}</ref> Greaves went on to make several appearances for semi-professional side [[Woodford Town F.C.|Woodford Town]] before retiring.<ref name=Barnetmidfield/> By this time he was sober, and has remained so ever since.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wallace |first1=Sam |title=Jimmy Greaves' family question why one of English football's greatest is yet to be recognised by honours system |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/03/30/jimmy-greaves-family-ask-great-goalscorer-still-yet-recognised/ |website=The Telegraph |date=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nGreaves made his debut for the [[England national under-21 football team|England under-23]] team in a 6\u20132 win over [[Bulgaria national under-21 football team|Bulgaria]] at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] on 25 September 1957; he scored two goals,<ref name=\"u23\" /> and missed out on a hat-trick after failing to convert a penalty.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=64}}</ref>\n\nGreaves won his first [[England national football team|England]] [[Cap (sport)|cap]] on 17 May 1959 against [[Peru national football team|Peru]] at the [[Estadio Nacional del Per\u00fa|Estadio Nacional]], scoring England's only goal in a 4\u20131 defeat.<ref name=thefa>{{cite web|title=Jimmy Greaves|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/All-Teams/Players/G/Jimmy-Greaves|publisher=www.thefa.com|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref> The tour of the American continents was not considered a success by the British media, as England also lost to [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] and [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], but Greaves mostly escaped criticism in the press as he was still a teenager and showed promise with his performances.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=141}}</ref> He scored consecutive hat-tricks on 8 October 1960 and 19 October, in victories at [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] and [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Match No. 342 \u2013 Saturday, 8th October 1960|url=http://www.englandstats.com/matches.php?mid=342|work=englandstats.com|accessdate=9 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Match No. 343 \u2013 Wednesday, 19th October 1960|url=http://www.englandstats.com/matches.php?mid=343|work=englandstats.com|accessdate=9 April 2014}}</ref> On 15 April 1961, Greaves scored another hat-trick in a 9\u20133 victory over [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]], and also had a fourth goal disallowed for offside.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=201}}</ref>\n[[File:Jimmy Greaves and Bobby Charlton.jpg|240px|thumbnail|left|Jimmy Greaves and Bobby Charlton, December 1964]]\nHe played in all four of England's games at the [[1962 FIFA World Cup]] in Chile, scoring one goal in the 3\u20131 victory over [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] before playing in the quarter-final defeat to [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=291}}</ref> During the defeat to Brazil a stray dog ran onto the pitch and evaded all of the players' efforts to catch it until Greaves got down on all fours to beckon the animal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jimmy Greaves on chasing a dog during 1962 World Cup quarter-final|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/video/2014/mar/18/jimmy-greaves-chasing-dog-world-cup-video|accessdate=31 July 2014|work=The Guardian|date=18 March 2014}}</ref> The Brazilian player [[Garrincha]] thought the incident was so amusing that he took the dog home as a pet.<ref name=dmbrazil>{{cite news|title=Jimmy Greaves|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/archive/Jimmy-Greaves-article867.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110231345/http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/archive/Jimmy-Greaves-article867.html|archivedate=10 November 2013|accessdate=17 June 2012|newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 November 1963, he scored four goals in an 8\u20133 win over Northern Ireland.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=334}}</ref> The following year, on 3 October, he scored another hat-trick against the same team<ref>{{cite web|title=England's Hat-tricks|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamGoals/GoalsHattricks.html|publisher=www.englandonline.co.uk|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref> making him [[Progression of England association football goalscoring record|England's all-time top goalscorer]] with 35 goals. He scored four goals again on 29 June 1966, in a 6\u20131 friendly win over [[Norway national football team|Norway]], bringing his tally to 43 goals and in doing so ensured himself a starting place in the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=346}}</ref>\n{{Quote box|quote=\"I danced around the pitch with everyone else but even in this moment of triumph and great happiness, deep down I felt my sadness. Throughout my years as a professional footballer I had dreamed of playing in a World Cup Final. I had missed out on the match of a lifetime and it hurt.\"|source=\u2014 Greaves was bitterly disappointed to have missed the World Cup final, though it was only after his playing career ended that he descended into alcoholism.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=353}}</ref>|width=35%|align=right}}\n\nAt the World Cup he played all three group games against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] and [[France national football team|France]], however, in the win against France, midfielder [[Joseph Bonnel]] racked his studs down Greaves' shin, causing a wound that required 14 stitches and left a permanent scar.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=350}}</ref> His replacement for the quarter-final against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], [[Geoff Hurst]], scored the only goal of the game and kept his place all the way to [[1966 FIFA World Cup Final|the final]], where Hurst scored a hat-trick as England won the tournament.<ref name=thefa/> Greaves was fit to play in the final, but manager [[Alf Ramsey]] opted against changing a winning team.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=351}}</ref> Only the 11 players on the pitch at the end of the 4\u20132 win over [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] received medals. Following a [[The Football Association|Football Association]]-led campaign to persuade [[FIFA]] to award medals to all the winners' squad members, Greaves was presented with his [[1966 FIFA World Cup|medal]] by [[Gordon Brown]] at a ceremony at [[10 Downing Street]] on 10 June 2009.<ref name=\"wc66\">{{cite news|title=World Cup 1966 winners honoured|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8093891.stm|accessdate=30 March 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=10 June 2009}}</ref> In November 2014, Greaves' medal was sold at auction for \u00a344,000.<ref name=\"Medal sale\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-29993650 | title=Sir Stanley Matthews FA Cup medal sells for \u00a3220,000 | publisher=BBC news | date=11 November 2014 | accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nGreaves played only three more times for England after the 1966 World Cup, scoring a single goal. His final cap came in a 1\u20130 win over [[Austria national football team|Austria]] on 27 May 1967.<ref name=thefa/> At the time, he was [[Progression of England association football goalscoring record|England's all-time top goalscorer]] but was succeeded the following year by [[Bobby Charlton]]. Although Greaves was called up for [[UEFA Euro 1968]], he remained an unused substitute throughout the tournament, as the team finished in third place. He retired from international football early the following year after telling Ramsey that he had no intention of becoming a bit-part player in the England squad.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=387}}</ref> In total he scored 44 goals in 57 appearances for England.<ref name=thefa/> He is currently in fourth place on the all-time list of England goalscorers, behind [[Wayne Rooney]], [[Bobby Charlton]] and [[Gary Lineker]].<ref>{{cite web|title=England's Top Goalscorers|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/teamgoals/Goals_10-49.html|publisher=www.englandonline.co.uk|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref> Greaves holds [[England national football team records|the record]] for most hat-tricks for England&nbsp;\u2013 six in all.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hogan|first1=Chris|title=Jimmy Greaves|url=http://www.englandcaps.co.uk/jimmygreaves.html|website=englandcaps.co.uk|accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nGreaves was a prolific goalscorer, and cited his relaxed attitude as the reason for his assured composure and confidence.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=1}}</ref><ref name=\"goal machine\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/tottenham-hotspur/11582191/Jimmy-Greaves-the-goal-machine-behind-Spurs-glory-game-as-public-show-outpouring-of-support-after-stroke.html |title=Jimmy Greaves the goal machine behind Spurs glory game as public show outpouring of support after stroke |work=The Telegraph |last1=Winter |first1=Henry |date=4 May 2015 |accessdate=7 October 2019 }}</ref> He also had great acceleration and pace,<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=61}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Giles|title=Sport on TV: Drink was no bar to success for Moore and Greaves|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/england/3026142/Sport-on-TV-Drink-was-no-bar-to-success-for-Moore-and-Greaves.html|accessdate=31 July 2014|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=17 April 2002}}</ref> as well as great positional skills,<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=101}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jimmy Greaves|url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/history/past-players/jimmy-greaves/|accessdate=31 July 2014|work=tottenhamhotspur.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808045059/http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/history/past-players/jimmy-greaves/|archive-date=8 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> clinical finishing,<ref name=\"goal machine\"/> and opportunism inside the penalty area; he was also an excellent [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbler]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/2894617.stm|title=Blast from the past: Part five|publisher=BBC Sport|author1=Tom Fordyce|date=28 March 2003|accessdate=7 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2010/oct/15/the-joy-of-six-great-dribbles|title=The Joy of Six: Great dribbles|work=The Guardian|author1=Scott Murray|date=15 October 2010|accessdate=7 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcasting career==\nGreaves became a columnist at ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper in 1979.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moss |first1=Stephen |title=The Monday Interview: Jimmy Greaves |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/aug/25/sport.comment4 |accessdate=22 September 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=25 August 2003}}</ref> He continued to write his column until 2009, then began working as a columnist for ''[[The Sunday People]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=White|first=Jim|title=Former footballer Jimmy Greaves plays to a new crowd in second career as a comedian|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/premier-league/6931940/Former-footballer-Jimmy-Greaves-plays-to-a-new-crowd-in-second-career-as-a-comedian.html|accessdate=13 April 2014|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=5 January 2010}}</ref> He worked as a pundit on ''[[Star Soccer]]'' from 1980, and later co-presented ''[[The Saturday Show (1982 TV series)|The Saturday Show]]'' before he was selected as a pundit for [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s coverage of the [[1982 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=454}}</ref> From there he worked on ''[[World of Sport (British TV programme)|World of Sport]]'' and ''[[On the Ball (British TV programme)|On the Ball]]'', where he struck up a partnership with [[Ian St John]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=458}}</ref> [[Greg Dyke]] also hired Greaves to work as a television reviewer and presenter on ''[[TV-am]]'' in what Dyke admitted was a way of \"dumbing down\" the programme to attract more viewers.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=461}}</ref> From October 1985 to April 1992 he and St. John presented a popular Saturday lunchtime football programme called ''[[Saint and Greavsie]]''.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=466}}</ref> He went on to work as a team captain on ''[[Sporting Triangles]]'', opposite [[Andy Gray (footballer, born 1955)|Andy Gray]] and [[Emlyn Hughes]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=475}}</ref> His career in television came to an end as the [[Premier League]] was starting up, and he believed that his light-hearted approach to football was not considered serious enough for television bosses at the time.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=494}}</ref> Despite this he continued as a pundit at Central Television until 1998.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Richardson |first1=Andy |title=Big Ron: We should pray for Greavesie |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/big-ron-should-pray-greavesie-9178494 |accessdate=22 September 2019 |work=Birmingham Mail |date=4 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe released his autobiography, ''Greavsie'', in 2003. Greaves has also written numerous books in partnership with his lifelong friend, the journalist and author [[Norman Giller]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Giller|first1=Norman|title=Time to praise the man who set the goals standard|url=http://www.sportsjournalists.co.uk/the-giller-memorandum/time-to-praise-the-man-who-set-the-goals-standard/|publisher=Sports Journalists' Association|accessdate=13 August 2014|date=27 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGreaves married Irene Barden at [[Romford]] register office on 26 March 1958,<ref name=upinarms/> and though the pair went through a divorce process during the height of his alcoholism, it was never finalised and they reunited after three months apart.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=443}}</ref> Jimmy and Irene remarried on 7 September 2017 in [[Danbury, Essex|Danbury]], Essex.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/frail-football-legend-jimmy-greaves-11141589|title=Football legend Jimmy Greaves remarries ex-wife six decades after first wedding|first=Tom|last=Hopkinson|date=10 September 2017|website=mirror}}</ref> They had four children, Lynn, Mitzi, [[Danny Greaves (footballer)|Danny]] (who was a professional footballer with [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]]), and Andrew.<ref>{{cite news|author=Stephen Moss |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/aug/25/sport.comment4 |title=The Monday Interview: Jimmy Greaves |work=The Guardian |date=25 August 2003 |accessdate=29 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsjournalists.co.uk/the-giller-memorandum/messi-anic-fervour-of-striker-to-match-greavsie/ |title=Messi-anic fervour of striker to match Greavsie |publisher=Sports Journalists' Association |accessdate=29 September 2013}}</ref> They also had another son, Jimmy Greaves Jr, who died before his first birthday.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=183}}</ref>\n\nWhilst playing for [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] Greaves took out a \u00a31,000 bank loan to start a packing business with his brother-in-law.<ref name=\"page 416\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=416}}</ref> By the end of his playing career this company had an annual turnover of over \u00a31 million.<ref name=\"page 416\"/> He had a number of different business interests, including a travel agency.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=425}}</ref> Greaves entered the [[1970 London to Mexico World Cup Rally]]. In his first ever rally, alongside co-driver, [[Tony Fall]], Greaves drove a [[Ford Escort (Europe)|Ford Escort]] to a sixth-place finish out of the 96 entrants.<ref name=upinarms>{{cite news|last=Shaw|first=Phil|title=Jimmy Greaves: 'John Terry sleeps with some bird and everyone's up in arms'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/jimmy-greaves-john-terry-sleeps-with-some-bird-and-everyones-up-in-arms-1891631.html|accessdate=17 June 2012|newspaper=The Independent|date=7 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=People|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1083597/index.htm|accessdate=30 March 2014|newspaper=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n\nGreaves underwent surgery on an artery in his neck after suffering a mild stroke in February 2012.<ref>{{cite web|author=Press Association |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/feb/26/jimmy-greaves-recovery-stroke |title=England great Jimmy Greaves making full recovery after stroke|work=The Guardian |date=26 February 2012 |accessdate=29 September 2013}}</ref> After a full recovery, he experienced a severe stroke in May 2015 which left him unable to speak. He was placed in intensive care and, according to doctors, was expected to undergo a slow recovery.<ref name=care>{{cite web|title=Jimmy Greaves: Former England & Spurs striker in intensive care|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32580282|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32594079 | title=Jimmy Greaves: Former striker faces 'slow recovery' after stroke | publisher=BBC Sport | date=5 May 2015 | accessdate=6 May 2015}}</ref> He left hospital after a month, his health having \"improved considerably\" according to Greaves' friend and agent Terry Baker.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/jun/12/jimmy-greaves-leaves-hospital-after-stroke | title=Jimmy Greaves leaves hospital a month after suffering severe stroke | work=The Guardian | date=12 June 2015 | accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref> In February 2016, although slowly recovering from the stroke, Greaves was in a wheelchair and had been told that he would never walk again.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/10185073/jimmy-greaves-told-he-will-never-walk-again | title=Jimmy Greaves told he will never walk again | publisher=Sky Sports | accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref>\nIn early April 2020 Greaves was admitted to hospital, being treated for an unspecified illness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/52209724|title=Jimmy Greaves: Former England, Spurs, Chelsea & West Ham striker admitted to hospital|date=8 April 2020|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n{|\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Season&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Division\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]||[[1957\u201358 Football League|1957\u201358]]||[[Football League First Division|First Division]]||35||22||2||0||0||0||0||0||37||22\n|-\n|[[1958\u201359 Football League|1958\u201359]]||First Division||42||32||2||2||0||0||3||3||47||37\n|-\n|[[1959\u201360 Football League|1959\u201360]]||First Division||40||29||2||1||0||0||0||0||42||30\n|-\n|[[1960\u201361 Chelsea F.C. season|1960\u201361]]||First Division||40||41||1||0||2||2||0||0||43||43\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!157!!124!!7!!3!!2!!2!!3!!3!!169!!132\n|-\n|[[A.C. Milan]]||[[1961\u201362 Serie A|1961\u201362]]||[[Serie A]]||12||9||2||0||0||0||0||0||14||9\n|-\n|rowspan=\"10\"|[[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]||[[1961\u201362 Football League|1961\u201362]]||First Division||22||21||7||9||0||0||2|