://web.archive.org/web/20140328090548/http://jimmygreaves.net/ The official website of Jimmy Greaves]\n\n{{commons category}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Awards\n|fg=navy\n|bg=gold\n|list1=\n{{English First Division top scorers}}\n{{UEFA Cup Winners' Cup top scorers}}\n{{Football League 100 Legends}}\n{{Tottenham Hotspur F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n{{English Football Hall of Fame}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title = England squads\n| bg = white\n| fg = #0B0B3F\n| bordercolor = #0B0B3F\n| list1 = \n{{England squad 1962 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{England squad 1966 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{England squad UEFA Euro 1968}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Greaves, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Hainault]]\n[[Category:People from Manor Park, London]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Essex]]\n[[Category:Footballers from the London Borough of Newham]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England under-23 international footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Chelsea F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:A.C. Milan players]]\n[[Category:Tottenham Hotspur F.C. players]]\n[[Category:West Ham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Brentwood Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chelmsford City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Barnet F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Woodford Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:London XI players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Southern Football League players]]\n[[Category:1962 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:1966 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1968 players]]\n[[Category:First Division/Premier League top scorers]]\n[[Category:English Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:English rally drivers]]\n[[Category:English sportswriters]]\n[[Category:The Sun (United Kingdom) people]]\n[[Category:The People people]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:English sports broadcasters]]\n[[Category:English autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Stroke survivors]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:ITV people]]\n[[Category:Association football players who received a testimonial]]\n[[Category:English expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Jimmy Greaves\n| image          = Jimmy Greaves 2007.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = Greaves in 2007\n| fullname       = James Peter Greaves\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1940|2|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Manor Park, London|Manor Park]], England\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=8}}<ref>{{cite web|title=James Peter Greaves|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersG/BioGreavesJP.html|work=englandfootballonline.com|accessdate=2 April 2014}}</ref>\n| position       = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| youthyears1    = 1955\u20131957| youthclubs1 = [[Chelsea F.C. Reserves and Academy|Chelsea]]\n| years1         = 1957\u20131961| clubs1 = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]                    | caps1 = 157| goals1 = 124\n| years2         = 1961     | clubs2 = [[A.C. Milan]]                              | caps2 =  12| goals2 = 9\n| years3         = 1961\u20131970| clubs3 = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]| caps3 = 321| goals3 = 220\n| years4         = 1970\u20131971| clubs4 = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]    | caps4 =  38| goals4 = 13\n| years5         = 1975\u20131976| clubs5 = [[Brentwood Town F.C.|Brentwood]]           | caps5 =    | goals5 = \n| years6         = 1976\u20131977| clubs6 = [[Chelmsford City F.C.|Chelmsford City]]    | caps6 =  38<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.chelmsfordcityfc.com/news/throwbackthursday-a-series-of-clarets-players-pict-1738225.html|title=#ThrowbackThursday: A series of Clarets players, pictures, programmes and collectables|publisher=Chelmsford City F.C.|date=5 January 2017|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref> | goals6 = 20\n| years7         = 1977\u20131979| clubs7 = [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]]                      | caps7 =    | goals7 = \n| years8         = 1979\u20131980| clubs8 = [[Woodford Town F.C.|Woodford Town]]        | caps8 =    | goals8 = \n| totalcaps      = 566| totalgoals = 386\n| nationalyears1 = 1957\u20131962<ref name=\"u23\">{{cite web|title=England - U-23 International Results- Details |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng-u23-intres-det.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040413100658/http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng-u23-intres-det.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 April 2004 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |accessdate=1 March 2015 }}</ref>| nationalteam1 = [[England national under-21 football team|England U23]]| nationalcaps1 = 12| nationalgoals1 = 13\n| nationalyears2 = 1959\u20131967<ref name=\"rsssf\">{{Cite news|title=James Peter \"Jimmy\" Greaves&nbsp;\u2013 Goals in International Matches|publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/greaves-intlg.html}}</ref>| nationalteam2 = [[England national football team|England]] | nationalcaps2 = 57| nationalgoals2 = 44\n| medaltemplates      = \n{{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{fb|ENG}}}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966 England]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''James Peter Greaves''' (born 20 February 1940) is a former [[England national football team|England]] international [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]]. He is England's fourth highest international goalscorer (44 goals), [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]'s highest ever goalscorer (266 goals), the highest goalscorer in the history of English [[English football league system|top-flight]] football (357 goals), and has also scored more [[hat-trick]]s (six) for England than anyone else. He finished as the [[Football League First Division|First Division]]'s top scorer in six seasons. He is a member of the [[English Football Hall of Fame]].\n\nGreaves began his professional career at [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in 1957, and played in the following year's [[FA Youth Cup]] final. He scored 124 First Division goals in just four seasons before being sold on to Italian club [[A.C. Milan]] for \u00a380,000 in April 1961. His stay in Italy was not a happy one and he returned to England with Tottenham Hotspur for a fee of \u00a399,999 in December 1961. Whilst with Spurs he won the [[FA Cup]] in [[1962 FA Cup Final|1961\u201362]] and [[1967 FA Cup Final|1966\u201367]], the [[FA Community Shield|Charity Shield]] in [[1962 FA Charity Shield|1962]] and [[1967 FA Charity Shield|1967]], and the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]] in [[1963 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|1962\u201363]]; he never won a league title but did help Spurs to a second-place finish in 1962\u201363. He moved to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in a player-exchange in March 1970 and retired the following year. After a four-year absence he returned to football at the non-league level, despite suffering from alcoholism. In a five-year spell he played for [[Brentwood Town F.C.|Brentwood]], [[Chelmsford City F.C.|Chelmsford City]], [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]], and [[Woodford Town F.C.|Woodford Town]] before retiring for good in 1980. \n\nGreaves scored 13 goals in 12 [[England national under-21 football team|England under-23]] internationals and scored 44 goals in 57 full England internationals between 1959 and 1967. He played in the [[1962 FIFA World Cup|1962]] and [[1966 FIFA World Cup]], but was injured in the group stage of the 1966 World Cup and lost his first team place to [[Geoff Hurst]], who kept Greaves out of the first team in [[1966 FIFA World Cup Final|the final]]. England won the World Cup, but Greaves was not given his medal until a change of FIFA rules in 2009.\n\nAfter retiring as a player Greaves went on to enjoy a successful career in broadcasting, most notably working alongside [[Ian St John]] on ''[[Saint and Greavsie]]'' from 1985 to 1992. During this period, he also made regular appearances on [[TV-am]]. He worked on a number of other sport programmes on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] during this period, including ''[[Sporting Triangles]]'' (1987-1990).\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Chelsea===\nGreaves was born in [[Manor Park, London|Manor Park]] and raised in [[Hainault, London|Hainault]].<ref name=\"page 29\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=29}}</ref> He was scouted playing football while a schoolboy by [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]'s [[James Thompson (footballer)|Jimmy Thompson]], and in 1955 was signed on as an apprentice to become one of \"Drake's Ducklings\" (Drake's Ducklings were named after manager [[Ted Drake]] in response to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]'s \"[[Busby Babes]]\").<ref name=\"page 29\"/> He soon made an impression at youth level, scoring 51 goals in the 1955\u201356 season and 122 goals in the 1956\u201357 season under the tutelage of youth team coach [[Dick Foss]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=34}}</ref> Greaves scored in the 1958 [[FA Youth Cup]] final, but Chelsea lost the [[two-legged tie]] 7\u20136 on aggregate after [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] turned round a four-goal deficit with a 6\u20131 win in the second leg.<ref name=\"yc58\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=35}}</ref> He turned professional in the summer of 1957, though spent eight weeks working at a steel company to supplement his income during the summer break.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=42}}</ref>\n\nAged 17, Greaves scored on his [[Football League First Division|First Division]] debut on 24 August 1957 against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in a 1\u20131 draw at [[White Hart Lane]].<ref name=cfc>{{cite web|title=Jimmy Greaves|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/the-club/club-history/former-players/boilerplate/jimmy-greaves.html|publisher=www.chelseafc.com|accessdate=11 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812202321/http://www.chelseafc.com/the-club/club-history/former-players/boilerplate/jimmy-greaves.html |archivedate=12 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"sdp\">{{cite web|last1=Lanigan |first1=Adam |title=Sporting memories - Jimmy Greaves breaks the British transfer record |url=http://www.sundaypost.com/sport/sporting-memories-2.1062/sporting-memories-jimmy-greaves-breaks-the-british-transfer-record-1.135853 |publisher=The Sunday Post |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140813120704/http://www.sundaypost.com/sport/sporting-memories-2.1062/sporting-memories-jimmy-greaves-breaks-the-british-transfer-record-1.135853 |archive-date=13 August 2014 |accessdate=13 August 2014 |date=27 September 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was an instant success, as the ''[[News Chronicle]]'' reported that he \"showed the ball control, confidence and positional strength of a seasoned campaigner\" and compared his debut to the instant impact the young [[Duncan Edwards]] had as a teenager.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=60}}</ref> The \"Blues\" played attacking football during the [[1957\u201358 Football League|1957\u201358]] campaign, resulting in high-scoring matches, and Greaves ended the season as the club's top scorer with 22 goals in 37 appearances.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=62}}</ref> Drake rested him for six weeks from mid-November as he did not wish the praise Greaves was receiving to go to his head; Greaves marked his return to the first team at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] with four goals in a 7\u20134 victory over [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] on Christmas Day.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=71}}</ref>\n\nGreaves scored five goals in a 6\u20132 win against league champions Wolverhampton Wanderers in the third match of the [[1958\u201359 Football League|1958\u201359]] season.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=102}}</ref> Chelsea remained inconsistent, though despite his team finishing in 14th place Greaves managed to finish as the division's top scorer with 32 goals in 44 league games.<ref name=\"sdp\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=107}}</ref> Greaves scored 29 goals in 40 league matches in the [[1959\u201360 Football League|1959\u201360]] campaign, five of which came in a 5\u20134 victory over [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=155}}</ref> Despite his goalscoring exploits, the club could manage only an 18th-place finish, three places and three points above the relegation zone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Season 1959-60|url=http://www.rsssf.com/engpaul/FLA/1959-60.html|publisher=rsssf.com|accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1960\u201361 Chelsea F.C. season|1960\u201361]] season, Greaves scored [[hat-trick]]s against Wolves, [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]; he scored four goals against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] and [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]; and hit five goals in a 7\u20131 win over [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]. His hat-trick against Manchester City on 19 November included his 100th league goal, making him the youngest player to pass the 100-goal mark, at the age of 20 years and 290 days.<ref name=cfc/> However, he became increasingly disillusioned at Chelsea as, despite his goals, the team also conceded goals with regularity, and were never consistent enough to mount a title challenge. They also exited the [[FA Cup]] by losing 2\u20131 at home to [[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]] side [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=181}}</ref> Club chairman [[Joe Mears]] agreed to sell Greaves as Chelsea were in need of extra cash.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=182}}</ref> His last game was the final game of the 1960\u201361 season on 29 April; he was made captain for the day and scored his 13th hat-trick for Chelsea, scoring all four goals in a 4\u20133 win against Nottingham Forest.<ref name=cfc/> This took his tally for the season to a [[List of Chelsea F.C. records and statistics|club record]] 41 goals in 40 league games, making him the division's top scorer<ref name=\"sdp\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Chelsea Legends|url=http://chelseazone.wordpress.com/chelsea-legends/|publisher=Chelsea News|accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref> and, at the time, Chelsea's second highest [[Chelsea F.C. statistics#Goalscorers|goalscorer]] ever with 132 goals.\n\n===A.C. Milan===\nGreaves was signed by Italian [[Serie A]] club [[A.C. Milan]] in June 1961 for an \u00a380,000 fee, and was given a three-year contract on \u00a3140 a week with a \u00a315,000 [[signing bonus]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=187}}</ref> He became unhappy at the thought of leaving London and tried to cancel the move before it was fully confirmed, but \"Rossoneri\" manager [[Giuseppe Viani]] refused to annul the deal.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=189}}</ref> Greaves scored on his debut in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas|Botafogo]] at the [[San Siro]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=205}}</ref> However, he did not get on well with new head coach [[Nereo Rocco]], who insisted on keeping the players in a strict training regime with little personal freedom.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=210}}</ref> Greaves scored nine goals in 14 appearances, including one against [[Inter Milan]] in the [[Derby della Madonnina|Milan derby]]. During a match against [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]], Greaves kicked a player who had spat in his face. Sampdoria equalised from the resulting free kick, for which Rocco blamed Greaves, despite him having scored Milan's opener and set up the second.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=213}}</ref> Due to his low morale, Greaves was transfer-listed and Brazilian attacker [[Dino Sani]] was signed as his replacement.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=221}}</ref> Both Tottenham Hotspur and Chelsea made \u00a396,500 bids, which were both accepted.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=222}}</ref> After he left, the club went on to win the league title in [[1961\u201362 Serie A|1961\u201362]].<ref name=\"ac62\">{{cite web|title=Italy 1961/62|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/ital62.html|publisher=rsssf.com|accessdate=9 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Tottenham Hotspur===\nAfter protracted negotiations, [[Bill Nicholson (footballer)|Bill Nicholson]] signed Greaves for Tottenham Hotspur in December 1961 for \u00a399,999&nbsp;\u2013 the unusual fee was intended to relieve Greaves of the pressure of being the first \u00a3100,000 player in British football.<ref name=\"sdp\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=225}}</ref> He joined Spurs just after they became the first club in England to complete the First Division and FA Cup [[Double (association football)|double]] during the 20th century.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=230}}</ref> He played his first game in a Spurs shirt for the [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C. Reserves and Academy|reserve team]] on 9 December 1961, and scored twice in a 4\u20131 win over [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] Reserves at [[Home Park]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=231}}</ref> He scored a hat-trick on his first team debut, including a [[Bicycle kick|flying scissor kick]], in a 5\u20132 win over [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] at White Hart Lane.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=234}}</ref> He went on to feature against [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] in the semi-finals of the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]]; in the first leg at the [[Est\u00e1dio da Luz (1954)|Est\u00e1dio da Luz]] he had a goal disallowed for offside, and another disallowed in the return fixture also for offside.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=251}}</ref> He played in all seven games of the club's FA Cup run, scoring nine goals in the competition as they beat [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] (after a replay), Plymouth Argyle, [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]], [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] and Manchester United to reach the [[1962 FA Cup Final]] against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]]. Greaves opened the scoring against Burnley on 3 minutes when he hit a low shot past goalkeeper [[Adam Blacklaw]] from a tight angle, and Spurs went on to win the game 3\u20131.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=261}}</ref><ref name=\"fa62\">{{cite news|title=Tottenham 3\u20131 Burnley|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/archive/1962-FA-Cup-final-Tottenham-3-1-Burnley-unseen-pictures-of-Jimmy-Greaves-Danny-Blanchflower-Jimmy-Robson-and-co-plus-original-Daily-Mirror-match-reports-and-features-from-the-time-article18231.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140409155402/http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/archive/1962-FA-Cup-final-Tottenham-3-1-Burnley-unseen-pictures-of-Jimmy-Greaves-Danny-Blanchflower-Jimmy-Robson-and-co-plus-original-Daily-Mirror-match-reports-and-features-from-the-time-article18231.html|archivedate=9 April 2014|accessdate=30 March 2014|newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]]}}</ref> They finished the league in third place in [[1961\u201362 Football League|1961\u201362]], four points behind champions [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Season 1961-62|url=http://www.rsssf.com/engpaul/FLA/1961-62.html|publisher=rsssf.com|accessdate=9 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nGreaves scored twice in the [[1962 FA Charity Shield]], as Spurs secured the trophy with a 5\u20131 win over Ipswich at [[Portman Road]].<ref name=\"cs62\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=300}}</ref> In the [[1962\u201363 Football League|1962\u201363]] season Greaves scored hat-tricks in victories over Manchester United, Ipswich Town and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], as well as four goals in a 9\u20132 win over Nottingham Forest.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=302}}</ref> Spurs finished the league campaign in second place, six points behind champions [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref name=\"d6263\">{{cite web|last1=Holmes|first1=Logan|title=Jimmy Greaves sets new goal scoring record for Tottenham|url=http://hotspurhq.com/2013/05/04/jimmy-greaves-sets-new-goal-scoring-record-for-tottenham/|publisher=HotSpurHQ|accessdate=9 August 2014}}</ref> Greaves scored 37 goals in 41 league games, finishing as the division's top scorer.<ref name=\"d6263\" /> In the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]], Tottenham beat [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] (Scotland), [[\u0160K Slovan Bratislava]] ([[Czechoslovakia]]) and [[OFK Beograd]] ([[Yugoslavia]]) to reach [[1963 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|the final]], where they met Spanish club [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] at [[De Kuip]].<ref name=\"ecuprun\">{{cite web|last1=Holmes|first1=Logan|title=1962-63 Tottenham European Cup Winners Cup Winners|url=http://hotspurhq.com/2013/02/19/1962-63-tottenham-european-cup-winners-cup-winners/|publisher=HotSpurHQ|accessdate=9 August 2014}}</ref> In the first leg of the semi-final against Beograd in [[Belgrade]], Greaves was sent off for violent conduct (his first and only red card) after attempting to punch centre-back [[Blagomir Krivoku\u0107a]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=311}}</ref> Greaves served a one match ban and was able to play in the final, where he opened the scoring after an assist from [[Cliff Jones (Welsh footballer)|Cliff Jones]] and later added a fourth in a 5\u20131 victory ([[John White (footballer, born 1937)|John White]] and [[Terry Dyson]] getting the other goals).<ref name=\"cwc\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=316}}</ref> In winning the competition, Tottenham Hotspur became the first British team to win a European trophy.<ref name=\"ecuprun\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=317}}</ref>\n\nManager Bill Nicholson and his assistant [[Eddie Baily]] then began a period of transition at White Hart Lane&nbsp;\u2013 [[Danny Blanchflower]] aged 38 retired in 1964 and John White was killed by a lightning strike.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=318}}</ref> [[Dave Mackay]] remained until 1968 and Greaves remained a consistent goalscorer. In the [[1963\u201364 Football League|1963\u201364]] season Greaves scored hat-tricks in victories over Nottingham Forest, Blackpool, [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] and [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]. Spurs finished in fourth place, six points behind champions Liverpool, and exited the FA Cup and Cup Winners' Cup at the opening stages.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=321}}</ref> Greaves scored 35 goals in 41 league games to again finish as the division's top scorer. Strike partner [[Bobby Smith (footballer, born 1933)|Bobby Smith]] left the club in the summer, though Greaves felt the partnership he went on to form with new signing [[Alan Gilzean]] was even more effective.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=323}}</ref>\n\nSpurs finished sixth in [[1964\u201365 Football League|1964\u201365]], though Greaves scored 29 goals in 41 league games to finish as the division's joint top scorer (with [[Andy McEvoy]]). He also scored two hat-tricks in the FA Cup&nbsp;\u2013 against [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]] and Ipswich Town &nbsp;\u2013 to take his total tally to 35 goals in 45 appearances. He missed three months at the start of the [[1965\u201366 Football League|1965\u201366]] season after being diagnosed with [[hepatitis]],<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=331}}</ref> but recovered to end the campaign with 16 goals in 31 matches, remaining the club's top scorer as they finished the league campaign in eighth place whilst failing to make it past the Fifth Round of the FA Cup.\n\nGreaves scored 31 goals in 47 appearances in the [[1966\u201367 Football League|1966\u201367]] campaign, helping Spurs to launch a title challenge that ended with a third-place finish, four points behind Manchester United. They also won the FA Cup after knocking out [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]], [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]], Birmingham City and Nottingham Forest to reach the [[1967 FA Cup Final]] with Chelsea. Though he did not score in the final itself, a 2\u20131 victory, with six goals in eight games Greaves was the competition's leading scorer.<ref name=\"fa67\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=382}}</ref> The [[1967\u201368 Football League|1967\u201368]] season was a disappointing one for Spurs following their 3\u20133 draw with Manchester United at Old Trafford in the [[1967 FA Charity Shield]]. They finished seventh in the league, exited the FA Cup in the Fifth Round and were knocked out of the Cup Winners' Cup in the Second Round.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=384}}</ref> Greaves had a poor season by his own standards, though with 29 goals in 48 appearances he was still the club's top scorer.<ref name=\"page 385\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=385}}</ref> Nicholson bought Greaves a new strike partner in [[Martin Chivers]] from [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] for a [[List of Tottenham Hotspur F.C. records and statistics|club record]] \u00a3125,000 fee, with Gilzean dropping further back into midfield to accommodate, but Greaves and Chivers were not as effective together as Nicholson had hoped.<ref name=\"page 385\"/>\n\nIn [[1968\u201369 Football League|1968\u201369]], Greaves scored 27 goals in 42 league games to finish as the First Division's leading scorer for the sixth and final time.<ref name=\"page 388\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=388}}</ref> He scored four of his goals in one match against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], and also scored hat-tricks against Burnley and [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]. His nine goals in cup competitions, including a hat-trick against [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]], left him with an overall goal tally of 36 in 52 games.<ref name=\"page 388\"/> His goals for the season took him past [[Bobby Smith (footballer, born 1933)|Bobby Smith]] as Spurs' top goalscorer<ref name=Top10Goalscorers>{{cite web|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news-archive-1/our-all-time-top-10-goalscorers-and-100-club/|title=Our all-time top 10 goalscorers and 100 club|website=www.tottenhamhotspur.com|date=27 December 2017|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref> as well as surpassing [[Steve Bloomer]] as the First Division's top goalscorer with 336 goals. Spurs performed inconsistently in the [[1969\u201370 Football League|1969\u201370]] season, and Greaves was dropped from the first team after playing in an FA Cup defeat to [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] at [[Selhurst Park]] on 28 January 1970.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=393}}</ref> He was never recalled to the starting line-up, but still ended the season as the club's joint top scorer (with Martin Chivers), having scored 11 goals in 33 matches, taking his total to 266 goals, a club record,<ref name=Top10Goalscorers/> including 15 hat-tricks, another club record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news-archive-1/2016-17-in-numbers-harrys-hat-tricks/|title=2016-17 in numbers - Harry's hat-tricks|website=www.tottenhamhotspur.com|date=1 June 2017|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref> Greaves was given a [[testimonial match]] by Spurs on 17 October 1972 in a 2\u20131 win over [[Feyenoord]] at White Hart Lane.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barham |first1=Albert |title=Jimmy Greaves takes a curtain call \u2013 archive, 18 October 1972 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/oct/18/jimmy-greaves-curtain-call-last-match-1972 |accessdate=23 January 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=18 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===West Ham United===\nIn March 1970, Greaves joined [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] as part-exchange in [[Martin Peters]]' transfer to White Hart Lane.<ref name=\"Greaves 2004 395\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=395}}</ref> [[Brian Clough]]'s [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] had also been interested in Greaves, but he did not want to move away from London. In hindsight Greaves felt that Clough might have helped him revive his career, as he had done for Greaves' former Tottenham teammate [[Dave Mackay]].<ref name=\"Greaves 2004 395\"/> Greaves later admitted his regret in making the move to [[Boleyn Ground|Upton Park]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=397}}</ref> He scored two goals on his \"Hammers\" debut on 21 March, in a 5\u20131 win against Manchester City at [[Maine Road]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Game played on 21 Mar 1970|url=http://www.westhamstats.info/westham.php?west=5&ham=2680&united=21_Mar_1970|publisher=www.westhamstats.info|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1971, with [[Bobby Moore]], [[Brian Dear]] and [[Clyde Best]], Greaves was involved in late-night drinking, against the wishes of manager [[Ron Greenwood]], prior to an FA Cup tie away to Blackpool.<ref name=40Blackpool>{{cite news|last=Giller|first=Martin|title=Moore and Greaves get Hammered in Blackpool|url=http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/211308/Moore-and-Greaves-get-Hammered-in-Blackpool-Moore-and-Greaves-get-Hammered-in-Blackpool-Moore-and-Greaves-get-Hammered-in-Blackpool-Moore-and-Greaves-get-Hammered-in-Blackpool-Moore-and-Greaves-get-Hammered-in-Blackpool-Moore-and-Greaves-get-Hammered-in-Blackpool-Moore-and-Greaves-get-Hammered-in-Blackpool|accessdate=17 June 2012|newspaper=[[Daily Express]]|date=13 November 2010}}</ref> On arriving in [[Blackpool]], Greaves and his teammates had been informed by members of [[News media|the press]] that the game, the following day, was unlikely to go ahead due to a frozen pitch and the likelihood of [[frost]] that night. Believing that there would be no game the following day, Greaves drank 12 lagers in a club owned by [[Brian London]] and did not return to the team hotel until 1.45am. In fact, the match went ahead and West Ham lost 4\u20130. Greaves claimed the defeat was not a result of the late night, the drinking or the frozen pitch, but because the West Ham team in which he was playing was not good enough. As a result, the players were fined and dropped by the club.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=292}}</ref>\n\nGreaves was struggling with his fitness and his motivation. He felt he had become a [[journeyman]] footballer and lost motivation as he believed that apart from Moore, [[Geoff Hurst]], [[Billy Bonds]] and [[Pop Robson]], few of his teammates could play good football. Towards the end of his career with West Ham Greaves began to drink more and more alcohol, often going straight from training in [[Chadwell Heath]] to a pub in [[Romford]], where he would remain until [[last call (bar term)|closing time]]. He later admitted that he was in the early stages of alcoholism.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=294}}</ref> His final game came on 1 May 1971 in a 1\u20130 home defeat to [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]].<ref name=whustats/> Greaves scored 13 goals in 40 games in all competitions for West Ham.<ref name=whustats>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Wonderful World of West Ham United Statistics&nbsp;\u2013 Jimmy Greaves|url=http://www.westhamstats.info/westham.php?west=2&ham=279&united=Jimmy_Greaves|publisher=www.westhamstats.info|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nGreaves' final season in the First Division took his goalscoring tally to a record 357 goals in the First Division. Together with the 9 goals at A.C. Milan, he had scored 366 goals in the top five European leagues, a record that lasted until 2017 when it was finally surpassed by [[Cristiano Ronaldo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11096/10819175/cristiano-ronaldo-smashes-jimmy-greaves-all-time-goal-record |title=Cristiano Ronaldo smashes Jimmy Greaves' all-time goal record |work=Sky Sports |date=17 May 2017 |accessdate=12 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518094459/http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11096/10819175/cristiano-ronaldo-smashes-jimmy-greaves-all-time-goal-record |archive-date=18 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Later career===\nAfter leaving West Ham, Greaves put on weight and did not attend a match as either a player or a spectator for two years.<ref name=\"page 415\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=415}}</ref> Drinking formed a large part of his life and he became an alcoholic; at times he was drinking 20 pints of lager during the day and consuming a bottle of vodka in the evening.<ref name=\"page 415\"/> He later admitted that he was also regularly driving whilst drunk during this period.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=297}}</ref> Seeking an answer to his alcoholism, Greaves decided to return to football at a lower level where he would not be required to be as fit as he had been whilst playing in [[the Football League]]. He started playing for his local side, [[Brentwood Town F.C.|Brentwood]],<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=299}}</ref> and made his debut on 27 December 1975 in a 2\u20130 defeat to [[Witham Town F.C.|Witham Town]].<ref name=\"bwood\">{{cite web | url=http://brentwoodtownfc.co.uk/about-the-club/club-history | title=Club History&nbsp;\u2013 Brentwood Town F.C. | publisher=www.brentwoodtownfc.co.uk | accessdate=11 April 2014 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413124300/http://brentwoodtownfc.co.uk/about-the-club/club-history | archivedate=13 April 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHis return to football was successful enough that he signed for [[Chelmsford City F.C.|Chelmsford City]] in the [[Southern Football League|Southern League]] for the [[1976\u201377 Southern Football League|1976\u201377]] season. He played for only a few months with Chelmsford. He was still struggling with alcoholism and [[delirium tremens]] and sought out help from [[Alcoholics Anonymous]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=429}}</ref> He was also hospitalised in the alcoholics' ward of [[Warley Hospital|Warley Psychiatric Hospital]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=307}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1977 and still coping with alcoholism, Greaves made his debut for [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] in a 3\u20132 win against [[Atherstone Town F.C.|Atherstone Town]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=313}}</ref> Playing from midfield in [[1977\u201378 Southern Football League|1977\u201378]], Greaves netted 25 goals (13 in the Southern League) and was their player of the season.<ref name=Barnetmidfield>{{cite news|title=Sol Campbell and the top 10 stars who lit up the lower leagues|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/news/Sol-Campbell-and-the-top-10-stars-who-lit-up-the-lower-leagues-article131571.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413143039/http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/news/Sol-Campbell-and-the-top-10-stars-who-lit-up-the-lower-leagues-article131571.html|archivedate=13 April 2014|accessdate=17 June 2012|newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=25 August 2009}}</ref> He chose to leave the \"Bees\" early in the [[1978\u201379 Southern Football League|1978\u201379]] season to focus on his business interests and beating his alcoholism, despite manager [[Barry Fry]]'s attempts to get him to stay at [[Underhill Stadium|Underhill]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=440}}</ref> Greaves went on to make several appearances for semi-professional side [[Woodford Town F.C.|Woodford Town]] before retiring.<ref name=Barnetmidfield/> By this time he was sober, and has remained so ever since.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wallace |first1=Sam |title=Jimmy Greaves' family question why one of English football's greatest is yet to be recognised by honours system |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/03/30/jimmy-greaves-family-ask-great-goalscorer-still-yet-recognised/ |website=The Telegraph |date=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nGreaves made his debut for the [[England national under-21 football team|England under-23]] team in a 6\u20132 win over [[Bulgaria national under-21 football team|Bulgaria]] at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] on 25 September 1957; he scored two goals,<ref name=\"u23\" /> and missed out on a hat-trick after failing to convert a penalty.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=64}}</ref>\n\nGreaves won his first [[England national football team|England]] [[Cap (sport)|cap]] on 17 May 1959 against [[Peru national football team|Peru]] at the [[Estadio Nacional del Per\u00fa|Estadio Nacional]], scoring England's only goal in a 4\u20131 defeat.<ref name=thefa>{{cite web|title=Jimmy Greaves|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/All-Teams/Players/G/Jimmy-Greaves|publisher=www.thefa.com|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref> The tour of the American continents was not considered a success by the British media, as England also lost to [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] and [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], but Greaves mostly escaped criticism in the press as he was still a teenager and showed promise with his performances.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=141}}</ref> He scored consecutive hat-tricks on 8 October 1960 and 19 October, in victories at [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] and [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Match No. 342 \u2013 Saturday, 8th October 1960|url=http://www.englandstats.com/matches.php?mid=342|work=englandstats.com|accessdate=9 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Match No. 343 \u2013 Wednesday, 19th October 1960|url=http://www.englandstats.com/matches.php?mid=343|work=englandstats.com|accessdate=9 April 2014}}</ref> On 15 April 1961, Greaves scored another hat-trick in a 9\u20133 victory over [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]], and also had a fourth goal disallowed for offside.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=201}}</ref>\n[[File:Jimmy Greaves and Bobby Charlton.jpg|240px|thumbnail|left|Jimmy Greaves and Bobby Charlton, December 1964]]\nHe played in all four of England's games at the [[1962 FIFA World Cup]] in Chile, scoring one goal in the 3\u20131 victory over [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] before playing in the quarter-final defeat to [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=291}}</ref> During the defeat to Brazil a stray dog ran onto the pitch and evaded all of the players' efforts to catch it until Greaves got down on all fours to beckon the animal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jimmy Greaves on chasing a dog during 1962 World Cup quarter-final|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/video/2014/mar/18/jimmy-greaves-chasing-dog-world-cup-video|accessdate=31 July 2014|work=The Guardian|date=18 March 2014}}</ref> The Brazilian player [[Garrincha]] thought the incident was so amusing that he took the dog home as a pet.<ref name=dmbrazil>{{cite news|title=Jimmy Greaves|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/archive/Jimmy-Greaves-article867.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110231345/http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/archive/Jimmy-Greaves-article867.html|archivedate=10 November 2013|accessdate=17 June 2012|newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 November 1963, he scored four goals in an 8\u20133 win over Northern Ireland.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=334}}</ref> The following year, on 3 October, he scored another hat-trick against the same team<ref>{{cite web|title=England's Hat-tricks|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamGoals/GoalsHattricks.html|publisher=www.englandonline.co.uk|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref> making him [[Progression of England association football goalscoring record|England's all-time top goalscorer]] with 35 goals. He scored four goals again on 29 June 1966, in a 6\u20131 friendly win over [[Norway national football team|Norway]], bringing his tally to 43 goals and in doing so ensured himself a starting place in the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=346}}</ref>\n{{Quote box|quote=\"I danced around the pitch with everyone else but even in this moment of triumph and great happiness, deep down I felt my sadness. Throughout my years as a professional footballer I had dreamed of playing in a World Cup Final. I had missed out on the match of a lifetime and it hurt.\"|source=\u2014 Greaves was bitterly disappointed to have missed the World Cup final, though it was only after his playing career ended that he descended into alcoholism.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=353}}</ref>|width=35%|align=right}}\n\nAt the World Cup he played all three group games against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] and [[France national football team|France]], however, in the win against France, midfielder [[Joseph Bonnel]] racked his studs down Greaves' shin, causing a wound that required 14 stitches and left a permanent scar.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=350}}</ref> His replacement for the quarter-final against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], [[Geoff Hurst]], scored the only goal of the game and kept his place all the way to [[1966 FIFA World Cup Final|the final]], where Hurst scored a hat-trick as England won the tournament.<ref name=thefa/> Greaves was fit to play in the final, but manager [[Alf Ramsey]] opted against changing a winning team.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=351}}</ref> Only the 11 players on the pitch at the end of the 4\u20132 win over [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] received medals. Following a [[The Football Association|Football Association]]-led campaign to persuade [[FIFA]] to award medals to all the winners' squad members, Greaves was presented with his [[1966 FIFA World Cup|medal]] by [[Gordon Brown]] at a ceremony at [[10 Downing Street]] on 10 June 2009.<ref name=\"wc66\">{{cite news|title=World Cup 1966 winners honoured|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8093891.stm|accessdate=30 March 2014|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=10 June 2009}}</ref> In November 2014, Greaves' medal was sold at auction for \u00a344,000.<ref name=\"Medal sale\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-29993650 | title=Sir Stanley Matthews FA Cup medal sells for \u00a3220,000 | publisher=BBC news | date=11 November 2014 | accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nGreaves played only three more times for England after the 1966 World Cup, scoring a single goal. His final cap came in a 1\u20130 win over [[Austria national football team|Austria]] on 27 May 1967.<ref name=thefa/> At the time, he was [[Progression of England association football goalscoring record|England's all-time top goalscorer]] but was succeeded the following year by [[Bobby Charlton]]. Although Greaves was called up for [[UEFA Euro 1968]], he remained an unused substitute throughout the tournament, as the team finished in third place. He retired from international football early the following year after telling Ramsey that he had no intention of becoming a bit-part player in the England squad.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=387}}</ref> In total he scored 44 goals in 57 appearances for England.<ref name=thefa/> He is currently in fourth place on the all-time list of England goalscorers, behind [[Wayne Rooney]], [[Bobby Charlton]] and [[Gary Lineker]].<ref>{{cite web|title=England's Top Goalscorers|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/teamgoals/Goals_10-49.html|publisher=www.englandonline.co.uk|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref> Greaves holds [[England national football team records|the record]] for most hat-tricks for England&nbsp;\u2013 six in all.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hogan|first1=Chris|title=Jimmy Greaves|url=http://www.englandcaps.co.uk/jimmygreaves.html|website=englandcaps.co.uk|accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nGreaves was a prolific goalscorer, and cited his relaxed attitude as the reason for his assured composure and confidence.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=1}}</ref><ref name=\"goal machine\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/tottenham-hotspur/11582191/Jimmy-Greaves-the-goal-machine-behind-Spurs-glory-game-as-public-show-outpouring-of-support-after-stroke.html |title=Jimmy Greaves the goal machine behind Spurs glory game as public show outpouring of support after stroke |work=The Telegraph |last1=Winter |first1=Henry |date=4 May 2015 |accessdate=7 October 2019 }}</ref> He also had great acceleration and pace,<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=61}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Giles|title=Sport on TV: Drink was no bar to success for Moore and Greaves|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/england/3026142/Sport-on-TV-Drink-was-no-bar-to-success-for-Moore-and-Greaves.html|accessdate=31 July 2014|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=17 April 2002}}</ref> as well as great positional skills,<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=101}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jimmy Greaves|url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/history/past-players/jimmy-greaves/|accessdate=31 July 2014|work=tottenhamhotspur.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808045059/http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/history/past-players/jimmy-greaves/|archive-date=8 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> clinical finishing,<ref name=\"goal machine\"/> and opportunism inside the penalty area; he was also an excellent [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbler]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/2894617.stm|title=Blast from the past: Part five|publisher=BBC Sport|author1=Tom Fordyce|date=28 March 2003|accessdate=7 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2010/oct/15/the-joy-of-six-great-dribbles|title=The Joy of Six: Great dribbles|work=The Guardian|author1=Scott Murray|date=15 October 2010|accessdate=7 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcasting career==\nGreaves became a columnist at ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper in 1979.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moss |first1=Stephen |title=The Monday Interview: Jimmy Greaves |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/aug/25/sport.comment4 |accessdate=22 September 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=25 August 2003}}</ref> He continued to write his column until 2009, then began working as a columnist for ''[[The Sunday People]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=White|first=Jim|title=Former footballer Jimmy Greaves plays to a new crowd in second career as a comedian|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/premier-league/6931940/Former-footballer-Jimmy-Greaves-plays-to-a-new-crowd-in-second-career-as-a-comedian.html|accessdate=13 April 2014|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=5 January 2010}}</ref> He worked as a pundit on ''[[Star Soccer]]'' from 1980, and later co-presented ''[[The Saturday Show (1982 TV series)|The Saturday Show]]'' before he was selected as a pundit for [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s coverage of the [[1982 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=454}}</ref> From there he worked on ''[[World of Sport (British TV programme)|World of Sport]]'' and ''[[On the Ball (British TV programme)|On the Ball]]'', where he struck up a partnership with [[Ian St John]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=458}}</ref> [[Greg Dyke]] also hired Greaves to work as a television reviewer and presenter on ''[[TV-am]]'' in what Dyke admitted was a way of \"dumbing down\" the programme to attract more viewers.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=461}}</ref> From October 1985 to April 1992 he and St. John presented a popular Saturday lunchtime football programme called ''[[Saint and Greavsie]]''.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=466}}</ref> He went on to work as a team captain on ''[[Sporting Triangles]]'', opposite [[Andy Gray (footballer, born 1955)|Andy Gray]] and [[Emlyn Hughes]].<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=475}}</ref> His career in television came to an end as the [[Premier League]] was starting up, and he believed that his light-hearted approach to football was not considered serious enough for television bosses at the time.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=494}}</ref> Despite this he continued as a pundit at Central Television until 1998.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Richardson |first1=Andy |title=Big Ron: We should pray for Greavesie |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/big-ron-should-pray-greavesie-9178494 |accessdate=22 September 2019 |work=Birmingham Mail |date=4 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe released his autobiography, ''Greavsie'', in 2003. Greaves has also written numerous books in partnership with his lifelong friend, the journalist and author [[Norman Giller]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Giller|first1=Norman|title=Time to praise the man who set the goals standard|url=http://www.sportsjournalists.co.uk/the-giller-memorandum/time-to-praise-the-man-who-set-the-goals-standard/|publisher=Sports Journalists' Association|accessdate=13 August 2014|date=27 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGreaves married Irene Barden at [[Romford]] register office on 26 March 1958,<ref name=upinarms/> and though the pair went through a divorce process during the height of his alcoholism, it was never finalised and they reunited after three months apart.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=443}}</ref> Jimmy and Irene remarried on 7 September 2017 in [[Danbury, Essex|Danbury]], Essex.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/frail-football-legend-jimmy-greaves-11141589|title=Football legend Jimmy Greaves remarries ex-wife six decades after first wedding|first=Tom|last=Hopkinson|date=10 September 2017|website=mirror}}</ref> They had four children, Lynn, Mitzi, [[Danny Greaves (footballer)|Danny]] (who was a professional footballer with [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]]), and Andrew.<ref>{{cite news|author=Stephen Moss |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/aug/25/sport.comment4 |title=The Monday Interview: Jimmy Greaves |work=The Guardian |date=25 August 2003 |accessdate=29 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsjournalists.co.uk/the-giller-memorandum/messi-anic-fervour-of-striker-to-match-greavsie/ |title=Messi-anic fervour of striker to match Greavsie |publisher=Sports Journalists' Association |accessdate=29 September 2013}}</ref> They also had another son, Jimmy Greaves Jr, who died before his first birthday.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=183}}</ref>\n\nWhilst playing for [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] Greaves took out a \u00a31,000 bank loan to start a packing business with his brother-in-law.<ref name=\"page 416\">{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=416}}</ref> By the end of his playing career this company had an annual turnover of over \u00a31 million.<ref name=\"page 416\"/> He had a number of different business interests, including a travel agency.<ref>{{harvnb|Greaves|2004|p=425}}</ref> Greaves entered the [[1970 London to Mexico World Cup Rally]]. In his first ever rally, alongside co-driver, [[Tony Fall]], Greaves drove a [[Ford Escort (Europe)|Ford Escort]] to a sixth-place finish out of the 96 entrants.<ref name=upinarms>{{cite news|last=Shaw|first=Phil|title=Jimmy Greaves: 'John Terry sleeps with some bird and everyone's up in arms'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/jimmy-greaves-john-terry-sleeps-with-some-bird-and-everyones-up-in-arms-1891631.html|accessdate=17 June 2012|newspaper=The Independent|date=7 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=People|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1083597/index.htm|accessdate=30 March 2014|newspaper=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n\nGreaves underwent surgery on an artery in his neck after suffering a mild stroke in February 2012.<ref>{{cite web|author=Press Association |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/feb/26/jimmy-greaves-recovery-stroke |title=England great Jimmy Greaves making full recovery after stroke|work=The Guardian |date=26 February 2012 |accessdate=29 September 2013}}</ref> After a full recovery, he experienced a severe stroke in May 2015 which left him unable to speak. He was placed in intensive care and, according to doctors, was expected to undergo a slow recovery.<ref name=care>{{cite web|title=Jimmy Greaves: Former England & Spurs striker in intensive care|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32580282|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32594079 | title=Jimmy Greaves: Former striker faces 'slow recovery' after stroke | publisher=BBC Sport | date=5 May 2015 | accessdate=6 May 2015}}</ref> He left hospital after a month, his health having \"improved considerably\" according to Greaves' friend and agent Terry Baker.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/jun/12/jimmy-greaves-leaves-hospital-after-stroke | title=Jimmy Greaves leaves hospital a month after suffering severe stroke | work=The Guardian | date=12 June 2015 | accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref> In February 2016, although slowly recovering from the stroke, Greaves was in a wheelchair and had been told that he would never walk again.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/10185073/jimmy-greaves-told-he-will-never-walk-again | title=Jimmy Greaves told he will never walk again | publisher=Sky Sports | accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref>\nIn early April 2020 Greaves was admitted to hospital, being treated for an unspecified illness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/52209724|title=Jimmy Greaves: Former England, Spurs, Chelsea & West Ham striker admitted to hospital|date=8 April 2020|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n{|\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Season&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Division\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]||[[1957\u201358 Football League|1957\u201358]]||[[Football League First Division|First Division]]||35||22||2||0||0||0||0||0||37||22\n|-\n|[[1958\u201359 Football League|1958\u201359]]||First Division||42||32||2||2||0||0||3||3||47||37\n|-\n|[[1959\u201360 Football League|1959\u201360]]||First Division||40||