iction Society |accessdate=2012-04-09 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66nnsGGRI?url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2012-hugo-awards/ |archivedate=2012-04-09 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hugo13\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2013-hugo-awards/ |title=2013 Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=2013-04-03 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906045317/http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2013-hugo-awards/ |archivedate=2015-09-06 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hugo14\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2014-hugo-awards/ |title=2014 Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=2014-04-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906071016/http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2014-hugo-awards/ |archivedate=2015-09-06 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hugo15\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2015-hugo-awards/ |title=2015 Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=2015-09-06 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905132816/http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2015-hugo-awards/ |archivedate=2015-09-05 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hugo16\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2016-hugo-awards/ |title=2016 Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=2016-04-27 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.thehugoawards.org%2Fhugo-history%2F2016-hugo-awards%2F&date=2017-08-11 |archivedate=2017-08-11 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hugo17\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2017-hugo-awards/ |title=2017 Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=2017-08-11 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.thehugoawards.org%2Fhugo-history%2F2017-hugo-awards%2F&date=2017-08-11 |archivedate=2017-08-11 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hugo18\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2018-hugo-awards/ |title=2018 Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=2018-04-02}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hugo19\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2019-hugo-awards/ |title=2019 Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=2019-04-02}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hugo20\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2020-hugo-awards/ |title=2020 Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Hugo39\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1939-retro-hugo-awards/|title=1939 Retro Hugo Awards|publisher=World Science Fiction Society|accessdate=2014-04-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422100119/http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1939-retro-hugo-awards/ |archivedate=2016-04-22 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hugo41\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1941-retro-hugo-awards/ |title=1941 Retro Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=2016-04-27 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814012002/http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1941-retro-hugo-awards/ |archivedate=2017-08-14 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hugo43\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1943-retro-hugo-awards/ |title=1943 Retro Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=2018-04-02}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hugo44\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1944-retro-hugo-awards/ |title=1944 Retro Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=2019-08-19}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hugo45\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1945-retro-hugo-awards/ |title=1945 Retro Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hugo46\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1946-retro-hugo-awards/ |title=1946 Retro Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=2010-04-19 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yVVKYXP8?url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1946-retro-hugo-awards/ |archivedate=2011-05-07 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hugo51\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1951-retro-hugo-awards/ |title=1951 Retro Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=2010-04-19 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yVVKlO0b?url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1951-retro-hugo-awards/ |archivedate=2011-05-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hugo54\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1954-retro-hugo-awards/ |title=1954 Retro Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=2010-04-19 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yVVKyJ1k?url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1954-retro-hugo-awards/ |archivedate=2011-05-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://thehugoawards.org/ Hugo Award official site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110920202744/http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/HugoNomList.html List of Hugo Award nominees] in ''[[Locus (magazine)|Locus]]'' magazine\n\n{{Hugo Awards}}\n{{Hugo Award Best Novelette}}\n\n{{featured list}}\n[[Category:Hugo Awards|Novelette]]\n[[Category:Short story awards]]\n", "name_user": "BPK2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWinners and nominees", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugo_Award_for_Best_Novelette"}
{"title_page": "Ryan Rowland-Smith", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian baseball player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2014}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| image=Ryan_Rowland_Smith_2008.jpg\n| image_size=240px\n| caption=Rowland-Smith with the Seattle Mariners\n| name=Ryan Rowland-Smith\n| position=[[Pitcher]]\n| bats=Left\n| throws=Left\n| team =\n| number =\n| birth_date={{birth date and age|df=yes|1983|1|26}}\n| birth_place=[[Sydney]], [[Australia]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate=22 June\n| debutyear=2007\n| debutteam=Seattle Mariners\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=April 14\n|finalyear=2014\n|finalteam=Arizona Diamondbacks\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n|stat1value=12\u201317\n|stat2label=[[Earned run average]]\n|stat2value=4.57\n|stat3label=[[Strikeout]]s\n|stat3value=229\n| teams=\n* [[Seattle Mariners]] ({{mlby|2007}}\u2013{{mlby|2010}})\n* [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] ({{mlby|2014}})\n* [[EDA Rhinos]] ({{by|2015}})\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{bb|AUS}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Baseball at the Summer Olympics|Olympics]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[Baseball at the 2004 Summer Olympics|Athens 2004]] | Team Competition}} \n}}\n'''Ryan Benjamin Rowland-Smith''' (born 26 January 1983), is an Australian former [[professional baseball]] [[pitcher]]. He previously played in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) for the [[Seattle Mariners]] and [[Arizona Diamondbacks]]. Rowland-Smith also represented Australia in the [[World Baseball Classic]] three times and in the [[Baseball at the 2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Summer Olympics]]. He batted and threw left-handed.\n\nBorn in [[Sydney]], Rowland-Smith grew up watching MLB games on videocassette. Signed out of high school by the Seattle Mariners, he spent the next several years pitching for their [[Minor League Baseball|minor league]] teams. Promoted to Seattle for the first time in July 2007, he struck out the first batter he faced, former Mariners' star [[Ken Griffey, Jr.]]. Rowland-Smith began 2008 as a [[relief pitcher]] for the Mariners but was sent to the minor leagues briefly in July to work on becoming a [[starting pitcher]]. He rejoined the team in August and remained in their starting rotation the rest of the year. In 2009, he made one start for the Mariners at the beginning of the year before going on the [[disabled list]] with triceps tendinitis. Rejoining the team in July, he completed the eighth inning in three of his remaining starts for Seattle. In 2010, he made a career-high 20 starts for the Mariners but posted a 1\u201310 record and a 6.75 [[earned run average]] (ERA). Seattle allowed him to become a [[free agent]] after the year.\n\nOver the next three seasons, Rowland-Smith pitched in the minor leagues for several teams. In 2014, he began the season with the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]], much to his excitement as the Diamondbacks were opening the 2014 season in Australia. His time with the Diamondbacks did not last long, as the team [[designated for assignment|designated him for assignment]] on April 18. Rowland-Smith pitched for some minor league teams the remainder of the year, then joined the [[EDA Rhinos]] of the [[Chinese Professional Baseball League]] in 2015. He pitched for the [[Brisbane Bandits]] of the [[Australian Baseball League]] in January of 2017, then retired after the [[2017 World Baseball Classic]].\n\n==Early life==\nRowland-Smith was born January 26, 1983, in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]. His father is Australian celebrity trainer Rob Rowland-Smith, known as \"The Sandhill Warrior\".<ref name=\"growing up\"/> Julie White, his mother, is a retired high school [[physical education]] teacher.<ref name=\"growing up\"/> Rob and Julie divorced when Ryan was three, and Rowland-Smith grew up with his mother and sister in [[Newcastle, New South Wales]].<ref name=\"growing up\"/> He was a baseball fan from childhood, though he had to watch games on video cassettes because [[Major League Baseball]] was not televised in Australia at the time. The videos he had were of the [[1992 World Series]] and the [[1993 World Series]]. Rowland-Smith started playing baseball himself at the age of 12.<ref name=\"growing up\">{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/mariners/ms-ryan-rowland-smith-from-a-land-down-under/\n |title=M's Ryan Rowland-Smith from a land down under |author=Geoff Baker |date=February 19, 2008 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nesn.com/2010/03/australian-pitcher-ryan-rowlandsmith-shares-unique-training-techniques/|title=Australian Pitcher Ryan Rowland-Smith Shares Unique Training Techniques|work=NESN|date=March 3, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> He graduated from [[Newcastle High School (Australia)|Newcastle High School]] in [[Newcastle, New South Wales]], Australia, in December 2000.<ref name=\"reference\"/> The [[Seattle Mariners]], one of the only [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) teams that scouted Australia at the time, signed Rowland-Smith as a non-drafted [[free agent]] on November 19, 2000. \"I signed it before the ink dried,\" Rowland-Smith said of his contract. \"It was the only opportunity I was going to get.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com/arizona/story/welcome-home-mate-031814|title=Welcome home, mate: MLB arm living dream with Aussie series|work=Fox Sports|date=March 18, 2014|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=0fUNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LnoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6737,4953576&dq=ryan+rowland-smith&hl=en |title=St. Petersburg Times \u2013 24 Nov 2000 |date=24 November 2000 |accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===2001\u201304 seasons===\nRowland-Smith began his pro career in 2001 with the [[Minor League Baseball#Rookie|Rookie level]] [[Arizona League Mariners]]. In 17 [[Relief pitcher|relief]] appearances, he allowed just one [[home run]] in {{frac|33|1|3}} [[innings pitched]].<ref name=\"minors\"/> He split the 2002 season between the [[Single-A (baseball)|Single-A]] [[Wisconsin Timber Rattlers]] and the Single-A short-season [[Everett AquaSox]]. With Wisconsin to begin the season, he appeared in 12 games (eight starts), posting a 1\u20132 record and a 6.75 [[earned run average]] (ERA).<ref name=\"minors\"/> In the middle of the season, he was demoted to Everett.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sherwin |first=Bob |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20020623&slug=minors23 |title=Mariners farm report: Everett the United Nations of Northwest |work=The Seattle Times |date=June 23, 2002 |accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref> He appeared in 18 games (six starts) with Everett, posting a 4\u20131 [[Win-loss record (pitching)|record]], a 2.77 ERA, 58 [[strikeouts]], and 58 [[hits allowed]] in {{frac|61|2|3}} innings pitched.<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\nIn 2003, Rowland-Smith pitched for Wisconsin again, appearing in 13 games. He had a 3\u20130 record, a 1.11 ERA, and 37 strikeouts in {{frac|32|1|3}} innings. During the year, he also pitched for the Single-A advanced [[Inland Empire 66ers]]. In 15 games with the 66ers, he lost one game, posted a 3.20 ERA, struck out 15, and allowed 12 hits over {{frac|19|2|3}} innings pitched. He had a 1.90 ERA and 52 strikeouts combined between Wisconsin and Inland Empire.<ref name=\"minors\"/> Rowland-Smith played the entire 2004 season with Inland Empire, appearing in 29 games. He split the season between the [[bullpen]] and the [[starting rotation]], going 5\u20133 with a 3.79 ERA as a starter. He struck out 119 batters in 99{{frac|2|3}} innings and held opponents to a .276 [[batting average]].<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\n===2005 season===\nThe [[Minnesota Twins]] selected Rowland-Smith in the Major League portion of the [[Rule 5 draft results#2004|2004 Rule 5 draft]].<ref name=\"reference\"/> He spent most of 2005 [[spring training]] with the Twins.<ref name=\"reference\"/> Ultimately, Minnesota decided not to keep him on the roster all season, and he was returned to Seattle on March 25.<ref name=\"reference\"/> He spent the season with the [[Double-A (baseball)|Double-A]] [[San Antonio Missions]], setting a career high with 122 innings pitched. In 33 games (17 starts), he had a 6\u20137 record, a 4.35 ERA, 102 strikeouts, and 133 hits allowed.<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\n===2006 season===\nRowland-Smith split the 2006 season with Inland Empire and San Antonio. With the 66ers, he gave up seven runs (four earned) in {{frac|6|1|3}} innings pitched over seven games.<ref name=\"minors\"/> He spent a greater portion of the season with the Missions.<ref name=\"minors\"/> On August 25, he struck out a season-high seven batters in {{frac|4|1|3}} innings.<ref>{{cite web ||last=Bowles|first=C. J. |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20060826&content_id=1630134&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Notes: Beltre back in lineup|work=MLB.com|date=August 26, 2006|accessdate=April 14, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305020311/http://m.mlb.com/news/article/1630134|archivedate=March 5, 2016}}</ref> In 23 games (one start) for the Missions, he had a 1\u20133 record, a 2.83 ERA, 48 strikeouts, and 38 hits allowed in {{frac|41|1|3}} innings.<ref name=\"minors\"/> Following the regular season, he played with the [[Peoria Javelinas]] in the [[Arizona Fall League]].<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\n===2007 season===\nFor the first time in 2007, Rowland-Smith pitched for the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] [[Tacoma Rainiers]] of the [[Pacific Coast League]] (PCL). He made 25 relief appearances for the team, posting a 3\u20134 record, a 3.67 ERA, 50 strikeouts, and 35 hits allowed in {{frac|41|2|3}} innings before getting promoted to the Mariners in June.<ref name=\"minors\"/> Rowland-Smith made his major league debut for the Mariners on June 22, against the [[Cincinnati Reds]] in a game notable for being the return of longtime Mariners star [[Ken Griffey, Jr.]], to [[Safeco Field]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Andriesen|first=David|url=https://www.seattlepi.com/sports/baseball/article/All-hugs-and-smiles-for-Ken-Griffey-Jr-s-return-1241628.php|title=All hugs and smiles for Ken Griffey Jr.'s return|work=The Seattle Post-Intelligencer|date=June 22, 2007|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Griffey wound up being the first batter Rowland-Smith faced; he struck him out, proceeding to pitch 1{{frac|1|3}} scoreless innings in a 16\u20131 Mariners loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA200706220.shtml|title=Cincinnati Reds at Seattle Mariners Box Score, June 22, 2007|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"wedding\"/> He did not allow a run in {{frac|10|2|3}} consecutive innings spanning five games from August 22 to 31.<ref name=\"2007 Rowland-Smith\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=rowlary01&t=p&year=2007|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith 2007 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> In the first game of that stretch, he struck out a career-high six batters in four scoreless innings of relief in an 8\u20134 loss to the Twins.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stevenson |first=David |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-167945851/rowland-smith-only-bright.html |title=Rowland-Smith only bright spot |publisher=Accessmylibrary.com |date= |accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref> He earned his first career win September 13 against the [[Tampa Bay Devil Rays]], pitching {{frac|2|1|3}} scoreless innings in a game the Mariners trailed 7\u20131 but rallied to win 8\u20137.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hickey|first=John|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/baseball/331677_mari14.html |title=Mariners rally late again, beat Devil Rays |work=The SeattlePost-Intelligencer|date=September 13, 2007|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> In his [[Rookie (baseball)|rookie]] year with Seattle, he struck out 42 batters in 38{{frac|1|3}} innings, posting a 1\u20130 record and limiting opposing batters to 39 hits.<ref name=\"reference\"/> After the season, he pitched for Lara in the [[Venezuelan Winter League]]. Rowland-Smith said about his offseason:\n{{cquote|I'd like to get four or five starts [in Venezuela], go back to Australia and try to get in shape for next season. I don't know what's going to happen after that, but they told me they want me down there, starting. I just wanted to get up here and show I could throw strikes at this level. Now that I've been here for a while, I've got so much more confidence.|||Ryan Rowland-Smith, ''The Seattle Times'': September 18, 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/mariners/ms-notebook-rowland-smith-set-for-venezuela-stint/ |title=M's Notebook: Rowland-Smith set for Venezuela stint|work=The Seattle Times|date=September 18, 2007|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>}}\n\n===2008 season===\n[[File:Ryan Rowland-Smith 2008.jpg|thumb|200px|Rowland-Smith pitching against the [[Oakland Athletics]].]]\nRowland-Smith began the season exclusively as a reliever, making 32 relief appearances before making two starts prior to the [[2008 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star break]].<ref name=\"2008 Rowland-Smith\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=rowlary01&t=p&year=2008|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith 2008 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He collected his first [[Save (baseball)|save]] April 8 against the [[Tampa Bay Rays]] in Seattle's 6\u20135 win, tossing {{frac|1|2|3}} innings and retiring all five batters he faced while protecting one-run lead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/TBA/TBA200804080.shtml|title=Seattle Mariners at Tampa Bay Rays Box Score, April 8, 2008|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> His first Major League start came July 1 against the [[Toronto Blue Jays]]; Rowland-Smith threw three scoreless innings before getting replaced by [[Roy Corcoran]] with two outs in the fourth inning after allowing three runs that inning. The Mariners rallied to win 7\u20136.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA200807010.shtml|title=Toronto Blue Jays at Seattle Mariners Box Score, July 1, 2008|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He made three more relief appearances before being optioned to Tacoma on July 20 to be converted to a starting pitcher.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thiel|first=Art|url=https://www.seattlepi.com/sports/article/Riggleman-making-most-of-impossible-situation-1279848.php|title=Riggleman making most of impossible situation|work=The Seattle Post-Intelligencer|date=July 20, 2008|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He went 2\u20130 with a 2.89 ERA in three starts for the Rainiers, holding opponents to a .185 batting average before joining Seattle's rotation on August 9.<ref name=\"minors\"/><ref name=\"2008 Rowland-Smith\"/> From August 21 until the end of the season, he posted a 2.56 ERA.<ref name=\"2008 Rowland-Smith\"/> Against the [[Oakland Athletics]] on August 21, he took the loss but held the team to four hits in seven innings, keeping Oakland scoreless except for a solo home run by [[Emil Brown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA200808210.shtml|title=Oakland Athletics at Seattle Mariners Box Score, August 21, 2008|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He faced Oakland again in his final start of the year on September 27, allowing three runs in {{frac|6|2|3}} innings this time but picking up the win in a 7\u20133 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA200809270.shtml|title=Oakland Athletics at Seattle Mariners Box Score, September 27, 2008|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> In 47 games (12 starts) with the Mariners in 2008, he had a 5\u20133 record, a 3.42 ERA, 77 strikeouts, and 114 hits allowed in {{frac|118|1|3}} innings.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===2009 season===\nIn a 2009 spring training game against the [[Colorado Rockies]], Rowland-Smith recorded two [[Single (baseball)|singles]] in two [[at bat]]s. This was his first time batting against a live pitcher since he was 17 years old. He used teammate [[Jeff Clement]]'s bat.<ref>{{cite web|last=Street|first=Jim|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/print.jsp?ymd=20090314&content_id=3988346&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb&affiliateId=CommentWidget |title=Rowland-Smith, star hitter?|work=MLB.com|date=March 14, 2009|accessdate=April 14, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303172448/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/print.jsp?ymd=20090314&content_id=3988346&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb&affiliateId=CommentWidget|archivedate=March 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of the season, he started one game before being placed on the disabled list with triceps tendinitis. He was sent to Tacoma for rehab starts, but a dismal outing on June 5 in which he allowed 12 runs in {{frac|4|2|3}} innings prompted the Mariners to option him to Tacoma.<ref name=\"minors\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Street|first=Jim|url=http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090606&content_id=5175924&vkey=news_sea&fext=.jsp&c_id=sea |title=Rowland-Smith struggles in rehab stint|work=MLB.com|date=June 5, 2009|accessdate=April 14, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222195322/http://m.mariners.mlb.com/news/article/5175924|archivedate=December 22, 2015}}</ref> In July, he was promoted and added to the starting rotation after going 5\u20133 with a 4.31 ERA in 10 starts for Tacoma.<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n<ref>{{cite web|last=Street|first=Jim|url=http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090722&content_id=6004676&vkey=news_sea&fext=.jsp&c_id=sea |title=Rowland-Smith recalled to start Friday|work=MLB.com|date=July 22, 2009|accessdate=April 14, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305080449/http://m.mariners.mlb.com/news/article/6004676|archivedate=March 5, 2016}}</ref> He lasted seven innings in his first start back on July 24, allowing four runs and taking the loss in a 9\u20130 defeat to the [[Cleveland Indians]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA200907240.shtml|title=Cleveland Indians at Seattle Mariners Box Score, July 24, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Five days later, he limited the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] to two runs over seven innings and picked up his first win of the year in the Mariners' 3\u20132 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA200907290.shtmlhttps://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA200907290.shtml|title=Toronto Blue Jays at Seattle Mariners Box Score, July 29, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Three times in 2009, he threw a season-high eight innings, including a game on September 16 when he limited the [[Chicago White Sox]] to one run in a 4\u20131 victory.<ref name=\"Rowland's gem\"/><ref name=\"2009 Rowland-Smith\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=rowlary01&t=p&year=2009|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith 2009 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Rowland-Smith made his last start of the year for the Mariners on October 3, holding the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] to one run over {{frac|6|2|3}} innings in a 2\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA200910030.shtml|title=Texas Rangers at Seattle Mariners Box Score, October 3, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRowland-Smith finished the season with a 5\u20134 record, a 3.74 ERA, 52 strikeouts, and 87 hits allowed in {{frac|96|1|3}} innings over 15 games (all starts).<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===2010 season===\nRowland-Smith's game against the White Sox on September 16, 2009, left Christian Caple of MLB.com excited about his chances for next season:\n{{cquote|Ryan Rowland-Smith is turning into a can't-miss starter for the Mariners...there's no reason why he can't head into [2010 spring training] as the team's No. 2 starter.|||Christian Caple, ''MLB.com'': September 17, 2009.<ref name=\"Rowland's gem\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090916&content_id=6998216&vkey=news_sea&fext=.jsp&c_id=sea|title=Rowland-Smith's gem quiets White Sox \u2013 Mariners lefty dominates South Siders in another strong start|last=Caple|first=Christian|date=17 September 2009|publisher=MLB.com|accessdate=14 October 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611090821/http://m.mariners.mlb.com/news/article/6998216/|archivedate=June 11, 2015}}</ref>}}\nIn fact, Rowland-Smith started the 2010 season as the third starter in the Mariners' rotation, behind [[Felix Hernandez]] and [[Ian Snell]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/tgl.cgi?team=SEA&t=p&year=2010|title=2010 Seattle Mariners Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> He struggled to begin the season, posting a 7.62 ERA in his first eight starts while losing all four of his decisions. After the shortest start of his career on May 18, in which he gave up seven runs in {{frac|2|2|3}} innings, the Mariners moved him to the bullpen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com/mlb/story/mariners-send-rowlandsmith-to-bullpen-87000359-051910|title=Mariners send Rowland-Smith to bullpen|work=Fox Sports|date=May 19, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Rowland-Smith returned to the rotation on June 5, when [[Doug Fister]] had to miss a start because of shoulder fatigue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com/mlb/story/mariners-doug-fister-to-miss-1-start-04739697-060510|title=Mariners\u2019 Doug Fister to miss 1 start|work=Fox Sports|date=June 5, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The Mariners lost to the Angels 11\u20132, but Rowland-Smith limited Los Angeles to one run in five innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA201006050.shtml|title=Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim at Seattle Mariners Box Score, June 5, 2010|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> After that, he continued to be used as a starter.<ref name=\"2010 Rowland-Smith\"/> He held the [[Cincinnati Reds]] scoreless for six innings on June 20, earning his first win of the year in a 1\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite web|last=Johns|first=Greg|url=https://blog.seattlepi.com/baseball/2010/06/20/another-gem-ms-shut-out-reds-1-0-once-again/|title=Another gem: M\u2019s shut out Reds 1-0 once again|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|date=June 20, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The win, however, would be his only victory of the year.<ref name=\"reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/rowlary01.shtml|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith Stats|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> On July 27, he gave up 11 runs over five innings in an 11\u20130 loss to the White Sox. The Mariners left him in the game that long because they wanted to preserve their bullpen. After the game, he was placed on the disabled list with a lower back strain, which Rob Neyer of ESPN speculated was a \"phantom injury\" designed to get him off the roster, since the Mariners could not send him to the minor leagues without exposing him to [[Waivers (baseball)|waivers]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Neyer|first=Rob|url=https://www.espn.com/blog/sweetspot/post/_/id/4533/ms-finally-diagnose-rowland-smiths-injury|title=M's finally diagnose Rowland-Smith's 'injury'|work=ESPN|date=July 28, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Sent to rehab in Tacoma, he rejoined the team in September when rosters expanded.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mayers|first=Joshua|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/mariners/ryan-rowland-smith-activated-from-disabled-list-called-up-from-rehab-assignment-in-tacoma/|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith activated from disabled list, called up from rehab assignment in Tacoma |work=The Seattle Times|date=September 3, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nUpon his activation from the disabled list, Rowland-Smith was mainly used out of the bullpen except for the last game of the season, October 3, in which he gave up two runs in five innings and had a no-decision in a 4\u20133 loss to the Athletics.<ref name=\"2010 Rowland-Smith\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=rowlary01&t=p&year=2010|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith 2010 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2010/10/03/mariners-beat-athletics-4-3-to-complete-sweep/|title=Athletics Beat Mariners 4-3 To Complete Sweep|work=sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com|date=October 3, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> 20 of Rowland-Smith's 27 appearances in 2010 were starts (a career-high), but only one of those was a win, as opposed to ten losses. He had a 6.75 ERA and gave up 141 hits in {{frac|109|1|3}} innings.<ref name=\"reference\"/> However, Rowland-Smith was the Mariners' nominee for the [[Roberto Clemente Award]], given annually to the MLB player who \"best represents the game through extraordinary character, community involvement, philanthropy and positive contributions, both on and off the field.\"<ref name=\"Root Sports\"/><ref name=\"MLB\">{{cite web|last=Newman|first=Mark|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/roberto-clemente-award-nominees-c199668596|title=Vote on social media for Roberto Clemente Award|work=MLB.com|date=September 6, 2016|accessdate=May 24, 2009}}</ref> Seattle made him their candidate because of his work in hosting the Mariners Care Cystic Fibrosis Foundation golf tournament.<ref name=\"Root Sports\"/> In November 2010, the [[Sydney Blue Sox]] named Rowland-Smith as one of the players on their 35-man roster for the inaugural [[Australian Baseball League]] season, but he never pitched for them.<ref name=\"minors\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=rowlan001rya|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith Minor, Fall & Winter League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Proszenko|first=Adrian|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/sydneys-28-dugout-diamonds-20101030-1785h.html|title=Sydney's 28 dugout diamonds|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=October 31, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> On December 2, 2010, the Mariners decided not to offer him a new contract, making him a free agent.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===2011\u20132013 seasons===\nOn December 9, 2010, the [[Houston Astros]] signed Rowland-Smith to a one-year contract.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://houston.astros.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101209&content_id=16290358&vkey=news_hou&c_id=hou |title=Astros sign Rowland-Smith to one-year deal &#124; astros.com: News |publisher=Houston.astros.mlb.com |accessdate=14 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212060641/http://houston.astros.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101209&content_id=16290358&vkey=news_hou&c_id=hou |archivedate=12 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He spent most of the season with the PCL's [[Oklahoma City RedHawks]]. In 22 games (19 starts), he had a 2\u201310 record, a 6.19 ERA, 87 strikeouts, and 131 hits allowed in {{frac|104|2|3}} innings.<ref name=\"minors\"/> After the season, he became a free agent.<ref name=\"reference\"/> During the offseason, he played winter ball for the [[Leones de Ponce (baseball)|Leones de Ponce]] of the [[Puerto Rican Winter League]], losing three of his five starts.<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\nThe [[Chicago Cubs]] signed Rowland-Smith to a minor league deal on February 2, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Price|first=Satchel|url=http://chicago.sbnation.com/chicago-cubs/2012/2/2/2767785/chicago-cubs-sign-ryan-rowland-smith-to-minor-league-contract-mlb-rumors-2012 |title=Chicago Cubs Sign Ryan Rowland-Smith To Minor League Contract |work=SB Nation Chicago |date= February 3, 2012|accessdate=June 14, 2013}}</ref> He spent the whole season with the [[Iowa Cubs]] of the PCL, where he was used more as a reliever (22 games) than a starter (eight games). He had a 3\u20136 record, a 3.94 ERA, 62 strikeouts, and 75 hits allowed in {{frac|77|2|3}} innings pitched.<ref name=\"minors\"/> After the season, he became a free agent.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nOn February 24, 2013, the [[Boston Red Sox]] signed Rowland-Smith to a minor league deal.<ref name=\"reference\"/> In 37 games in relief for the [[Pawtucket Red Sox]], their Triple-A team, he had a 7\u20130 record and a 1.55 ERA.<ref name=\"minors\"/> However, he never got to pitch for Boston because of an illness.<ref name=\"SCG\">{{cite web|last=Stevenson|first=Amy|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/more-sports/aussie-pitcher-ryan-rowlandsmith-pumped-for-arizona-diamondbacks-v-la-dodgers-at-scg/news-story/42b6c5cd2c117ef14dfa4db223d7286e|title=Aussie pitcher Ryan Rowland-Smith pumped for Arizona Diamondbacks v LA Dodgers at SCG|work=The Courier Mail|date=January 30, 2014|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2014 season===\nRowland-Smith signed a minor league contract with the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] prior to the 2014 season.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cotillo|first=Chris|url=http://www.mlbdailydish.com/2013/11/18/5117316/diamondbacks-sign-ryan-rowland-smith-to-minor-league-deal |title=Diamondbacks sign Ryan Rowland-Smith to minor league deal |work=SB Nation |date=November 5, 2013 |accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref> He was excited about joining Arizona because they were opening their season with two regular-season games in March against the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]] in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gilbert|first=Steve|url=https://www.mlb.com/dbacks/news/d-backs-pitcher-ryan-rowland-smith-excited-for-busy-week-in-australia/c-69265420|title=Rowland-Smith excited for busy week in Australia|work=MLB.com|date=March 13, 2014|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|To play Major League Baseball in Australia is such a special thing...For me to be able to play MLB in my own backyard is bizarre to be honest with you. To be able to put my American life and Australian life together will be pretty special.|||Ryan Rowland-Smith, ''The Daily Telegraph'', January 30, 2014.<ref name=\"SCG\"/>}}\n\nWhile he did not pitch in the Australian series, Rowland-Smith was on the Diamondbacks roster at the beginning of the 2014 season, his first time on a major league roster since 2010 with the Mariners.<ref name=\"reference\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=rowlary01&t=p&year=2014|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith 2014 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He made what would be his last appearance in the major leagues on April 14, giving up two runs (one earned) in the final two innings of a 7\u20133 loss to the [[New York Mets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/ARI/ARI201404140.shtml|title=New York Mets at Arizona Diamondbacks Box Score, April 14, 2014|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> [[Designated for assignment]] on April 18, he cleared waivers and elected to become a free agent on April 21.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Adams|first=Steve | url=http://bleacherreport.com/tb/dcWXA |title = Ryan Rowland-Smith Elects Free Agency |work=Bleacher Report|date=April 22, 2014|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> In six games with the Diamondbacks, he posted a 4.91 ERA, allowing five runs (four earned) in {{frac|7|1|3}} innings of work.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nOn April 25, Rowland-Smith signed a minor league deal with the [[Toronto Blue Jays]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bluebirdbanter.com/2014/4/25/5653672/jays-sign-ryan-rowland-smith-to-a-minor-league-deal |title=Jays sign Ryan Rowland-Smith to a minor league deal |date=April 25, 2014 |accessdate=April 25, 2014 |first=Tom |last=Dakers |work=Bluebird Banter}}</ref> He pitched for the Triple-A [[Buffalo Bisons]] of the International League, allowing 8 runs in just 14 innings before drawing his release on June 11.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Todd|first=Jeff| url=http://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2014/06/minor-moves-marmol-pina-exposito-barden.html |title = Minor Moves: Rowland-Smith, Hill, Marmol, Pina|work=MLB Trade Rumors|date=June 11, 2014|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> On June 28, he signed a minor league deal with the [[Cincinnati Reds]]. He made one start for the [[Louisville Bats]] of the International League but was mostly used out of the bullpen, posting a 4.20 ERA in 12 games with no wins or losses.<ref name=\"minors\"/> On August 2, the Reds released him.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===Last years===\nFor 2015, Rowland-Smith left the United States, signing with the [[EDA Rhinos]] of the [[Chinese Professional Baseball League]], located in Taiwan.<ref>{{cite web|last=White|first=R. J. |url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/report-ryan-rowland-smith-signs-with-taiwanese-team/|title=Report: Ryan Rowland-Smith signs with Taiwanese team|work=cbssports.com|date=February 16, 2015|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He appeared in nine games with the team, posting a 1\u20134 record and a 4.70 ERA in 46 innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpbl.com.tw/players/person.html?&player_id=B0I8|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith|work=CPBL|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> For winter 2015-16, Rowland-Smith pitched in one game for [[Gigantes del Cibao]] of the [[Dominican Winter League]].<ref name=\"minors\"/> After not pitching in 2016, Rowland-Smith signed with the [[Brisbane Bandits]] of the [[Australian Baseball League]] in January 2017. In four starts with the team, he won one game but had a 6.35 ERA.<ref name=\"minors\"/> However, he was part of a Brisbane club which won its second consecutive ABLchampionship. Rowland-Smith planned to retire after the season once he had finished playing for Australia in the World Baseball Classic.<ref>{{cite web|last=Malone|first=Paul|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/brisbane-bandits-win-backtoback-abl-titles/news-story/b1d9e622a4521cdd28aad93dfed8fe96|date=February 13, 2017|title=Brisbane Bandits win back-to-back ABL titles|work=The Courier-Mail|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International play==\nRowland-Smith represented his native Australia in multiple international tournaments throughout his career. He played for [[Australia national baseball team|Australia]] in the [[Baseball at the 2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Summer Olympic games]], making four relief appearances, going 2\u20130 with a 1.23 ERA allowing only six hits and five walks while striking out 5. He helped the team to a silver medal. They made it to the championship game before falling to [[Cuba national baseball team|Cuba]], 6\u20132.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gardner|first=Michelle|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SBCB&p_theme=sbcb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=104D371671B43DB1&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Rowland-Smith brings back medal |work=The Sun|date=August 28, 2004|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Rowland-Smith's teammates on the Inland Empire 66ers paid close attention to the gold medal game, cheering on their teammate.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gardner|first=Michelle|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SBCB&p_theme=sbcb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=104B5A022EAE68E8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Sixers' Rowland-Smith medals|work=The Sun|date=August 26, 2004|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the start of the 2006 season, Rowland-Smith was added to the [[Australia national baseball team]] for the [[2006 World Baseball Classic]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Manuel|first=John|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/news/060218wbcaus.html |title=Australia Announces World Baseball Classic Roster|work=Baseball America|date=February 18, 2006|accessdate=April 14, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060326201924/https://www.baseballamerica.com/today/news/060218wbcaus.html|archivedate=March 26, 2006}}</ref> However, he was unable to pitch in the Classic because of a sore elbow.<ref>{{cite web |last=Mullen|first=Maureen|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20060304&content_id=1334800&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Notes: Brassington knuckles down|work=MLB.com|date=March 5, 2006|accessdate=April 14, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402081218/http://m.mlb.com/news/article/1334800|archivedate=April 2, 2017}}</ref> Rowland-Smith once again represented Australia in the [[2013 World Baseball Classic]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Meisel|first=Zack|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20121203&content_id=40505114&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Cabrera, Wright, Cano among stars in Classic|work=MLB.com|date=February 27, 2013|accessdate=April 14, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306025541/http://m.mlb.com/news/article/40505114|archivedate=March 6, 2016}}</ref> The team was eliminated after losing all three of its games in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/mlb/news/4481866-world-baseball-classic-2013-results-scores-tv-schedule-pool-standings|title=World Baseball Classic: Results of all games|work=Sporting News|date=March 2, 2013|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBefore he retired, Rowland-Smith represented Australia one last time at the [[2017 World Baseball Classic]]. First, he pitched with the team in the [[2017 World Baseball Classic \u2013 Qualifier 1]] from February 11 to 14, 2016. In Australia's second game of the qualifier (the first against South Africa), Rowland-Smith pitched three scoreless innings in relief of [[Warwick Saupold]], allowing two hits and striking out three.<ref>{{cite web|last=Adler|first=Por Niall|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/australia-beats-south-africa-in-wbc-qualifier-c164325486|title=Australia rides combined gem to Qualifier final|work=MLB.com|date=February 12, 2016|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Australia defeated the Philippines and South Africa twice to advance in the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|last=Randhawa|first=Manny|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/world-baseball-classic-preview-team-australia-c213549596|title=WBC 2017 preview: Breaking down Australia |work=MLB.com|date=January 14, 2017|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> \"On paper, as far as rosters go, we have the best roster, we have the most depth,\" he said of the team during the qualifier.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lian|first=Jotham|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/world-baseball-classic-australia-confident-before-qualifier-20160202-gmjbix.html|title=World Baseball Classic: Australia confident before qualifier|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=February 2, 2016|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> It was Australia's fourth-straight World Baseball Classic qualified for, but they failed to advance past the first round, going 1-2 with a win over [[China national baseball team|China]] and losses to [[Japan national baseball team|Japan]] and [[Cuba national baseball team|Cuba]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com.au/espn/story/_/id/18870501/cuba-loss-sends-australia-packing-world-baseball-classic|title=Cuba loss sends Australia packing at WBC|work=ESPN|date=March 10, 2017|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Post-playing career==\nRowland-Smith is currently a baseball television analyst for [[Root Sports Northwest]], appearing on the pre- and post-game shows for [[Seattle Mariners]] broadcasts. He is also a baseball radio analyst for [[KIRO (AM)|ESPN710 Seattle]], appearing on Mariners post-game shows. Rowland-Smith said that baseball and talking were the two things he enjoyed doing the most; thus, being a commentator was the perfect occupation for him.<ref name=\"Root Sports\">{{cite web|url=https://northwest.rootsports.com/for-fans-only/meet-the-talent/|title=Meet the Talent|work=northwest.rootsports.com|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> He and fellow Australian ballplayer [[Trent Oeltjen]] co-founded NxtGen Baseball, a training camp for young baseball players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nxtgenbaseball.com/about/|title=About|work=NxtGen Baseball|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRowland-Smith's grandfather was a former New South Wales minister for sport and recreation.<ref name=\"growing up\"/> His older sister, Rhiannon, is a competitive [[surfing|surfer]].<ref name=\"growing up\"/> While surfing is not his profession, Rowland-Smith avidly pursues it as a hobby.<ref name=\"Root Sports\"/>\n\nRowland-Smith was married in 2013 to American actress Amanda Aardsma.<ref name=\"wedding\">{{cite web|last=Walker|first=Martin|url=https://www.newcastleherald.com.au/story/3702888/living-the-dream/|title=Pitching ace Ryan Rowland-Smith plans comeback |work=The Newcastle Herald|date=February 5, 2016|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Amanda is the sister of Rowland-Smith's former teammate [[David Aardsma]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Baker|first=Geoff|date=December 25, 2010|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/mariners/where-are-they-now-ryan-rowland-smith/|title=Where Are They Now: Ryan Rowland-Smith|work=The Seattle Times|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> He became friends with Griffey, Jr., victim of his first major league strikeout, who attended Rowland-Smith's wedding in 2013.<ref name=\"wedding\"/>\n\nRowland-Smith is the first player with a hyphenated last name ever to appear in a major league game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/baseball/315553_mbok14.html |title=Mariners Notebook: Power arm joins bullpen |author=John Hickey |date=May 13, 2007 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer |accessdate=January 29, 2010}}</ref> During his career, he maintained his own blog to keep up with fans.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/al/2009-08-11-1258310629_x.htm |title=Mariners hold forum to highlight social media |author=Tim Booth |date=11 August 2009 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=usatoday.com |accessdate=29 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Rowland-Smith appeared on the television show [[American Ninja Warrior]] in the Seattle Qualifying Round but fell on Lunatic Ledges, the second obstacle.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Nikki|url=https://www.americanninjawarriornation.com/2019/6/24/18657960/american-ninja-warrior-season-11-2019-seattle-tacoma-qualifier-recap-result|title=Seattle/Tacoma Qualifiers recap: A location full of firsts, twists, and fun|work=SB Nation|date=June 24, 2019|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{baseballstats|mlb=434884|espn=6183|br=r/rowlary01|fangraphs=3245|brm=rowlan001rya}}, or [http://www.cpbl.com.tw/players/person.html?&player_id=B0I8 CPBL], or [https://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/R/Prowlr002.htm Retrosheet], or [http://www.pelotabinaria.com.ve/beisbol/mostrar.php?ID=rowlrya001 Pelota Binaria (Venezuelan Winter League)], or [http://www.prolebrity.com/profile/ryanrowlandsmith/?blog=1 Ryan Rowland-Smith's Blog]\n\n{{Australia roster 2006 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{Australia roster 2013 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{Australia roster 2017 World Baseball Classic}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rowland-Smith, Ryan}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Arizona Diamondbacks players]]\n[[Category:Arizona League Mariners players]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate baseball players in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate baseball players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Baseball players at the 2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Brisbane Bandits players]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Cardenales de Lara players]]\n[[Category:EDA Rhinos players]]\n[[Category:Estrellas Orientales players]]\n[[Category:Everett AquaSox players]]\n[[Category:Gigantes del Cibao players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Astros players]]\n[[Category:Inland Empire 66ers of San Bernardino players]]\n[[Category:Iowa Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Leones de Ponce players]]\n[[Category:Louisville Bats players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball players from Australia]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma City RedHawks players]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in baseball]]\n[[Category:Olympic baseball players of Australia]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Pawtucket Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:Peoria Javelinas players]]\n[[Category:San Antonio Missions players]]\n[[Category:Seattle Mariners broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Seattle Mariners players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Tacoma Rainiers players]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin Timber Rattlers players]]\n[[Category:2006 World Baseball Classic players]]\n[[Category:2013 World Baseball Classic players]]\n[[Category:2017 World Baseball Classic players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian baseball player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2014}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| image=Ryan_Rowland_Smith_2008.jpg\n| image_size=240px\n| caption=Rowland-Smith with the Seattle Mariners\n| name=Ryan Rowland-Smith\n| position=[[Pitcher]]\n| bats=Left\n| throws=Left\n| team =\n| number =\n| birth_date={{birth date and age|df=yes|1983|1|26}}\n| birth_place=[[Sydney]], [[Australia]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate=22 June\n| debutyear=2007\n| debutteam=Seattle Mariners\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=April 14\n|finalyear=2014\n|finalteam=Arizona Diamondbacks\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n|stat1value=12\u201317\n|stat2label=[[Earned run average]]\n|stat2value=4.57\n|stat3label=[[Strikeout]]s\n|stat3value=229\n| teams=\n* [[Seattle Mariners]] ({{mlby|2007}}\u2013{{mlby|2010}})\n* [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] ({{mlby|2014}})\n* [[EDA Rhinos]] ({{by|2015}})\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{bb|AUS}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Baseball at the Summer Olympics|Olympics]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[Baseball at the 2004 Summer Olympics|Athens 2004]] | Team Competition}} \n}}\n'''Ryan Benjamin Rowland-Smith''' (born 26 January 1983), is an Australian former [[professional baseball]] [[pitcher]]. He previously played in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) for the [[Seattle Mariners]] and [[Arizona Diamondbacks]]. Rowland-Smith also represented Australia in the [[World Baseball Classic]] three times and in the [[Baseball at the 2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Summer Olympics]]. He batted and threw left-handed.\n\nBorn in [[Sydney]], Rowland-Smith grew up watching MLB games on videocassette. Signed out of high school by the Seattle Mariners, he spent the next several years pitching for their [[Minor League Baseball|minor league]] teams. Promoted to Seattle for the first time in July 2007, he struck out the first batter he faced, former Mariners' star [[Ken Griffey, Jr.]]. Rowland-Smith began 2008 as a [[relief pitcher]] for the Mariners but was sent to the minor leagues briefly in July to work on becoming a [[starting pitcher]]. He rejoined the team in August and remained in their starting rotation the rest of the year. In 2009, he made one start for the Mariners at the beginning of the year before going on the [[disabled list]] with triceps tendinitis. Rejoining the team in July, he completed the eighth inning in three of his remaining starts for Seattle. In 2010, he made a career-high 20 starts for the Mariners but posted a 1\u201310 record and a 6.75 [[earned run average]] (ERA). Seattle allowed him to become a [[free agent]] after the year.\n\nOver the next three seasons, Rowland-Smith pitched in the minor leagues for several teams. In 2014, he began the season with the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]], much to his excitement as the Diamondbacks were opening the 2014 season in Australia. His time with the Diamondbacks did not last long, as the team [[designated for assignment|designated him for assignment]] on April 18. Rowland-Smith pitched for some minor league teams the remainder of the year, then joined the [[EDA Rhinos]] of the [[Chinese Professional Baseball League]] in 2015. He pitched for the [[Brisbane Bandits]] of the [[Australian Baseball League]] in January of 2017, then retired after the [[2017 World Baseball Classic]].\n\n==Early life==\nRowland-Smith was born January 26, 1983, in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]. His father is Australian celebrity trainer Rob Rowland-Smith, known as \"The Sandhill Warrior\".<ref name=\"growing up\"/> Julie White, his mother, is a retired high school [[physical education]] teacher.<ref name=\"growing up\"/> Rob and Julie divorced when Ryan was three, and Rowland-Smith grew up with his mother and sister in [[Newcastle, New South Wales]].<ref name=\"growing up\"/> He was a baseball fan from childhood, though he had to watch games on video cassettes because [[Major League Baseball]] was not televised in Australia at the time. The videos he had were of the [[1992 World Series]] and the [[1993 World Series]]. Rowland-Smith started playing baseball himself at the age of 12.<ref name=\"growing up\">{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/mariners/ms-ryan-rowland-smith-from-a-land-down-under/\n |title=M's Ryan Rowland-Smith from a land down under |author=Geoff Baker |date=February 19, 2008 |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nesn.com/2010/03/australian-pitcher-ryan-rowlandsmith-shares-unique-training-techniques/|title=Australian Pitcher Ryan Rowland-Smith Shares Unique Training Techniques|work=NESN|date=March 3, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> He graduated from [[Newcastle High School (Australia)|Newcastle High School]] in [[Newcastle, New South Wales]], Australia, in December 2000.<ref name=\"reference\"/> The [[Seattle Mariners]], one of the only [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) teams that scouted Australia at the time, signed Rowland-Smith as a non-drafted [[free agent]] on November 19, 2000. \"I signed it before the ink dried,\" Rowland-Smith said of his contract. \"It was the only opportunity I was going to get.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com/arizona/story/welcome-home-mate-031814|title=Welcome home, mate: MLB arm living dream with Aussie series|work=Fox Sports|date=March 18, 2014|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=0fUNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LnoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6737,4953576&dq=ryan+rowland-smith&hl=en |title=St. Petersburg Times \u2013 24 Nov 2000 |date=24 November 2000 |accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===2001\u201304 seasons===\nRowland-Smith began his pro career in 2001 with the [[Minor League Baseball#Rookie|Rookie level]] [[Arizona League Mariners]]. In 17 [[Relief pitcher|relief]] appearances, he allowed just one [[home run]] in {{frac|33|1|3}} [[innings pitched]].<ref name=\"minors\"/> He split the 2002 season between the [[Single-A (baseball)|Single-A]] [[Wisconsin Timber Rattlers]] and the Single-A short-season [[Everett AquaSox]]. With Wisconsin to begin the season, he appeared in 12 games (eight starts), posting a 1\u20132 record and a 6.75 [[earned run average]] (ERA).<ref name=\"minors\"/> In the middle of the season, he was demoted to Everett.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sherwin |first=Bob |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20020623&slug=minors23 |title=Mariners farm report: Everett the United Nations of Northwest |work=The Seattle Times |date=June 23, 2002 |accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref> He appeared in 18 games (six starts) with Everett, posting a 4\u20131 [[Win-loss record (pitching)|record]], a 2.77 ERA, 58 [[strikeouts]], and 58 [[hits allowed]] in {{frac|61|2|3}} innings pitched.<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\nIn 2003, Rowland-Smith pitched for Wisconsin again, appearing in 13 games. He had a 3\u20130 record, a 1.11 ERA, and 37 strikeouts in {{frac|32|1|3}} innings. During the year, he also pitched for the Single-A advanced [[Inland Empire 66ers]]. In 15 games with the 66ers, he lost one game, posted a 3.20 ERA, struck out 15, and allowed 12 hits over {{frac|19|2|3}} innings pitched. He had a 1.90 ERA and 52 strikeouts combined between Wisconsin and Inland Empire.<ref name=\"minors\"/> Rowland-Smith played the entire 2004 season with Inland Empire, appearing in 29 games. He split the season between the [[bullpen]] and the [[starting rotation]], going 5\u20133 with a 3.79 ERA as a starter. He struck out 119 batters in 99{{frac|2|3}} innings and held opponents to a .276 [[batting average]].<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\n===2005 season===\nThe [[Minnesota Twins]] selected Rowland-Smith in the Major League portion of the [[Rule 5 draft results#2004|2004 Rule 5 draft]].<ref name=\"reference\"/> He spent most of 2005 [[spring training]] with the Twins.<ref name=\"reference\"/> Ultimately, Minnesota decided not to keep him on the roster all season, and he was returned to Seattle on March 25.<ref name=\"reference\"/> He spent the season with the [[Double-A (baseball)|Double-A]] [[San Antonio Missions]], setting a career high with 122 innings pitched. In 33 games (17 starts), he had a 6\u20137 record, a 4.35 ERA, 102 strikeouts, and 133 hits allowed.<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\n===2006 season===\nRowland-Smith split the 2006 season with Inland Empire and San Antonio. With the 66ers, he gave up seven runs (four earned) in {{frac|6|1|3}} innings pitched over seven games.<ref name=\"minors\"/> He spent a greater portion of the season with the Missions.<ref name=\"minors\"/> On August 25, he struck out a season-high seven batters in {{frac|4|1|3}} innings.<ref>{{cite web ||last=Bowles|first=C. J. |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20060826&content_id=1630134&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Notes: Beltre back in lineup|work=MLB.com|date=August 26, 2006|accessdate=April 14, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305020311/http://m.mlb.com/news/article/1630134|archivedate=March 5, 2016}}</ref> In 23 games (one start) for the Missions, he had a 1\u20133 record, a 2.83 ERA, 48 strikeouts, and 38 hits allowed in {{frac|41|1|3}} innings.<ref name=\"minors\"/> Following the regular season, he played with the [[Peoria Javelinas]] in the [[Arizona Fall League]].<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\n===2007 season===\nFor the first time in 2007, Rowland-Smith pitched for the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] [[Tacoma Rainiers]] of the [[Pacific Coast League]] (PCL). He made 25 relief appearances for the team, posting a 3\u20134 record, a 3.67 ERA, 50 strikeouts, and 35 hits allowed in {{frac|41|2|3}} innings before getting promoted to the Mariners in June.<ref name=\"minors\"/> Rowland-Smith made his major league debut for the Mariners on June 22, against the [[Cincinnati Reds]] in a game notable for being the return of longtime Mariners star [[Ken Griffey, Jr.]], to [[Safeco Field]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Andriesen|first=David|url=https://www.seattlepi.com/sports/baseball/article/All-hugs-and-smiles-for-Ken-Griffey-Jr-s-return-1241628.php|title=All hugs and smiles for Ken Griffey Jr.'s return|work=The Seattle Post-Intelligencer|date=June 22, 2007|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Griffey wound up being the first batter Rowland-Smith faced; he struck him out, proceeding to pitch 1{{frac|1|3}} scoreless innings in a 16\u20131 Mariners loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA200706220.shtml|title=Cincinnati Reds at Seattle Mariners Box Score, June 22, 2007|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"wedding\"/> He did not allow a run in {{frac|10|2|3}} consecutive innings spanning five games from August 22 to 31.<ref name=\"2007 Rowland-Smith\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=rowlary01&t=p&year=2007|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith 2007 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> In the first game of that stretch, he struck out a career-high six batters in four scoreless innings of relief in an 8\u20134 loss to the Twins.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stevenson |first=David |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-167945851/rowland-smith-only-bright.html |title=Rowland-Smith only bright spot |publisher=Accessmylibrary.com |date= |accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref> He earned his first career win September 13 against the [[Tampa Bay Devil Rays]], pitching {{frac|2|1|3}} scoreless innings in a game the Mariners trailed 7\u20131 but rallied to win 8\u20137.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hickey|first=John|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/baseball/331677_mari14.html |title=Mariners rally late again, beat Devil Rays |work=The SeattlePost-Intelligencer|date=September 13, 2007|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> In his [[Rookie (baseball)|rookie]] year with Seattle, he struck out 42 batters in 38{{frac|1|3}} innings, posting a 1\u20130 record and limiting opposing batters to 39 hits.<ref name=\"reference\"/> After the season, he pitched for Lara in the [[Venezuelan Winter League]]. Rowland-Smith said about his offseason:\n{{cquote|I'd like to get four or five starts [in Venezuela], go back to Australia and try to get in shape for next season. I don't know what's going to happen after that, but they told me they want me down there, starting. I just wanted to get up here and show I could throw strikes at this level. Now that I've been here for a while, I've got so much more confidence.|||Ryan Rowland-Smith, ''The Seattle Times'': September 18, 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/mariners/ms-notebook-rowland-smith-set-for-venezuela-stint/ |title=M's Notebook: Rowland-Smith set for Venezuela stint|work=The Seattle Times|date=September 18, 2007|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>}}\n\n===2008 season===\n[[File:Ryan Rowland-Smith 2008.jpg|thumb|200px|Rowland-Smith pitching against the [[Oakland Athletics]].]]\nRowland-Smith began the season exclusively as a reliever, making 32 relief appearances before making two starts prior to the [[2008 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star break]].<ref name=\"2008 Rowland-Smith\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=rowlary01&t=p&year=2008|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith 2008 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He collected his first [[Save (baseball)|save]] April 8 against the [[Tampa Bay Rays]] in Seattle's 6\u20135 win, tossing {{frac|1|2|3}} innings and retiring all five batters he faced while protecting one-run lead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/TBA/TBA200804080.shtml|title=Seattle Mariners at Tampa Bay Rays Box Score, April 8, 2008|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> His first Major League start came July 1 against the [[Toronto Blue Jays]]; Rowland-Smith threw three scoreless innings before getting replaced by [[Roy Corcoran]] with two outs in the fourth inning after allowing three runs that inning. The Mariners rallied to win 7\u20136.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA200807010.shtml|title=Toronto Blue Jays at Seattle Mariners Box Score, July 1, 2008|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He made three more relief appearances before being optioned to Tacoma on July 20 to be converted to a starting pitcher.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thiel|first=Art|url=https://www.seattlepi.com/sports/article/Riggleman-making-most-of-impossible-situation-1279848.php|title=Riggleman making most of impossible situation|work=The Seattle Post-Intelligencer|date=July 20, 2008|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He went 2\u20130 with a 2.89 ERA in three starts for the Rainiers, holding opponents to a .185 batting average before joining Seattle's rotation on August 9.<ref name=\"minors\"/><ref name=\"2008 Rowland-Smith\"/> From August 21 until the end of the season, he posted a 2.56 ERA.<ref name=\"2008 Rowland-Smith\"/> Against the [[Oakland Athletics]] on August 21, he took the loss but held the team to four hits in seven innings, keeping Oakland scoreless except for a solo home run by [[Emil Brown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA200808210.shtml|title=Oakland Athletics at Seattle Mariners Box Score, August 21, 2008|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He faced Oakland again in his final start of the year on September 27, allowing three runs in {{frac|6|2|3}} innings this time but picking up the win in a 7\u20133 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA200809270.shtml|title=Oakland Athletics at Seattle Mariners Box Score, September 27, 2008|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> In 47 games (12 starts) with the Mariners in 2008, he had a 5\u20133 record, a 3.42 ERA, 77 strikeouts, and 114 hits allowed in {{frac|118|1|3}} innings.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===2009 season===\nIn a 2009 spring training game against the [[Colorado Rockies]], Rowland-Smith recorded two [[Single (baseball)|singles]] in two [[at bat]]s. This was his first time batting against a live pitcher since he was 17 years old. He used teammate [[Jeff Clement]]'s bat.<ref>{{cite web|last=Street|first=Jim|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/print.jsp?ymd=20090314&content_id=3988346&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb&affiliateId=CommentWidget |title=Rowland-Smith, star hitter?|work=MLB.com|date=March 14, 2009|accessdate=April 14, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303172448/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/print.jsp?ymd=20090314&content_id=3988346&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb&affiliateId=CommentWidget|archivedate=March 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of the season, he started one game before being placed on the disabled list with triceps tendinitis. He was sent to Tacoma for rehab starts, but a dismal outing on June 5 in which he allowed 12 runs in {{frac|4|2|3}} innings prompted the Mariners to option him to Tacoma.<ref name=\"minors\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Street|first=Jim|url=http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090606&content_id=5175924&vkey=news_sea&fext=.jsp&c_id=sea |title=Rowland-Smith struggles in rehab stint|work=MLB.com|date=June 5, 2009|accessdate=April 14, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222195322/http://m.mariners.mlb.com/news/article/5175924|archivedate=December 22, 2015}}</ref> In July, he was promoted and added to the starting rotation after going 5\u20133 with a 4.31 ERA in 10 starts for Tacoma.<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n<ref>{{cite web|last=Street|first=Jim|url=http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090722&content_id=6004676&vkey=news_sea&fext=.jsp&c_id=sea |title=Rowland-Smith recalled to start Friday|work=MLB.com|date=July 22, 2009|accessdate=April 14, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305080449/http://m.mariners.mlb.com/news/article/6004676|archivedate=March 5, 2016}}</ref> He lasted seven innings in his first start back on July 24, allowing four runs and taking the loss in a 9\u20130 defeat to the [[Cleveland Indians]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA200907240.shtml|title=Cleveland Indians at Seattle Mariners Box Score, July 24, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Five days later, he limited the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] to two runs over seven innings and picked up his first win of the year in the Mariners' 3\u20132 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA200907290.shtmlhttps://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA200907290.shtml|title=Toronto Blue Jays at Seattle Mariners Box Score, July 29, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Three times in 2009, he threw a season-high eight innings, including a game on September 16 when he limited the [[Chicago White Sox]] to one run in a 4\u20131 victory.<ref name=\"Rowland's gem\"/><ref name=\"2009 Rowland-Smith\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=rowlary01&t=p&year=2009|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith 2009 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Rowland-Smith made his last start of the year for the Mariners on October 3, holding the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] to one run over {{frac|6|2|3}} innings in a 2\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA200910030.shtml|title=Texas Rangers at Seattle Mariners Box Score, October 3, 2009|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRowland-Smith finished the season with a 5\u20134 record, a 3.74 ERA, 52 strikeouts, and 87 hits allowed in {{frac|96|1|3}} innings over 15 games (all starts).<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===2010 season===\nRowland-Smith's game against the White Sox on September 16, 2009, left Christian Caple of MLB.com excited about his chances for next season:\n{{cquote|Ryan Rowland-Smith is turning into a can't-miss starter for the Mariners...there's no reason why he can't head into [2010 spring training] as the team's No. 2 starter.|||Christian Caple, ''MLB.com'': September 17, 2009.<ref name=\"Rowland's gem\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090916&content_id=6998216&vkey=news_sea&fext=.jsp&c_id=sea|title=Rowland-Smith's gem quiets White Sox \u2013 Mariners lefty dominates South Siders in another strong start|last=Caple|first=Christian|date=17 September 2009|publisher=MLB.com|accessdate=14 October 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611090821/http://m.mariners.mlb.com/news/article/6998216/|archivedate=June 11, 2015}}</ref>}}\nIn fact, Rowland-Smith started the 2010 season as the third starter in the Mariners' rotation, behind [[Felix Hernandez]] and [[Ian Snell]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/tgl.cgi?team=SEA&t=p&year=2010|title=2010 Seattle Mariners Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> He struggled to begin the season, posting a 7.62 ERA in his first eight starts while losing all four of his decisions. After the shortest start of his career on May 18, in which he gave up seven runs in {{frac|2|2|3}} innings, the Mariners moved him to the bullpen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com/mlb/story/mariners-send-rowlandsmith-to-bullpen-87000359-051910|title=Mariners send Rowland-Smith to bullpen|work=Fox Sports|date=May 19, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Rowland-Smith returned to the rotation on June 5, when [[Doug Fister]] had to miss a start because of shoulder fatigue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com/mlb/story/mariners-doug-fister-to-miss-1-start-04739697-060510|title=Mariners\u2019 Doug Fister to miss 1 start|work=Fox Sports|date=June 5, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The Mariners lost to the Angels 11\u20132, but Rowland-Smith limited Los Angeles to one run in five innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA201006050.shtml|title=Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim at Seattle Mariners Box Score, June 5, 2010|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> After that, he continued to be used as a starter.<ref name=\"2010 Rowland-Smith\"/> He held the [[Cincinnati Reds]] scoreless for six innings on June 20, earning his first win of the year in a 1\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite web|last=Johns|first=Greg|url=https://blog.seattlepi.com/baseball/2010/06/20/another-gem-ms-shut-out-reds-1-0-once-again/|title=Another gem: M\u2019s shut out Reds 1-0 once again|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|date=June 20, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The win, however, would be his only victory of the year.<ref name=\"reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/rowlary01.shtml|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith Stats|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> On July 27, he gave up 11 runs over five innings in an 11\u20130 loss to the White Sox. The Mariners left him in the game that long because they wanted to preserve their bullpen. After the game, he was placed on the disabled list with a lower back strain, which Rob Neyer of ESPN speculated was a \"phantom injury\" designed to get him off the roster, since the Mariners could not send him to the minor leagues without exposing him to [[Waivers (baseball)|waivers]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Neyer|first=Rob|url=https://www.espn.com/blog/sweetspot/post/_/id/4533/ms-finally-diagnose-rowland-smiths-injury|title=M's finally diagnose Rowland-Smith's 'injury'|work=ESPN|date=July 28, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Sent to rehab in Tacoma, he rejoined the team in September when rosters expanded.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mayers|first=Joshua|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/mariners/ryan-rowland-smith-activated-from-disabled-list-called-up-from-rehab-assignment-in-tacoma/|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith activated from disabled list, called up from rehab assignment in Tacoma |work=The Seattle Times|date=September 3, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nUpon his activation from the disabled list, Rowland-Smith was mainly used out of the bullpen except for the last game of the season, October 3, in which he gave up two runs in five innings and had a no-decision in a 4\u20133 loss to the Athletics.<ref name=\"2010 Rowland-Smith\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=rowlary01&t=p&year=2010|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith 2010 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2010/10/03/mariners-beat-athletics-4-3-to-complete-sweep/|title=Athletics Beat Mariners 4-3 To Complete Sweep|work=sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com|date=October 3, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> 20 of Rowland-Smith's 27 appearances in 2010 were starts (a career-high), but only one of those was a win, as opposed to ten losses. He had a 6.75 ERA and gave up 141 hits in {{frac|109|1|3}} innings.<ref name=\"reference\"/> However, Rowland-Smith was the Mariners' nominee for the [[Roberto Clemente Award]], given annually to the MLB player who \"best represents the game through extraordinary character, community involvement, philanthropy and positive contributions, both on and off the field.\"<ref name=\"Root Sports\"/><ref name=\"MLB\">{{cite web|last=Newman|first=Mark|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/roberto-clemente-award-nominees-c199668596|title=Vote on social media for Roberto Clemente Award|work=MLB.com|date=September 6, 2016|accessdate=May 24, 2009}}</ref> Seattle made him their candidate because of his work in hosting the Mariners Care Cystic Fibrosis Foundation golf tournament.<ref name=\"Root Sports\"/> In November 2010, the [[Sydney Blue Sox]] named Rowland-Smith as one of the players on their 35-man roster for the inaugural [[Australian Baseball League]] season, but he never pitched for them.<ref name=\"minors\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=rowlan001rya|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith Minor, Fall & Winter League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Proszenko|first=Adrian|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/sydneys-28-dugout-diamonds-20101030-1785h.html|title=Sydney's 28 dugout diamonds|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=October 31, 2010|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> On December 2, 2010, the Mariners decided not to offer him a new contract, making him a free agent.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===2011\u20132013 seasons===\nOn December 9, 2010, the [[Houston Astros]] signed Rowland-Smith to a one-year contract.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://houston.astros.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101209&content_id=16290358&vkey=news_hou&c_id=hou |title=Astros sign Rowland-Smith to one-year deal &#124; astros.com: News |publisher=Houston.astros.mlb.com |accessdate=14 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212060641/http://houston.astros.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101209&content_id=16290358&vkey=news_hou&c_id=hou |archivedate=12 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He spent most of the season with the PCL's [[Oklahoma City RedHawks]]. In 22 games (19 starts), he had a 2\u201310 record, a 6.19 ERA, 87 strikeouts, and 131 hits allowed in {{frac|104|2|3}} innings.<ref name=\"minors\"/> After the season, he became a free agent.<ref name=\"reference\"/> During the offseason, he played winter ball for the [[Leones de Ponce (baseball)|Leones de Ponce]] of the [[Puerto Rican Winter League]], losing three of his five starts.<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\nThe [[Chicago Cubs]] signed Rowland-Smith to a minor league deal on February 2, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Price|first=Satchel|url=http://chicago.sbnation.com/chicago-cubs/2012/2/2/2767785/chicago-cubs-sign-ryan-rowland-smith-to-minor-league-contract-mlb-rumors-2012 |title=Chicago Cubs Sign Ryan Rowland-Smith To Minor League Contract |work=SB Nation Chicago |date= February 3, 2012|accessdate=June 14, 2013}}</ref> He spent the whole season with the [[Iowa Cubs]] of the PCL, where he was used more as a reliever (22 games) than a starter (eight games). He had a 3\u20136 record, a 3.94 ERA, 62 strikeouts, and 75 hits allowed in {{frac|77|2|3}} innings pitched.<ref name=\"minors\"/> After the season, he became a free agent.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nOn February 24, 2013, the [[Boston Red Sox]] signed Rowland-Smith to a minor league deal.<ref name=\"reference\"/> In 37 games in relief for the [[Pawtucket Red Sox]], their Triple-A team, he had a 7\u20130 record and a 1.55 ERA.<ref name=\"minors\"/> However, he never got to pitch for Boston because of an illness.<ref name=\"SCG\">{{cite web|last=Stevenson|first=Amy|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/more-sports/aussie-pitcher-ryan-rowlandsmith-pumped-for-arizona-diamondbacks-v-la-dodgers-at-scg/news-story/42b6c5cd2c117ef14dfa4db223d7286e|title=Aussie pitcher Ryan Rowland-Smith pumped for Arizona Diamondbacks v LA Dodgers at SCG|work=The Courier Mail|date=January 30, 2014|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2014 season===\nRowland-Smith signed a minor league contract with the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] prior to the 2014 season.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cotillo|first=Chris|url=http://www.mlbdailydish.com/2013/11/18/5117316/diamondbacks-sign-ryan-rowland-smith-to-minor-league-deal |title=Diamondbacks sign Ryan Rowland-Smith to minor league deal |work=SB Nation |date=November 5, 2013 |accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref> He was excited about joining Arizona because they were opening their season with two regular-season games in March against the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]] in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gilbert|first=Steve|url=https://www.mlb.com/dbacks/news/d-backs-pitcher-ryan-rowland-smith-excited-for-busy-week-in-australia/c-69265420|title=Rowland-Smith excited for busy week in Australia|work=MLB.com|date=March 13, 2014|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|To play Major League Baseball in Australia is such a special thing...For me to be able to play MLB in my own backyard is bizarre to be honest with you. To be able to put my American life and Australian life together will be pretty special.|||Ryan Rowland-Smith, ''The Daily Telegraph'', January 30, 2014.<ref name=\"SCG\"/>}}\n\nWhile he did not pitch in the Australian series, Rowland-Smith was on the Diamondbacks roster at the beginning of the 2014 season, his first time on a major league roster since 2010 with the Mariners.<ref name=\"reference\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=rowlary01&t=p&year=2014|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith 2014 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He made what would be his last appearance in the major leagues on April 14, giving up two runs (one earned) in the final two innings of a 7\u20133 loss to the [[New York Mets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/ARI/ARI201404140.shtml|title=New York Mets at Arizona Diamondbacks Box Score, April 14, 2014|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> [[Designated for assignment]] on April 18, he cleared waivers and elected to become a free agent on April 21.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Adams|first=Steve | url=http://bleacherreport.com/tb/dcWXA |title = Ryan Rowland-Smith Elects Free Agency |work=Bleacher Report|date=April 22, 2014|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> In six games with the Diamondbacks, he posted a 4.91 ERA, allowing five runs (four earned) in {{frac|7|1|3}} innings of work.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nOn April 25, Rowland-Smith signed a minor league deal with the [[Toronto Blue Jays]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bluebirdbanter.com/2014/4/25/5653672/jays-sign-ryan-rowland-smith-to-a-minor-league-deal |title=Jays sign Ryan Rowland-Smith to a minor league deal |date=April 25, 2014 |accessdate=April 25, 2014 |first=Tom |last=Dakers |work=Bluebird Banter}}</ref> He pitched for the Triple-A [[Buffalo Bisons]] of the International League, allowing 8 runs in just 14 innings before drawing his release on June 11.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Todd|first=Jeff| url=http://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2014/06/minor-moves-marmol-pina-exposito-barden.html |title = Minor Moves: Rowland-Smith, Hill, Marmol, Pina|work=MLB Trade Rumors|date=June 11, 2014|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> On June 28, he signed a minor league deal with the [[Cincinnati Reds]]. He made one start for the [[Louisville Bats]] of the International League but was mostly used out of the bullpen, posting a 4.20 ERA in 12 games with no wins or losses.<ref name=\"minors\"/> On August 2, the Reds released him.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===Last years===\nFor 2015, Rowland-Smith left the United States, signing with the [[EDA Rhinos]] of the [[Chinese Professional Baseball League]], located in Taiwan.<ref>{{cite web|last=White|first=R. J. |url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/report-ryan-rowland-smith-signs-with-taiwanese-team/|title=Report: Ryan Rowland-Smith signs with Taiwanese team|work=cbssports.com|date=February 16, 2015|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He appeared in nine games with the team, posting a 1\u20134 record and a 4.70 ERA in 46 innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpbl.com.tw/players/person.html?&player_id=B0I8|title=Ryan Rowland-Smith|work=CPBL|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> For winter 2015-16, Rowland-Smith pitched in one game for [[Gigantes del Cibao]] of the [[Dominican Winter League]].<ref name=\"minors\"/> After not pitching in 2016, Rowland-Smith signed with the [[Brisbane Bandits]] of the [[Australian Baseball League]] in January 2017. In four starts with the team, he won one game but had a 6.35 ERA.<ref name=\"minors\"/> However, he was part of a Brisbane club which won its second consecutive ABLchampionship. Rowland-Smith planned to retire after the season once he had finished playing for Australia in the World Baseball Classic.<ref>{{cite web|last=Malone|first=Paul|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/brisbane-bandits-win-backtoback-abl-titles/news-story/b1d9e622a4521cdd28aad93dfed8fe96|date=February 13, 2017|title=Brisbane Bandits win back-to-back ABL titles|work=The Courier-Mail|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International play==\nRowland-Smith represented his native Australia in multiple international tournaments throughout his career. He played for [[Australia national baseball team|Australia]] in the [[Baseball at the 2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Summer Olympic games]], making four relief appearances, going 2\u20130 with a 1.23 ERA allowing only six hits and five walks while striking out 5. He helped the team to a silver medal. They made it to the championship game before falling to [[Cuba national baseball team|Cuba]], 6\u20132.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gardner|first=Michelle|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SBCB&p_theme=sbcb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=104D371671B43DB1&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Rowland-Smith brings back medal |work=The Sun|date=August 28, 2004|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Rowland-Smith's teammates on the Inland Empire 66ers paid close attention to the gold medal game, cheering on their teammate.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gardner|first=Michelle|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SBCB&p_theme=sbcb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=104B5A022EAE68E8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Sixers' Rowland-Smith medals|work=The Sun|date=August 26, 2004|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the start of the 2006 season, Rowland-Smith was added to the [[Australia national baseball team]] for the [[2006 World Baseball Classic]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Manuel|first=John|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/news/060218wbcaus.html |title=Australia Announces World Baseball Classic Roster|work=Baseball America|date=February 18, 2006|accessdate=April 14, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060326201924/https://www.baseballamerica.com/today/news/060218wbcaus.html|archivedate=March 26, 2006}}</ref> However, he was unable to pitch in the Classic because of a sore elbow.<ref>{{cite web |last=Mullen|first=Maureen|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20060304&content_id=1334800&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Notes: Brassington knuckles down|work=MLB.com|date=March 5, 2006|accessdate=April 14, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402081218/http://m.mlb.com/news/article/1334800|archivedate=APril 2, 2017}}</ref> Rowland-Smith once again represented Australia in the [[2013 World Baseball Classic]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Meisel|first=Zack|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20121203&content_id=40505114&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Cabrera, Wright, Cano among stars in Classic|work=MLB.com|date=February 27, 2013|accessdate=April 14, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306025541/http://m.mlb.com/news/article/40505114|archivedate=March 6, 2016}}</ref> The team was eliminated after losing all three of its games in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/mlb/news/4481866-world-baseball-classic-2013-results-scores-tv-schedule-pool-standings|title=World Baseball Classic: Results of all games|work=Sporting News|date=March 2, 2013|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBefore he retired, Rowland-Smith represented Australia one last time at the [[2017 World Baseball Classic]]. First, he pitched with the team in the [[2017 World Baseball Classic \u2013 Qualifier 1]] from February 11 to 14, 2016. In Australia's second game of the qualifier (the first against South Africa), Rowland-Smith pitched three scoreless innings in relief of [[Warwick Saupold]], allowing two hits and striking out three.<ref>{{cite web|last=Adler|first=Por Niall|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/australia-beats-south-africa-in-wbc-qualifier-c164325486|title=Australia rides combined gem to Qualifier final|work=MLB.com|date=February 12, 2016|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Australia defeated the Philippines and South Africa twice to advance in the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|last=Randhawa|first=Manny|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/world-baseball-classic-preview-team-australia-c213549596|title=WBC 2017 preview: Breaking down Australia |work=MLB.com|date=January 14, 2017|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> \"On paper, as far as rosters go, we have the best roster, we have the most depth,\" he said of the team during the qualifier.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lian|first=Jotham|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/world-baseball-classic-australia-confident-before-qualifier-20160202-gmjbix.html|title=World Baseball Classic: Australia confident before qualifier|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=February 2, 2016|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> It was Australia's fourth-straight World Baseball Classic qualified for, but they failed to advance past the first round, going 1-2 with a win over [[China national baseball team|China]] and losses to [[Japan national baseball team|Japan]] and [[Cuba national baseball team|Cuba]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com.au/espn/story/_/id/18870501/cuba-loss-sends-australia-packing-world-baseball-classic|title=Cuba loss sends Australia packing at WBC|work=ESPN|date=March 10, 2017|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Post-playing career==\nRowland-Smith is currently a baseball television analyst for [[Root Sports Northwest]], appearing on the pre- and post-game shows for [[Seattle Mariners]] broadcasts. He is also a baseball radio analyst for [[KIRO (AM)|ESPN710 Seattle]], appearing on Mariners post-game shows. Rowland-Smith said that baseball and talking were the two things he enjoyed doing the most; thus, being a commentator was the perfect occupation for him.<ref name=\"Root Sports\">{{cite web|url=https://northwest.rootsports.com/for-fans-only/meet-the-talent/|title=Meet the Talent|work=northwest.rootsports.com|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> He and fellow Australian ballplayer [[Trent Oeltjen]] co-founded NxtGen Baseball, a training camp for young baseball players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nxtgenbaseball.com/about/|title=About|work=NxtGen Baseball|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRowland-Smith's grandfather was a former New South Wales minister for sport and recreation.<ref name=\"growing up\"/> His older sister, Rhiannon, is a competitive [[surfing|surfer]].<ref name=\"growing up\"/> While surfing is not his profession, Rowland-Smith avidly pursues it as a hobby.<ref name=\"Root Sports\"/>\n\nRowland-Smith was married in 2013 to American actress Amanda Aardsma.<ref name=\"wedding\">{{cite web|last=Walker|first=Martin|url=https://www.newcastleherald.com.au/story/3702888/living-the-dream/|title=Pitching ace Ryan Rowland-Smith plans comeback |work=The Newcastle Herald|date=February 5, 2016|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Amanda is the sister of Rowland-Smith's former teammate [[David Aardsma]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Baker|first=Geoff|date=December 25, 2010|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/mariners/where-are-they-now-ryan-rowland-smith/|title=Where Are They Now: Ryan Rowland-Smith|work=The Seattle Times|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> He became friends with Griffey, Jr., victim of his first major league strikeout, who attended Rowland-Smith's wedding in 2013.<ref name=\"wedding\"/>\n\nRowland-Smith is the first player with a hyphenated last name ever to appear in a major league game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/baseball/315553_mbok14.html |title=Mariners Notebook: Power arm joins bullpen |author=John Hickey |date=May 13, 2007 |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer |accessdate=January 29, 2010}}</ref> During his career, he maintained his own blog to keep up with fans.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/al/2009-08-11-1258310629_x.htm |title=Mariners hold forum to highlight social media |author=Tim Booth |date=11 August 2009 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=usatoday.com |accessdate=29 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Rowland-Smith appeared on the television show [[American Ninja Warrior]] in the Seattle Qualifying Round but fell on Lunatic Ledges, the second obstacle.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Nikki|url=https://www.americanninjawarriornation.com/2019/6/24/18657960/american-ninja-warrior-season-11-2019-seattle-tacoma-qualifier-recap-result|title=Seattle/Tacoma Qualifiers recap: A location full of firsts, twists, and fun|work=SB Nation|date=June 24, 2019|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{baseballstats|mlb=434884|espn=6183|br=r/rowlary01|fangraphs=3245|brm=rowlan001rya}}, or [http://www.cpbl.com.tw/players/person.html?&player_id=B0I8 CPBL], or [https://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/R/Prowlr002.htm Retrosheet], or [http://www.pelotabinaria.com.ve/beisbol/mostrar.php?ID=rowlrya001 Pelota Binaria (Venezuelan Winter League)], or [http://www.prolebrity.com/profile/ryanrowlandsmith/?blog=1 Ryan Rowland-Smith's Blog]\n\n{{Australia roster 2006 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{Australia roster 2013 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{Australia roster 2017 World Baseball Classic}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rowland-Smith, Ryan}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Arizona Diamondbacks players]]\n[[Category:Arizona League Mariners players]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate baseball players in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate baseball players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Baseball players at the 2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Brisbane Bandits players]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Cardenales de Lara players]]\n[[Category:EDA Rhinos players]]\n[[Category:Estrellas Orientales players]]\n[[Category:Everett AquaSox players]]\n[[Category:Gigantes del Cibao players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Astros players]]\n[[Category:Inland Empire 66ers of San Bernardino players]]\n[[Category:Iowa Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Leones de Ponce players]]\n[[Category:Louisville Bats players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball players from Australia]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma City RedHawks players]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in baseball]]\n[[Category:Olympic baseball players of Australia]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Pawtucket Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:Peoria Javelinas players]]\n[[Category:San Antonio Missions players]]\n[[Category:Seattle Mariners broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Seattle Mariners players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Tacoma Rainiers players]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin Timber Rattlers players]]\n[[Catego