{"title_page": "Upcountry National Front", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Cleanup|reason=grammar, spelling, cohesion and tone|date=March 2020}}\n{{Update|date=March 2020}}\n{{Original research|date=March 2020}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n{{Distinguish|Up-Country People's Front}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Upcountry National Front\n| colors = {{colour box|Red,Yellow,Black}}\n| membership = \n| ideology = \n| religion = \n| national = Upcountry National Front\n| international = \n| affiliation1_title = \n| affiliation1 = \n| seats1_title = [[Sri Lankan Parliament|Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n| youth_wing = Upcountry National Front Youth Front\n| seats1 = \n| seats2_title = [[Provinces of Sri Lanka|Sri Lankan Provincial Councils]]\n| seats2 = \n| seats3_title = [[Local government in Sri Lanka|Local Government Bodies]]\n| seats3 = \n| symbol = \n| website = https://www.unfparty.com/\n| country = Sri Lanka\n| membership_year = \n| student_wing = \n| native_name = {{lang|si|\u0d9a\u0db3\u0dd4\u0d9a\u0dbb \u0da2\u0dcf\u0dad\u0dd2\u0d9a \u0db4\u0dd9\u0dbb\u0db8\u0dd4\u0dab}}<br />{{lang|ta|\u0bae\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0baf\u0b95 \u0ba4\u0bc7\u0b9a\u0bbf\u0baf \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0ba3\u0bbf}}\n| leader1_name = \n| logo = \n| flag = \n| logo_size = 250px\n| colorcode = {{upcountry national front/meta/color}}\n| leader = [[Rishi Senthil Raj]]\n| president = \n| secretary = S. Sivatharshini\n| founder = \n| slogan = \n| newspaper = \n| founded = \n| dissolved = \n| merger = \n| predecessor = \n| split = \n| merged = \n| successor = \n| headquarters = 86 Dunbar Road, Hatton, [[Hatton, Sri Lanka|Hatton]]\n| footnotes = \n}}The '''Upcountry National Front''' ({{lang-si|\u0d9a\u0db3\u0dd4\u0d9a\u0dbb \u0da2\u0dcf\u0dad\u0dd2\u0d9a \u0db4\u0dd9\u0dbb\u0db8\u0dd4\u0dab|translit=Upcountry National Front}}; {{lang-ta|\u0bae\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0baf\u0b95 \u0ba4\u0bc7\u0b9a\u0bbf\u0baf \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0ba3\u0bbf|translit=Upcountry National Front}}) is a Sri Lankan political party. The party's current leader is Dr. Rishi Senthil Raj and the secretary is S. Sivatharshini.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Upcountry National Front ===\nThe Upcountry National Front is a historical political party that can determine the ruler of Sri Lanka. The party was founded in Colombo on May 20, 2000. Its founder was Dr. Rishi Senthil Raj. Its trade union division was launched in 2004. The party has contested all the elections since 2004 and gained membership. Founded by its founder leader Rishi Senthil Raj in the early days of the \u201cUpcountry National Front\u201d, it was named as the \u201cWorkers Liberation Front\u201d. Its political wing was led by party leader Rishi Senthil Raj and Ayyadurai{{who|date=March 2020}} led the trade union wing.\n\nIn 2004, [[Santhanam Arulsamy]] and [[Palani Digambaran]], who split from the Upcountry People's Front, won two seats in the provincial council and became the provincial council education minister.{{who|date=March 2020}} In 2006, the party won 22 Pradeshiya Sabha members in a coalition in all areas of the hill country. Thikambaram{{who|date=March 2020}} left the party after a conflict of opinion between the Minister of Education and Dikambaram in the Provincial Council.{{when|date=March 2020}} Following the defeat in the ensuing elections, Education Minister Arul Sami left the party.\n\nIn 2013, the party renamed the \"Workers Liberation Front\" as the \"Upcountry National Front\". In 2013, the coalition formed a coalition with the Upcountry National Alliance (UPFA) and secured a provincial council seat in the Nuwara Eliya district. In 2014, Ayyadurai withdrew from the party and joined another union.\n\nSignificantly, Maithripala Sirisena's victory in the 2015 presidential election was a major factor in the national campaign of President Maithripala Sirisena's victory in the presidential election of 2015. It was because all the other upstart parties in the hill country had joined hands with the government. Since then, the Upcountry National Front has contributed to the success of the Tamil Progressive Alliance in the 2015 parliamentary election. In November 2015, it withdrew its support to the past government and joined the Alliance with [[Sri Lanka Podujana Peramuna]].\n\n=== Workers Liberation Front ===\nIn 2013 the WLF changed its name to Upcountry National Front (Upcountry National Front) and ....\n\n=== Alliance with Sri Lanka Podujana Peramuna ===\nIn November 2015 UNF Alliance with Sri Lanka Podujana Peramuna, a [[Political front|front]] for the [[Joint Opposition]]\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Political parties in Sri Lanka]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Cleanup|reason=grammar, spelling, cohesion and tone|date=March 2020}}\n{{Update|date=March 2020}}\n{{Original research|date=March 2020}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n{{Distinguish|Up-Country People's Front}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Upcountry National Front\n| colors = {{colour box|Red,Yellow,Black}}\n| membership = \n| ideology = \n| religion = \n| national = Upcountry National Front\n| international = \n| affiliation1_title = \n| affiliation1 = \n| seats1_title = [[Sri Lankan Parliament|Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n| youth_wing = Upcountry National Front Youth Front\n| seats1 = \n| seats2_title = [[Provinces of Sri Lanka|Sri Lankan Provincial Councils]]\n| seats2 = \n| seats3_title = [[Local government in Sri Lanka|Local Government Bodies]]\n| seats3 = \n| symbol = \n| website = https://www.unfparty.com/\n| country = Sri Lanka\n| membership_year = \n| student_wing = \n| native_name = {{lang|si|\u0d9a\u0db3\u0dd4\u0d9a\u0dbb \u0da2\u0dcf\u0dad\u0dd2\u0d9a \u0db4\u0dd9\u0dbb\u0db8\u0dd4\u0dab}}<br />{{lang|ta|\u0bae\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0baf\u0b95 \u0ba4\u0bc7\u0b9a\u0bbf\u0baf \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba9\u